{"title_page": "Be\u017eanija", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Be\u017eanija\n| native_name             = \u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\n| native_name_lang        = sr\n| settlement_type         = [[List of Belgrade neighbourhoods and suburbs|Urban neighbourhood]]\n| image_skyline           = Be\u017eanijskaKosa03.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Be\u017eanijska kosa\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| etymology               = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Serbia Belgrade\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within Belgrade\n| coordinates             = {{coord|44|48|22.37|N|20|22|19.61|E|display=inline, title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Subdivisions of Serbia|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|Belgrade}} \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Subdivisions of Belgrade|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[New Belgrade]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_urban_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_rural_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_metro_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_magnitude          = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_note               = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_blank1_title       = \n| area_blank2_title       = \n<!-- square kilometers -->\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_urban_km2          = \n| area_rural_km2          = \n| area_metro_km2          = \n| area_blank1_km2         = \n| area_blank2_km2         = \n<!-- hectares -->\n| area_total_ha           = \n| area_land_ha            = \n| area_water_ha           = \n| area_urban_ha           = \n| area_rural_ha           = \n| area_metro_ha           = \n| area_blank1_ha          = \n| area_blank2_ha          = \n| length_km               = \n| width_km                = \n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 38,204\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| population_demonym      = \n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal codes in Serbia|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Serbia|Area code]]\n| area_code               = +381(0)11\n| blank_name              = [[Vehicle registration plates of Serbia|Car plates]]\n| blank_info              = BG\n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Be\u017eanija''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430}}; {{IPA-sh|b\u025b\u0292\u01cenija|pron}}) is an [[List of Belgrade neighborhoods|urban neighborhood]] of [[Belgrade]], the capital of [[Serbia]]. It is located in Belgrade's municipality of [[Novi Beograd]], in the [[Syrmia]] region.\n\n== Location ==\n[[Image:Novi Beograd.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Be\u017eanija blocks]]\n[[Image:58848448bkosa1.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Be\u017eanijska Kosa]]\nBe\u017eanija is located west of the downtown Belgrade, across the [[Sava]] river, in the [[Syrmia]] region. It is situated in the central part of the Novi Beograd municipality, on the southern extension of the elongated, crescent-shaped yellow [[loess]] ridge of ''Be\u017eanijska kosa''. The ridge (or slope, as it is called in Serbian, ''kosa'') gives its name to the northern extension of Be\u017eanija, Be\u017eanijska Kosa, and stretches to the right banks of the [[Danube]] in the neighborhood of [[Zemun]]. Once a suburb of Belgrade, separated from it by the vast marshlands on the Sava's left bank, Be\u017eanija today forms one completely urbanized area with Belgrade thanks to the rapid development of [[Novi Beograd]] after [[World War II]]. Today, Be\u017eanija extends to the northeast into Be\u017eanijska kosa and the west into [[Ledine]].\n\n==Administration==\nAfter the World War II ended, Belgrade was divided into [[raion]]s and Be\u017eanija was part of the Raion X. When this division was abolished in 1952, Be\u017eanija became a municipality. In 1955 it was annexed to the municipality of New Belgrade, but remained as the separate settlement until 1971, when it became a ''local community'' (Serbian: ''mesna zajednica'' within Belgrade. In the 1990s, local community was administratively divided into Be\u017eanija and Be\u017eanijska Kosa.\n\n== Population ==\nBe\u017eanija experienced a rapid growth of population after 1948 as it was almost immediately attached to the newly constructed city-within-the city of Novi Beograd. As internal communal boundaries changed a lot since the 1970s, despite further expansion, censuses showed a reduced number of population as many border areas (entirely or partially) were detached from Be\u017eanija (Be\u017eanijska kosa, blocks 61-65, etc.). Historical population of Be\u017eanija (1921-61 as the separate settlement, 1971-81 as a local community, 2002-11 as local communities of Be\u017eanija and Be\u017eanijska kosa):\n* 1921 - 2,069\n* 1953 - 3,330\n* 1961 - 7,129\n* 1971 - 15,580\n* 1981 - 14,067\n* 2002 - 32,416<ref>{{cite book|title=Popis stanovni\u0161tva po mesnim zajednicama, Saop\u0161tenje 40/2002, page 4|date=26 July 2002|publisher=Zavod za informatiku i statistiku grada Beograda}}</ref>\n* 2011 - 38,204<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo po op\u0161tinama i mesnim zajednicama, Popis 2011|date=23 April 2015|publisher=Grad Beograd \u2013 Sektor statistike (xls file)}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBe\u017eanija is the oldest part of today's Novi Beograd, where a settlement existed from the [[neolithic]] to the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] period.\n\nThe remains belonging to the [[Scordisci]], a [[Celts|Celtic]]  tribe which founded [[Singidunum]] and [[Taurunum]], the predecessors of Belgrade and [[Zemun]], respectively, were found in Be\u017eanija.<ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Tragom Skordiska u na\u0161em gradu | trans-title = Trails of the Scordisci in our city | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Kru\u0161evski pomenik'' from 1713, which was kept in the Dobrun monastery near [[Vi\u0161egrad]], settlement of Be\u017eanija was mentioned for the first time under its present name as far as 1512, as a small village with 32 houses, populated by [[Serbs]].<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web|url= http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/221990/Bezanija-od-imperije-do-tranzicije|author=Nikola Beli\u0107|title= Be\u017eanija, od imperije do tranzicije|date=11 June 2012 |publisher=[[Politika]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> In this time, the village was under the administration of the medieval [[Kingdom of Hungary (medieval)|Kingdom of Hungary]], and was part of the [[Syrmia County]]. The inhabitants of the village crossed the Sava river and settled in Syrmia after fleeing the fall of the medieval [[Serbian Despotate]] under the hands of the [[Ottoman Empire]] (hence the name ''be\u017eanija'', \"refugee camp\" in archaic Serbian). ''Kru\u0161evski pomenik'' was later transferred to the [[National Library of Serbia]] and perished during the [[Operation Retribution (1941)|German bombing of Belgrade]] on 6 April 1941.<ref name=\"triveka\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Nikola Beli\u0107| title = Tri veka Be\u017eanije u istorijskim dokumentima| newspaper = [[Politika]] | pages = 17 | language = Serbian | date = 6 February 2013| url = }}</ref>\n\nAn old German map of the [[Syrmia]], shows a village south of Zemun called Verschania.<ref name=\"triveka\"/> In 1521, the village became part of the Ottoman Empire. From 1527 to 1530, Be\u017eanija was part of [[Radoslav \u010celnik]]'s Duchy of Syrmia, an Ottoman vassal, until its subsequent organization into the Ottoman [[Sanjak of Syrmia]]. The [[Habsburg Monarchy]] conquered it temporarily during the [[Great Turkish War]] (1689-1691), but it remained under Ottoman administration by the provisions of the [[Treaty of Karlowitz]] in 1699, until 1718. In 1718, the village became part of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] and was placed under military administration. It was part of the Habsburg [[Military Frontier]] ([[Petrovaradin]] regiment of [[Slavonian Krajina]]). During the 17th and 18th centuries, hunger and constant Turkish intrusions devastated the village, but it was constantly being repopulated by the refugees from central Serbia. In 1810, population census counted 115, mostly Serbian households. By the 1850s, Austrians colonized a large number of Germans in Be\u017eanija.<ref name=\"Politika\"/> In 1848-1849 it was part of the [[Serbian Vojvodina]], an ethnic Serb autonomous region within the Austrian Empire, but in 1849 was again placed under administration of the Military Frontier.\n\n[[Image:Belgr\u00e1d - 38-45.jpg|left|180px|thumb|Old map from 1910, showing settlements in eastern Syrmia, including Be\u017eanija]]\n\nAs the Frontier was abolished in 1881-1882, it became part of the [[Syrmia County]] within the autonomous Habsburg kingdom [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia|Croatia-Slavonia]], which was located within the Hungarian part of the Dual Monarchy of [[Austria-Hungary]]. In 1910, the largest ethnic group in the village were [[Serbs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img190.imageshack.us/img190/3899/vojvodina1910.png |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007194009/http://img190.imageshack.us/img190/3899/vojvodina1910.png |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> while other sizable ethnic groups were [[Germans]], [[Hungarians]] and [[Croats]]. After dissolution of Austria-Hungary, in autumn of 1918, Be\u017eanija became part of the newly formed [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]]. On November 24, 1918, as part of [[Syrmia]] region, the village became part of the [[Kingdom of Serbia]], and on December 1, it became part of the newly formed [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] (future [[Yugoslavia]]).\n\nFrom 1918 to 1922, the village was part of the Syrmia County and from 1922 to 1929 part of the Syrmia Oblast. Be\u017eanija became part of the wider [[Belgrade]] area for the first time in 1929 after [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] conducted by the king [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia]], who, among other things, draw a new map of Yugoslavia's administrative division creating a new administrative unit ''Uprava grada Beograda'' or ''Administration of the City of Belgrade'' which comprised [[Belgrade]], [[Zemun]] (with Be\u017eanija) and [[Pan\u010devo]]. Administrative area of the village of Be\u017eanija was quite large at the time, stretching to the [[King Alexander Bridge]], which was a dividing point between Be\u017eanija and Zemun.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:594635-Beogradske-price-Novi-Beograd-rodjen-na-Starom-sajmu|author=Zoran Nikoli\u0107|title= Beogradske pri\u010de \u2013 Novi Beograd ro\u0111en na Starom sajmu|date=9 March 2016|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernje Novosti]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> It means it encompassed of what would be 2/3 of the area of modern New Belgrade.\n\nDuring World War II, from 1941 to 1944, the village was occupied by the [[Axis Powers]] and was attached to the [[Ante Paveli\u0107|Paveli\u0107's]] [[Independent State of Croatia]]. After World War II, Be\u017eanija became part of new socialist [[SR Serbia|Serbia]] within restored [[SFRJ|Yugoslavia]]. It remained part of the Belgrade area but with its own municipality. As the construction of [[Novi Beograd]] began in 1948, municipality of Be\u017eanija was abolished an annexed to the municipality of Novi Beograd in 1955 (itself established in 1952), becoming one of its ''local communities''.\n\n== Economy ==\n\nBe\u017eanija is mostly residential area. Some very important industrial facilities are located in the areas geographically, though not administratively, parts of Be\u017eanija: IMT and FOM factories, section of the Belgrade's Waterwoks and Sewage, Minel, etc. Commercial sector is developing recently, including a green market, several gas pumps, a stadium and several shopping malls (like ''Immo Idea'').\n\nThe major [[transmission grid]]'s [[Electrical substation|substation]] for western Belgrade is located in Be\u017eanija and was heavily damaged during the [[Legitimacy of NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|NATO bombing of Serbia]] in 1999. The [[graphite bomb]]s (or ''blackout bombs'') were used. The major substation for eastern Belgrade, in [[Le\u0161tane]] was also bombed.\n\n== Features ==\n=== Cemeteries ===\n\n'''New Be\u017eanija Cemetery'''\n\nNew Be\u017eanija Cemetery (''Novo Be\u017eanijsko groblje''), west of the settlement, is Belgrade's largest cemetery, covering an area of {{convert|94|ha|abbr=on}}. It was open in 1974 and was conceived as the main cemetery for the Syrmian part of urban Belgrade (Zemun and New Belgrade). The project was designed in the Urbanism and Planning Institute Belgrade, and the main architect was Slobodanka Prekajski. Costruction of the Church of [[Thomas the Apostle]] began in 2001. It was finished and consecrated on 19 October 2003, on the Saint Thomas the Apostle day.<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0448\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430 | trans-title = Resting places originating from the end of the previous century | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Old Be\u017eanija Cemetery'''\n\nOld cemetery, much smaller than the new one, is located in the old part of the settlement.\n\n'''Pet Cemetery'''\n\nIn January 2019 it was announced that the forested area in Block 51, south of the Belgrade-Novi Sad highway, is chosen as the location of the first Belgrade's pet cemetery. The cemetery will cover an area of {{convert|1.51|ha|abbr=on}}, 70% of which will be green areas. The entire complex will be bordered with the protective green belt, {{convert|15|m|abbr=on}} wide. The complex will consist of several areas: open area (800 burial places), forested cemetery (900), columbarium and rosarium (1,100), communal cemetery (1,400) and memorial park for the animals from the [[Belgrade Zoo]]. In the best case scenario, the construction will not start before 2020.<ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Projekat za prvo groblje ku\u0107nih ljubimaca | trans-title = Project for the first pet cemetery | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 23 January 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/421041/Projekat-za-prvo-groblje-kucnih-ljubimaca}}</ref> In February 2020, city administration announced works for November 2020. The complex will also include administrative building, veterinary clinic and incinerator.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u045a\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0459\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u043d\u0435 \u0459\u0443\u0431\u0438\u043c\u0446\u0435 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 | trans-title = Construction of pet cemetery starts at the end of the year | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Dojno Polje Airport ===\n[[File:Dojno polje aerodrom.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Dojno Polje Airport in 1931]]\n\nWest of Be\u017eanija and {{convert|2|km|abbr=on}} south of Zemun, between the village and the Sava river, is the location of the old Belgrade airport which was finished in March 1927. The locality was called Dojno Polje.<ref name=kljakic>{{Citation | author = Slobodan Kljaki\u0107| title = Aeromiting nad Dojnim poljem | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 1 September 2012}}</ref> Construction of an airfield began in 1923. An initiative asked for the creation of the airline company in 1926 which was approved by the government on 23 March 1926. Then the [[initial public offering]] began but largely failed as only 10% of the planned amount was gathered. According to the existing laws, the airline company was to be closed even before it was officially formed. In order to bust the sale of the shares, pilot {{ill|Tadija Sondermajer|sr}} decided to conduct the promotional flight [[Paris]]-[[Bombay]]-Belgrade. With his colleague {{ill|Leonid Bajdak|sr}}, he started the journey on 20 April 1927 from Paris, arriving back to Belgrade after 11 days and {{convert|14.800|km|abbr=on}}, on 8 May. They were awaited as heroes by the crowd of 30,000. The sale of the shares was boosted and in three months there were sufficient funds for the company, named [[Aeroput]] and established on 17 June 1927, to purchase its first 4 airplanes.<ref>{{cite news | author =  Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Kada su svi putevi vodili u Beograd | trans-title = When all roads were leading to Belgrade | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1092 | pages = 28-29 | language = Serbian | date = 2 September 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/410658/Kada-su-svi-putevi-vodili-u-Beograd}}</ref>\n\nNew administrative building was constructed in 1931 and to celebrate the occasion, a big [[air show]] of the [[biplanes]] was held.<ref name=kljakic/> Around the airport, a workers settlement developed.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0423\u0433\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0422\u0435\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b \u0422\u043e\u0448\u0430 | trans-title = A distinguished man Todor Apostolovi\u0107 To\u0161a | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 11 October 2019}}</ref> The airport was destroyed by the [[Germans]] in 1944, and became defunct in 1962 when the new airport near the village of [[Sur\u010din]] was finished (today's [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]]).<ref name=muzej>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Zavr\u0161ni radovi na pristupnicama Mostu na Adi | newspaper = Politika | page = 17 | language = Serbian | date = 24 May 2017}}</ref> In 1960, {{convert|500|m2|abbr=on}} of the former officer's club were adapted for the first permanent location of the future military aeronautical museum. First exhibition was held in 1961 and the permanent setup was organized in 1965. It was then decided that the museum would also host civilian aircraft. Civilian wing was established and by 1966 already held some 30 planes and the expansion became necessary. Air force then swapped the former airport complex for the apartments for its members throughout massively constructed New Belgrade. It was suggested that museum should remain, with added parcel of {{convert|2.6|ha|abbr=on}} around it, but this was still not enough for all the hangars needed for the exhibitions. The idea was abandoned and the exhibition moved to Zemun in 1967 before it was decided that the [[Aeronautical Museum Belgrade]] will be built near Sur\u010din.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107  | script-title=sr: \u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0432\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 | trans-title = Aeronautical Museum | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016 works began on the construction of the access road to the [[Ada Bridge]]. During works on the new boulevard, remnants of the old airport's runway, hangars and warehouses were discovered.<ref name=muzej/> The area is today occupied by the modern commercial and business neighborhood of [[Airport City Belgrade]], named so after the old airport.\n\n=== Cultural monuments ===\nThe Old Elementary School, at 68 Vojvo\u0111anska Street, was built in 1891. It was a standard object of its kind, designed by the subdued postulates of the [[Academism]]. As the representative of the continual development of education in the 19th century, but also of the economic status and economy in general among the Serbian population of this area, it was declared a [[cultural monument]] in January 2019. It is also the oldest preserved building on the territory of the New Belgrade municipality.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Prvo moderno stambeno naselje postalo kulturno dobro | trans-title = First modern residential neighborhood declared a cultural monument | newspaper = [[Politika]] | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 31 January 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/421709/Prvo-moderno-stambeno-naselje-postalo-kulturno-dobro}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\nBe\u017eanija has many Sports facilities including tennis courts, basketball courts and the [[Stadion Be\u017eanije]], where [[FK Be\u017eanija]] play their home matches. FK Be\u017eanija was founded in 1921.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n==Sub-neighborhoods==\n[[File:Novi beograd mz.png|right|thumb|250px|Map of Local communities in Novi Beograd]]\n\n===Stara Be\u017eanija===\n'''Stara Be\u017eanija''' (Cyrillic: '''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430'''; ''Old Be\u017eanija''), as the name says, is the oldest section of Be\u017eanija, location of the original village. It had a population of 13,378 in 2002 and 8,412 in 2011.\n\nAt the roundabout on the corner of ''Sur\u010dinska'' and ''Vojvo\u0111anska'' streets, an obelisk was erected in 2012 to celebrate the 500 years of the first mention of Be\u017eanija. It is 5 meters, or 500 centimeters tall, one centimeter for each year.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n=== Be\u017eanijska Kosa ===\n[[Image:Le temple de Saint Vasilije Ostro\u0161ki \u00e0 Belgrade.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Orthodox Church of ''Saint Vasilije Ostro\u0161ki'' in Be\u017eanijska Kosa]]\n\nNortheastern extension of the Be\u017eanija, along the [[loess]] ridge, is called '''Be\u017eanijska Kosa''' (Cyrillic: '''\u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0430'''; ''slope of Be\u017eanija''). It is crescent shaped, leaning on the western border of the urban area of Novi Beograd, stretching along the ''To\u0161in bunar'' street to Zemun. Northern section of the neighborhood is crossed by the Belgrade-[[Zagreb]] highway.\n\nIn 1883 Austrian general Laudon built a trench through the loess to make way for the railway, thus creating an artificial hill, known today as Be\u017eanijska Kosa. Laudon's trench, whose remnants still can be seen but are turned into an [[informal settlement]], marked to border between the south [[Kalvarija (Zemun)|Kalvarija]] and north Be\u017eanijska Kosa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e-zemun.rs/vesti/zemun_vesti/posetilac-reporter/brdo-gardos-nije-brdo/|author=Miloje Jovanovi\u0107 Miki|title=Brdo Gardo\u0161 nije brdo|date=2 December 2010|publisher=[[Politika]]|language=Serbian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531232826/http://e-zemun.rs/vesti/zemun_vesti/posetilac-reporter/brdo-gardos-nije-brdo/|archivedate=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nModern neighborhood was built in 1987. It roughly comprises Blocks 6, 35, 49, 50 and 60. Southern section is industrialized (IMT and Minel factories) and the location of the old airport (now a new neighborhood in the process of construction, [[Airport City Belgrade]]), while the central parts are mostly residential. Northern section, along the highway, comprises stadiums of the ''Be\u017eanija'' and ''Radni\u010dki'' soccer clubs, auto-camp, hotel ''Nacional'', sports center of ''11 April'', ''Be\u017eanija'' retirement home and one of the major Belgrade hospitals, ''KBC Be\u017eanijska Kosa''. In the northeast it borders the [[Studentski Grad (Belgrade)|Studentski Grad]] while northwestern section belongs to the municipality of Zemun. The railway tunnel has been dug through the loess ridge.\n\nIt distincts itself from the rest of Novi Beograd as it has no skyscrapers, but smaller, more 'humane' buildings. It had a population of 19,036 in 2002 and 29,792 in 2011.\n\n=== Be\u017eanijski Blokovi ===\n{{main|Blokovi#Be\u017eanija Blocks }}\n\nNot considered part of the modern Be\u017eanija, but rather as a separate neighborhood of [[Blokovi]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Mala Prosvetina Enciklopedija'', Third edition (1985); Prosveta; {{ISBN|86-07-00001-2}}\n* Jovan \u0110. Markovi\u0107 (1990): ''Enciklopedijski geografski leksikon Jugoslavije''; Svjetlost-Sarajevo; {{ISBN|86-01-02651-6}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Novi Beograd}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Be\u017eanija}}\n* [http://bezanija.go-forum.net/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bezanija}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Former and proposed municipalities of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:New Belgrade]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Be\u017eanija\n| native_name             = \u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\n| native_name_lang        = sr\n| settlement_type         = [[List of Belgrade neighbourhoods and suburbs|Urban neighbourhood]]\n| image_skyline           = Be\u017eanijskaKosa03.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Be\u017eanijska kosa\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| etymology               = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Serbia Belgrade\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within Belgrade\n| coordinates             = {{coord|44|48|22.37|N|20|22|19.61|E|display=inline, title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Subdivisions of Serbia|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|Belgrade}} \n| subdivision_type2       = [[Subdivisions of Belgrade|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[New Belgrade]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_urban_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_rural_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_metro_footnotes    = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_magnitude          = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_note               = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_blank1_title       = \n| area_blank2_title       = \n<!-- square kilometers -->\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_urban_km2          = \n| area_rural_km2          = \n| area_metro_km2          = \n| area_blank1_km2         = \n| area_blank2_km2         = \n<!-- hectares -->\n| area_total_ha           = \n| area_land_ha            = \n| area_water_ha           = \n| area_urban_ha           = \n| area_rural_ha           = \n| area_metro_ha           = \n| area_blank1_ha          = \n| area_blank2_ha          = \n| length_km               = \n| width_km                = \n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 38,204\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| population_demonym      = \n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal codes in Serbia|Postal code]]\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Serbia|Area code]]\n| area_code               = +381(0)11\n| blank_name              = [[Vehicle registration plates of Serbia|Car plates]]\n| blank_info              = BG\n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Be\u017eanija''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430}}; {{IPA-sh|b\u025b\u0292\u01cenija|pron}}) is an [[List of Belgrade neighborhoods|urban neighborhood]] of [[Belgrade]], the capital of [[Serbia]]. It is located in Belgrade's municipality of [[Novi Beograd]], in the [[Syrmia]] region.\n\n== Location ==\n[[Image:Novi Beograd.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Be\u017eanija blocks]]\n[[Image:58848448bkosa1.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Be\u017eanijska Kosa]]\nBe\u017eanija is located west of the downtown Belgrade, across the [[Sava]] river, in the [[Syrmia]] region. It is situated in the central part of the Novi Beograd municipality, on the southern extension of the elongated, crescent-shaped yellow [[loess]] ridge of ''Be\u017eanijska kosa''. The ridge (or slope, as it is called in Serbian, ''kosa'') gives its name to the northern extension of Be\u017eanija, Be\u017eanijska Kosa, and stretches to the right banks of the [[Danube]] in the neighborhood of [[Zemun]]. Once a suburb of Belgrade, separated from it by the vast marshlands on the Sava's left bank, Be\u017eanija today forms one completely urbanized area with Belgrade thanks to the rapid development of [[Novi Beograd]] after [[World War II]]. Today, Be\u017eanija extends to the northeast into Be\u017eanijska kosa and the west into [[Ledine]].\n\n==Administration==\nAfter the World War II ended, Belgrade was divided into [[raion]]s and Be\u017eanija was part of the Raion X. When this division was abolished in 1952, Be\u017eanija became a municipality. In 1955 it was annexed to the municipality of New Belgrade, but remained as the separate settlement until 1971, when it became a ''local community'' (Serbian: ''mesna zajednica'' within Belgrade. In the 1990s, local community was administratively divided into Be\u017eanija and Be\u017eanijska Kosa.\n\n== Population ==\nBe\u017eanija experienced a rapid growth of population after 1948 as it was almost immediately attached to the newly constructed city-within-the city of Novi Beograd. As internal communal boundaries changed a lot since the 1970s, despite further expansion, censuses showed a reduced number of population as many border areas (entirely or partially) were detached from Be\u017eanija (Be\u017eanijska kosa, blocks 61-65, etc.). Historical population of Be\u017eanija (1921-61 as the separate settlement, 1971-81 as a local community, 2002-11 as local communities of Be\u017eanija and Be\u017eanijska kosa):\n* 1921 - 2,069\n* 1953 - 3,330\n* 1961 - 7,129\n* 1971 - 15,580\n* 1981 - 14,067\n* 2002 - 32,416<ref>{{cite book|title=Popis stanovni\u0161tva po mesnim zajednicama, Saop\u0161tenje 40/2002, page 4|date=26 July 2002|publisher=Zavod za informatiku i statistiku grada Beograda}}</ref>\n* 2011 - 38,204<ref>{{cite book|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo po op\u0161tinama i mesnim zajednicama, Popis 2011|date=23 April 2015|publisher=Grad Beograd \u2013 Sektor statistike (xls file)}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nBe\u017eanija is the oldest part of today's Novi Beograd, where a settlement existed from the [[neolithic]] to the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] period.\n\nThe remains belonging to the [[Scordisci]], a [[Celts|Celtic]]  tribe which founded [[Singidunum]] and [[Taurunum]], the predecessors of Belgrade and [[Zemun]], respectively, were found in Be\u017eanija.<ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Tragom Skordiska u na\u0161em gradu | trans-title = Trails of the Scordisci in our city | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Kru\u0161evski pomenik'' from 1713, which was kept in the Dobrun monastery near [[Vi\u0161egrad]], settlement of Be\u017eanija was mentioned for the first time under its present name as far as 1512, as a small village with 32 houses, populated by [[Serbs]].<ref name=\"Politika\">{{cite web|url= http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/221990/Bezanija-od-imperije-do-tranzicije|author=Nikola Beli\u0107|title= Be\u017eanija, od imperije do tranzicije|date=11 June 2012 |publisher=[[Politika]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> In this time, the village was under the administration of the medieval [[Kingdom of Hungary (medieval)|Kingdom of Hungary]], and was part of the [[Syrmia County]]. The inhabitants of the village crossed the Sava river and settled in Syrmia after fleeing the fall of the medieval [[Serbian Despotate]] under the hands of the [[Ottoman Empire]] (hence the name ''be\u017eanija'', \"refugee camp\" in archaic Serbian). ''Kru\u0161evski pomenik'' was later transferred to the [[National Library of Serbia]] and perished during the [[Operation Retribution (1941)|German bombing of Belgrade]] on 6 April 1941.<ref name=\"triveka\">{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Nikola Beli\u0107| title = Tri veka Be\u017eanije u istorijskim dokumentima| newspaper = [[Politika]] | pages = 17 | language = Serbian | date = 6 February 2013| url = }}</ref>\n\nAn old German map of the [[Syrmia]], shows a village south of Zemun called Verschania.<ref name=\"triveka\"/> In 1521, the village became part of the Ottoman Empire. From 1527 to 1530, Be\u017eanija was part of [[Radoslav \u010celnik]]'s Duchy of Syrmia, an Ottoman vassal, until its subsequent organization into the Ottoman [[Sanjak of Syrmia]]. The [[Habsburg Monarchy]] conquered it temporarily during the [[Great Turkish War]] (1689-1691), but it remained under Ottoman administration by the provisions of the [[Treaty of Karlowitz]] in 1699, until 1718. In 1718, the village became part of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] and was placed under military administration. It was part of the Habsburg [[Military Frontier]] ([[Petrovaradin]] regiment of [[Slavonian Krajina]]). During the 17th and 18th centuries, hunger and constant Turkish intrusions devastated the village, but it was constantly being repopulated by the refugees from central Serbia. In 1810, population census counted 115, mostly Serbian households. By the 1850s, Austrians colonized a large number of Germans in Be\u017eanija.<ref name=\"Politika\"/> In 1848-1849 it was part of the [[Serbian Vojvodina]], an ethnic Serb autonomous region within the Austrian Empire, but in 1849 was again placed under administration of the Military Frontier.\n\n[[Image:Belgr\u00e1d - 38-45.jpg|left|180px|thumb|Old map from 1910, showing settlements in eastern Syrmia, including Be\u017eanija]]\n\nAs the Frontier was abolished in 1881-1882, it became part of the [[Syrmia County]] within the autonomous Habsburg kingdom [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia|Croatia-Slavonia]], which was located within the Hungarian part of the Dual Monarchy of [[Austria-Hungary]]. In 1910, the largest ethnic group in the village were [[Serbs]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://img190.imageshack.us/img190/3899/vojvodina1910.png |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007194009/http://img190.imageshack.us/img190/3899/vojvodina1910.png |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> while other sizable ethnic groups were [[Germans]], [[Hungarians]] and [[Croats]]. After dissolution of Austria-Hungary, in autumn of 1918, Be\u017eanija became part of the newly formed [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]]. On November 24, 1918, as part of [[Syrmia]] region, the village became part of the [[Kingdom of Serbia]], and on December 1, it became part of the newly formed [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] (future [[Yugoslavia]]).\n\nFrom 1918 to 1922, the village was part of the Syrmia County and from 1922 to 1929 part of the Syrmia Oblast. Be\u017eanija became part of the wider [[Belgrade]] area for the first time in 1929 after [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] conducted by the king [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia]], who, among other things, draw a new map of Yugoslavia's administrative division creating a new administrative unit ''Uprava grada Beograda'' or ''Administration of the City of Belgrade'' which comprised [[Belgrade]], [[Zemun]] (with Be\u017eanija) and [[Pan\u010devo]]. Administrative area of the village of Be\u017eanija was quite large at the time, stretching to the [[King Alexander Bridge]], which was a dividing point between Be\u017eanija and Zemun.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:594635-Beogradske-price-Novi-Beograd-rodjen-na-Starom-sajmu|author=Zoran Nikoli\u0107|title= Beogradske pri\u010de \u2013 Novi Beograd ro\u0111en na Starom sajmu|date=9 March 2016|publisher=[[Ve\u010dernje Novosti]]|language=Serbian}}</ref> It means it encompassed of what would be 2/3 of the area of modern New Belgrade.\n\nDuring World War II, from 1941 to 1944, the village was occupied by the [[Axis Powers]] and was attached to the [[Ante Paveli\u0107|Paveli\u0107's]] [[Independent State of Croatia]]. After World War II, Be\u017eanija became part of new socialist [[SR Serbia|Serbia]] within restored [[SFRJ|Yugoslavia]]. It remained part of the Belgrade area but with its own municipality. As the construction of [[Novi Beograd]] began in 1948, municipality of Be\u017eanija was abolished an annexed to the municipality of Novi Beograd in 1955 (itself established in 1952), becoming one of its ''local communities''.\n\n== Economy ==\n\nBe\u017eanija is mostly residential area. Some very important industrial facilities are located in the areas geographically, though not administratively, parts of Be\u017eanija: IMT and FOM factories, section of the Belgrade's Waterwoks and Sewage, Minel, etc. Commercial sector is developing recently, including a green market, several gas pumps, a stadium and several shopping malls (like ''Immo Idea'').\n\nThe major [[transmission grid]]'s [[Electrical substation|substation]] for western Belgrade is located in Be\u017eanija and was heavily damaged during the [[Legitimacy of NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|NATO bombing of Serbia]] in 1999. The [[graphite bomb]]s (or ''blackout bombs'') were used. The major substation for eastern Belgrade, in [[Le\u0161tane]] was also bombed.\n\n== Features ==\n=== Cemeteries ===\n\n'''New Be\u017eanija Cemetery'''\n\nNew Be\u017eanija Cemetery (''Novo Be\u017eanijsko groblje''), west of the settlement, is Belgrade's largest cemetery, covering an area of {{convert|94|ha|abbr=on}}. It was open in 1974 and was concieved as the main cemetery for the Syrmian part of urban Belgrade (Zemun and New Belgrade). The project was designed in the Urbanism and Planning Institute Belgrade, and the main architect was Slobodanka Prekajski. Costruction of the Church of [[Thomas the Apostle]] began in 2001. It was finished and consecrated on 19 October 2003, on the Saint Thomas the Apostle day.<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0448\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0448\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430 | trans-title = Resting places originating from the end of the previous century | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Old Be\u017eanija Cemetery'''\n\nOld cemetery, much smaller than the new one, is located in the old part of the settlement.\n\n'''Pet Cemetery'''\n\nIn January 2019 it was announced that the forested area in Block 51, south of the Belgrade-Novi Sad highway, is chosen as the location of the first Belgrade's pet cemetery. The cemetery will cover an area of {{convert|1.51|ha|abbr=on}}, 70% of which will be green areas. The entire complex will be bordered with the protective green belt, {{convert|15|m|abbr=on}} wide. The complex will consist of several areas: open area (800 burial places), forested cemetery (900), columbarium and rosarium (1,100), communal cemetery (1,400) and memorial park for the animals from the [[Belgrade Zoo]]. In the best case scenario, the construction will not start before 2020.<ref>{{cite news | author = Ana Vukovi\u0107 | title = Projekat za prvo groblje ku\u0107nih ljubimaca | trans-title = Project for the first pet cemetery | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 23 January 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/421041/Projekat-za-prvo-groblje-kucnih-ljubimaca}}</ref> In February 2020, city administration announced works for November 2020. The complex will also include administrative building, veterinary clinic and incinerator.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u045a\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0459\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u043d\u0435 \u0459\u0443\u0431\u0438\u043c\u0446\u0435 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 | trans-title = Construction of pet cemetery starts at the end of the year | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Dojno Polje Airport ===\n[[File:Dojno polje aerodrom.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Dojno Polje Airport in 1931]]\n\nWest of Be\u017eanija and {{convert|2|km|abbr=on}} south of Zemun, between the village and the Sava river, is the location of the old Belgrade airport which was finished in March 1927. The locality was called Dojno Polje.<ref name=kljakic>{{Citation | author = Slobodan Kljaki\u0107| title = Aeromiting nad Dojnim poljem | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 1 September 2012}}</ref> Construction of an airfield began in 1923. An initiative asked for the creation of the airline company in 1926 which was approved by the government on 23 March 1926. Then the [[initial public offering]] began but largely failed as only 10% of the planned amount was gathered. According to the existing laws, the airline company was to be closed even before it was officially formed. In order to bust the sale of the shares, pilot {{ill|Tadija Sondermajer|sr}} decided to conduct the promotional flight [[Paris]]-[[Bombay]]-Belgrade. With his colleague {{ill|Leonid Bajdak|sr}}, he started the journey on 20 April 1927 from Paris, arriving back to Belgrade after 11 days and {{convert|14.800|km|abbr=on}}, on 8 May. They were awaited as heroes by the crowd of 30,000. The sale of the shares was boosted and in three months there were sufficient funds for the company, named [[Aeroput]] and established on 17 June 1927, to purchase its first 4 airplanes.<ref>{{cite news | author =  Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Kada su svi putevi vodili u Beograd | trans-title = When all roads were leading to Belgrade | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1092 | pages = 28-29 | language = Serbian | date = 2 September 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/410658/Kada-su-svi-putevi-vodili-u-Beograd}}</ref>\n\nNew administrative building was constructed in 1931 and to celebrate the occasion, a big [[air show]] of the [[biplanes]] was held.<ref name=kljakic/> Around the airport, a workers settlement developed.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0423\u0433\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0422\u0435\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b \u0422\u043e\u0448\u0430 | trans-title = A distinguished man Todor Apostolovi\u0107 To\u0161a | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 11 October 2019}}</ref> The airport was destroyed by the [[Germans]] in 1944, and became defunct in 1962 when the new airport near the village of [[Sur\u010din]] was finished (today's [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]]).<ref name=muzej>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Zavr\u0161ni radovi na pristupnicama Mostu na Adi | newspaper = Politika | page = 17 | language = Serbian | date = 24 May 2017}}</ref> In 1960, {{convert|500|m2|abbr=on}} of the former officer's club were adapted for the first permanent location of the future military aeronautical museum. First exhibition was held in 1961 and the permanent setup was organized in 1965. It was then decided that the museum would also host civilian aircraft. Civilian wing was established and by 1966 already held some 30 planes and the expansion became necessary. Air force then swapped the former airport complex for the apartments for its members throughout massively constructed New Belgrade. It was suggested that museum should remain, with added parcel of {{convert|2.6|ha|abbr=on}} around it, but this was still not enough for all the hangars needed for the exhibitions. The idea was abandoned and the exhibition moved to Zemun in 1967 before it was decided that the [[Aeronautical Museum Belgrade]] will be built near Sur\u010din.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107  | script-title=sr: \u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0432\u0430\u0437\u0434\u0443\u0445\u043e\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 | trans-title = Aeronautical Museum | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016 works began on the construction of the access road to the [[Ada Bridge]]. During works on the new boulevard, remnants of the old airport's runway, hangars and warehouses were discovered.<ref name=muzej/> The area is today occupied by the modern commercial and business neighborhood of [[Airport City Belgrade]], named so after the old airport.\n\n=== Cultural monuments ===\nThe Old Elementary School, at 68 Vojvo\u0111anska Street, was built in 1891. It was a standard object of its kind, designed by the subdued postulates of the [[Academism]]. As the representative of the continual development of education in the 19th century, but also of the economic status and economy in general among the Serbian population of this area, it was declared a [[cultural monument]] in January 2019. It is also the oldest preserved building on the territory of the New Belgrade municipality.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Prvo moderno stambeno naselje postalo kulturno dobro | trans-title = First modern residential neighborhood declared a cultural monument | newspaper = [[Politika]] | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 31 January 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/421709/Prvo-moderno-stambeno-naselje-postalo-kulturno-dobro}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\nBe\u017eanija has many Sports facilities including tennis courts, basketball courts and the [[Stadion Be\u017eanije]], where [[FK Be\u017eanija]] play their home matches. FK Be\u017eanija was founded in 1921.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n==Sub-neighborhoods==\n[[File:Novi beograd mz.png|right|thumb|250px|Map of Local communities in Novi Beograd]]\n\n===Stara Be\u017eanija===\n'''Stara Be\u017eanija''' (Cyrillic: '''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430'''; ''Old Be\u017eanija''), as the name says, is the oldest section of Be\u017eanija, location of the original village. It had a population of 13,378 in 2002 and 8,412 in 2011.\n\nAt the roundabout on the corner of ''Sur\u010dinska'' and ''Vojvo\u0111anska'' streets, an obelisk was erected in 2012 to celebrate the 500 years of the first mention of Be\u017eanija. It is 5 meters, or 500 centimeters tall, one centimeter for each year.<ref name=\"Politika\"/>\n\n=== Be\u017eanijska Kosa ===\n[[Image:Le temple de Saint Vasilije Ostro\u0161ki \u00e0 Belgrade.jpg|right|240px|thumb|Orthodox Church of ''Saint Vasilije Ostro\u0161ki'' in Be\u017eanijska Kosa]]\n\nNortheastern extension of the Be\u017eanija, along the [[loess]] ridge, is called '''Be\u017eanijska Kosa''' (Cyrillic: '''\u0411\u0435\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0430'''; ''slope of Be\u017eanija''). It is crescent shaped, leaning on the western border of the urban area of Novi Beograd, stretching along the ''To\u0161in bunar'' street to Zemun. Northern section of the neighborhood is crossed by the Belgrade-[[Zagreb]] highway.\n\nIn 1883 Austrian general Laudon built a trench through the loess to make way for the railway, thus creating an artificial hill, known today as Be\u017eanijska Kosa. Laudon's trench, whose remnants still can be seen but are turned into an [[informal settlement]], marked to border between the south [[Kalvarija (Zemun)|Kalvarija]] and north Be\u017eanijska Kosa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e-zemun.rs/vesti/zemun_vesti/posetilac-reporter/brdo-gardos-nije-brdo/|author=Miloje Jovanovi\u0107 Miki|title=Brdo Gardo\u0161 nije brdo|date=2 December 2010|publisher=[[Politika]]|language=Serbian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531232826/http://e-zemun.rs/vesti/zemun_vesti/posetilac-reporter/brdo-gardos-nije-brdo/|archivedate=31 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nModern neighborhood was built in 1987. It roughly comprises Blocks 6, 35, 49, 50 and 60. Southern section is industrialized (IMT and Minel factories) and the location of the old airport (now a new neighborhood in the process of construction, [[Airport City Belgrade]]), while the central parts are mostly residential. Northern section, along the highway, comprises stadiums of the ''Be\u017eanija'' and ''Radni\u010dki'' soccer clubs, auto-camp, hotel ''Nacional'', sports center of ''11 April'', ''Be\u017eanija'' retirement home and one of the major Belgrade hospitals, ''KBC Be\u017eanijska Kosa''. In the northeast it borders the [[Studentski Grad (Belgrade)|Studentski Grad]] while northwestern section belongs to the municipality of Zemun. The railway tunnel has been dug through the loess ridge.\n\nIt distincts itself from the rest of Novi Beograd as it has no skyscrapers, but smaller, more 'humane' buildings. It had a population of 19,036 in 2002 and 29,792 in 2011.\n\n=== Be\u017eanijski Blokovi ===\n{{main|Blokovi#Be\u017eanija Blocks }}\n\nNot considered part of the modern Be\u017eanija, but rather as a separate neighborhood of [[Blokovi]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Mala Prosvetina Enciklopedija'', Third edition (1985); Prosveta; {{ISBN|86-07-00001-2}}\n* Jovan \u0110. Markovi\u0107 (1990): ''Enciklopedijski geografski leksikon Jugoslavije''; Svjetlost-Sarajevo; {{ISBN|86-01-02651-6}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Novi Beograd}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Be\u017eanija}}\n* [http://bezanija.go-forum.net/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bezanija}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Former and proposed municipalities of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:New Belgrade]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Be%C5%BEanija"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sarawak}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| caption         = \n| alt             = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| date            = \n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 254\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 14\n| deaths          = 10\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://covid19.sarawak.com.my/}}\n| width           = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the state of [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]] in March 2020. As of 4 April 2020, there are 254 confirmed cases.\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 13 March 2020, Sarawak has recorded its first Covid-19 cases, with three patients tested positive for the virus in [[Kuching]]. The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee in a statement said 2 cases were from the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March, the third cases was a family member of case 2.<ref name=\"first three COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sarawak039s-first-three-covid-19-cases-traced-to-sri-petaling-mosque|title=Sarawak's first three Covid-19 cases traced to Sri Petaling Mosque|last=Ling|first=Sharon|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040222/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sarawak039s-first-three-covid-19-cases-traced-to-sri-petaling-mosque|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee reported 6 new cases were recorded, bringing the total of positive cases to nine. The chairman, Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said 2 new cases were recorded in [[Limbang]] while 4 new cases were recorded in [[Kuching]]. All new cases were from the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque.<ref name=\"six new COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148753/six-new-covid-19-cases-in-sarawak/|title=Six new Covid-19 cases in Sarawak|work=The Star|via=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040530/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148753/six-new-covid-19-cases-in-sarawak/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, Sarawak recorded 11 new positive cases of Covid-19, bringing the total to 20 cases.  Among the 11 new cases, one of them was [[Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] after tested positive for the virus in [[Sibu Hospital]]. Sarawak DAP chairman [[Chong Chieng Jen]] directed all party members and lawmakers who had close contact with the Sarikei MP in the last 14 days to self-quarantine for two weeks.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/15/covid-19-sarawak-dap-orders-lawmakers-members-who-had-close-contact-with-sa/1846812|title=Covid-19: Sarawak DAP orders lawmakers, members who had close contact with Sarikei MP to self-quarantine|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041034/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/15/covid-19-sarawak-dap-orders-lawmakers-members-who-had-close-contact-with-sa/1846812|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, State Minister of Local Government and Housing Datuk Sri Dr [[Sim Kui Hian]] said 14 new Covid-19 cases were recorded making the total cases to 34. Among the new cases, 6 are from [[Kuching]], 4 from [[Betong Division|Betong]], 2 from [[Sarikei]] and one each from [[Serian Division|Serian]] and [[Simunjan District|Simunjan]].<ref name=\"State Health Department monitoring\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/state-health-dept-is-monitoring-sarikei-mps-condition-says-sarawak-cm/1847102|title=State Health Dept is monitoring Sarikei MP's condition, says Sarawak CM|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041808/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/state-health-dept-is-monitoring-sarikei-mps-condition-says-sarawak-cm/1847102|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the 2 cases from Sarikei was Malaysian national hammer thrower Jackie Wong Siew Cheer as he was tested positive for the virus in [[Sibu Hospital]] after visiting his father, [[Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] who was also tested positive for the virus on 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/16/hammer-thrower-jackie-wong-first-national-athlete-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|title=Hammer thrower Jackie Wong first national athlete tested positive for Covid-19|work=Bernama|via=Borneo Post|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041959/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/16/hammer-thrower-jackie-wong-first-national-athlete-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Sarawak records nation first Covid-19 death involving  Patient 18. The victim died at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. Sarawak also recorded 11 new positive cases bringing the total to 45. Out of 11 new cases, 6 are from [[Kuching]], 3 from [[Limbang]] and one each from [[Betong Division|Betong]] and [[Lawas]].<ref name=\"first fatality in Sarawak\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/17/pastor-from-sarawak-is-first-covid-19-fatality-in-malaysia|title=Pastor from Sarawak is first Covid-19 fatality in Malaysia|last=Ling|first=Sharon|work=The Star|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318042229/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/17/pastor-from-sarawak-is-first-covid-19-fatality-in-malaysia|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee confirms 5 new positive cases for Covid-19 with 2 patients currently treated in [[Sarawak General Hospital]], 2 in [[Sibu Hospital]]  and one in [[:ms:Hospital Bintulu|Bintulu Hospital]].<ref name=\"five new COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/covid-19-five-new-confirmed-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-at-50/|title=Covid-19: Five new confirmed cases recorded in Sarawak, total at 50|last=C|first=Irene|work=Borneo Post|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319065215/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/covid-19-five-new-confirmed-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-at-50/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Sarawak government has enforced measures that align with the federal government [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] from 18 March to 31 March 2020.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/infografik-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-sarawak-1838900|title=[INFOGRAFIK] Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Sarawak|date=18 March 2020|language=Malay|trans-title=[INFOGRAPHIC] Sarawak Movement Control Order|accessdate=18 March 2020|format=video|medium=0:45|via=Astro Awani}}</ref> On 19 March, Sarawak recorded one new positive case in [[Kuching]] making the total to 51.<ref name=\"one positive cases recorded today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-only-one-positive-case-recorded-in-sarawak-today-total-at-51/|title=Covid-19: Only one positive case recorded in Sarawak today, total at 51|work=Borneo Post|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123106/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-only-one-positive-case-recorded-in-sarawak-today-total-at-51/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Sarawak recorded 7 new Covid-19 cases bringing the total to 58 cases. Sarawak Deputy Chief Minister Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said all 7 cases were reported in [[Kuching]] and are currently treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 4 of the cases are among the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March. 2 cases were local church cluster while one are still under investigation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/covid-19-7-new-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-brings-total-number-to-58|title=Sarawak recorded 7 new positive Covid-19 cases|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=20 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320130822/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/covid-19-7-new-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-brings-total-number-to-58|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> State Disaster Management Committee has identified 4 possible Covid-19 clusters other then the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque namely Emmanuel Baptist Church Kuching cluster, Good News Fellowship Church cluster, [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] fundraising dinner cluster and Josephian Day cluster at SMK St Joseph Kuching. Sarawak Multimedia Authority (SMA) has come up with a tracking device to be used by those under home quarantine which will be attached to their wrists and a digital mapping method would also be used to identify hotspots of Covid-19 infections to prevent its spread.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/20/sarawak-identifies-four-possible-covid-19-clusters/1848412|title=Sarawak identifies four possible Covid-19 clusters|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|date=20 March 2020|website=The Malay Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131554/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/20/sarawak-identifies-four-possible-covid-19-clusters/1848412|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Sarawak's National Safety Council branch had identified seven hotspots related to the pandemic, which are [[Kuching]], [[Serian, Sarawak|Serian]], [[Betong, Sarawak|Betong]], [[Sarikei]], [[Bintulu]], [[Miri]] and [[Limbang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sarawak-kenal-pasti-tujuh-lokasi-panas-covid-19-234625|title=Sarawak kenal pasti tujuh lokasi panas COVID-19|trans-title=Sarawak identified seven COVID-19 hotspots|first=Rudi|last=Affendi Khalik|website=Astro Awani|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Another two deaths in the state involving a 79-year-old woman and her 40-year-old daughter were reported within the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|title=Sarawak independently reports two more Covid-19 deaths|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321093731/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sarawak Disaster Management Committee reported 10 new positive cases in the state (inclusive both that died on the same day) making the total to 68 cases.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/covid-19-sarawak-reports-two-more-deaths-10-new-cases|title=Sarawak reports 10 new cases|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=21 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321115808/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/covid-19-sarawak-reports-two-more-deaths-10-new-cases|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee recorded 8 new positive Covid-19 cases bringing the total to 76.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/covid-19-sarawak-records-8-new-positive-cases-total-at-76/|title=Sarawak records 8 new positive cases|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=22 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322131020/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/covid-19-sarawak-records-8-new-positive-cases-total-at-76/|archive-date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, Sarawak announced 2 new Covid-19 deaths involving a 49-year-old man from [[Kuching]] and a 51-year-old woman from [[Limbang]]. Sarawak also recorded 6 new positive Covid-19 cases, all from [[Kuching]] bringing the total cases to 82.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths-bringing-toll-to-5/|title=Sarawak records two more Covid-19 deaths|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200323122554/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths-bringing-toll-to-5/|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced RM1.15 billion special aid package to reduce Covid-19 impact on the state.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-announces-rm115bil-aid-to-mitigate-covid-19-impact|title=Sarawak announces RM1.15bil aid to mitigate Covid-19 impact|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=23 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200323123440/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-announces-rm115bil-aid-to-mitigate-covid-19-impact|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Sarawak recorded 5 new positive Covid-19 cases with 2 each from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and [[Sibu Hospital]] and one in [[Miri Hospital]]. According to Sarawak DIsaster Management Committee clusters statistic, one of the new cases in [[Sarawak General Hospital]] is from the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] while the other one are connected to the church cluster. The 2 new cases in [[Sibu Hospital]] are also from the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/24/covid-19-sarawak-records-5-new-positive-cases-total-at-87/|title=Sarawak records 5 new positive cases|last=Kong|first=Joash|date=24 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325041334/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/24/covid-19-sarawak-records-5-new-positive-cases-total-at-87/|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, 4 new positive cases were recorded, bringing the total to 91.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/4-new-positive-cases-in-sarawak/|title=4 new positive cases in Sarawak|date=26 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325172458/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/4-new-positive-cases-in-sarawak/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Another 4 new positive cases were detected the following day.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/sarawak-detects-4-new-covid-19-positive-cases-today-total-stands-at-95/|title=Sarawak detects 4 new Covid-19 positive cases today, total stands at 95|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=26 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326160011/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/sarawak-detects-4-new-covid-19-positive-cases-today-total-stands-at-95/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said 15 new cases recorded where all of the cases are treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 7 of them have been traced to having close contacts with three family members who succumbed to the virus due to an imported case from Italy, 4 from the Good News Fellowship church in Kuching and the other four to the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/27/sarawak-records-15-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-110/|title=Sarawak records 15 new Covid-19 cases|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328053722/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/27/sarawak-records-15-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-110/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Sarawak recorded 8 new positive cases with 7 cases are treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and one at [[Sibu Hospital]]. Sarawak also recorded 9 positive patients recovered and has been discharged from hospital.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/28/covid-19-8-new-positive-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-stands-at-118/|title=8 new positive cases recorded in Sarawak|last=Edgar|first=Nigel|date=28 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328095637/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/28/covid-19-8-new-positive-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-stands-at-118/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On 29 March, 11 new cases recorded in [[Sarawak General Hospital]] bringing the total to 129.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/29/sarawak-records-11-new-positive-covid-19-cases-total-now-129/|title=Sarawak records 11 new positive Covid-19 cases|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=29 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329133112/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/29/sarawak-records-11-new-positive-covid-19-cases-total-now-129/|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Sarawak recorded 2 Covid-19 deaths, one from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and another one from [[Miri Hospital]]. 6 new cases were recorded in the state making the total to 135 where 3 cases recorded in [[Sarawak General Hospital]], 2 in [[Miri Hospital]] and one in [[Sibu Hospital]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/30/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths|title=Sarawak records two more Covid-19 deaths|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=30 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331032603/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/30/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March, Sarawak recorded nation's first foreign Covid-19 death involving Indonesian lecturer in [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 21 new cases recorded in the state and 5 more patients recovered and discharged from hospital.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/31/covid-19-swak-records-21-new-cases-1-death-on-march-31|title=Sarawak records 21 new cases and 1 death .|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=31 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131920/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/31/covid-19-swak-records-21-new-cases-1-death-on-march-31|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, Sarawak recorded 32 new positive cases with one from [[Samarahan Division|Samarahan]] and the rest from [[Kuching Division|Kuching]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/01/covid-19-32-positive-cases-reported-in-sarawak-total-at-188/|title=32 new positive cases reported in Sarawak|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=1 April 2020|website=Borneo Post|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said 23 new cases and 1 death were recorded bringing the total cases to 211.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-s039wak-records-one-death-on-april-2|title=Sarawak records one death on April 2|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=3 April 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403131509/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-s039wak-records-one-death-on-april-2|archive-date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Another 28 new cases recorded in the state the following day.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/03/covid-19-28-new-positive-cases-detected-in-sarawak-total-at-239/|title=28 new positive cases detected in Sarawak|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=3 April 2020|website=Borneo Post|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403122403/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/03/covid-19-28-new-positive-cases-detected-in-sarawak-total-at-239/|archive-date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, Sarawak recorded 1 more Covid-19 death bringing the death toll to 10 deaths. The state also recorded 15 new positive cases with 13 from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and one each from [[Sibu Hospital]] and [[Miri Hospital]].<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/04/sarawak-covid-19-death-toll-rises-to-10-15-new-positive-cases-recorded/1853549|title=Sarawak Covid-19 death toll rises to 10, 15 new positive cases recorded|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|date=4 April 2020|website=Malay Mail|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405004235/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/04/sarawak-covid-19-death-toll-rises-to-10-15-new-positive-cases-recorded/1853549|archive-date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\nCases by Divisions\n!Date\n![[Betong Division|Betong]]\n![[Bintulu Division|Bintulu]]\n![[Kuching Division|Kuching]]\n![[Limbang Division|Limbang]]\n![[Miri Division|Miri]]\n![[Mukah Division|Mukah]]\n![[Samarahan Division|Samarahan]]\n![[Sarikei Division|Sarikei]]\n![[Serian Division|Serian]]\n![[Sibu]]\n![[Sri Aman Division|Sri Aman]]\n!Total\n!Cumulative\n!Source\n|-\n|13/3\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n|1\n!\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n|2\n! rowspan=\"8\" |\n! rowspan=\"18\" |\n|'''3'''\n|'''3'''\n|<ref name=\"first three COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|14/3\n|3\n|2\n|1\n|'''6'''\n|'''9'''\n|<ref name=\"six new COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|15/3\n|1\n|1\n|\n|8\n|1\n|\n|'''11'''\n|'''20'''\n|<ref name=\":7\" />\n|-\n|16/3\n|4\n|\n|6\n|\n|\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|'''14'''\n|'''34'''\n|<ref name=\"State Health Department monitoring\"/>\n|-\n|17/3\n|1\n|\n|6\n|4\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''11'''\n|'''45'''\n|<ref name=\"first fatality in Sarawak\"/>\n|-\n|18/3\n|\n|1\n|2\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|1\n|\n|'''5'''\n|'''50'''\n|<ref name=\"five new COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|19/3\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''1'''\n|'''51'''\n|<ref name=\"one positive cases recorded today\"/>\n|-\n|20/3\n|\n|\n|7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''7'''\n|'''58'''\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|21/3\n|2\n|2\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|2\n|\n|1\n|'''10'''\n|'''68'''\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|22/3\n|\n|\n|7\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''8'''\n|'''76'''\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|23/3\n|\n|\n|6\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''6'''\n|'''82'''\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|24/3\n|\n|\n|2\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|2\n|'''5'''\n|'''87'''\n|<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|25/3\n|\n|1\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''4'''\n|'''91'''\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|26/3\n|\n|\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|'''4'''\n|'''95'''\n|<ref name=\":8\" />\n|-\n|27/3\n|\n|\n|14\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|'''15'''\n|'''110'''\n|<ref name=\":10\" />\n|-\n|28/3\n|1\n|\n|5\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|1\n|\n|'''8'''\n|'''118'''\n|<ref name=\":11\" />\n|-\n|29/3\n|\n|\n|6\n|\n|\n|\n|5\n|\n|\n|\n|'''11'''\n|'''129'''\n|<ref name=\":12\" />\n|-\n|30/3\n|1\n|\n|3\n|\n|2\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''6'''\n|'''135'''\n|<ref name=\":13\" />\n|-\n|31/3\n|\n|\n|16\n|\n|\n|\n|2\n|\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|'''21'''\n|'''156'''\n|<ref name=\":14\" />\n|-\n|1/4\n|\n|\n|31\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''32'''\n|'''188'''\n|<ref name=\":15\" />\n|-\n|2/4\n|2\n|\n|13\n|\n|\n|\n|8\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''23'''\n|'''211'''\n|<ref name=\":16\" />\n|-\n|3/4\n|\n|\n|19\n|1\n|2\n|\n|5\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|'''28'''\n|'''239'''\n|<ref name=\":17\" />\n|-\n|4/4\n|1\n|\n|13\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''15'''\n|'''254'''\n|<ref name=\":18\" />\n|-\n!Total\n|'''12'''\n|'''5'''\n|'''171'''\n|'''8'''\n|'''14'''\n|'''2'''\n|'''24'''\n|'''6'''\n|'''7'''\n|'''4'''\n|'''1'''\n|'''254'''\n!Cumulative\n!Source\n|}<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Statistics of Quarantined Hospitals<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SarawakDisasterInfo/|title=Sarawak Disaster Information|via=Facebook|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n!Hospital\n!Confirmed\n!Recovered\n!Death\n!Active\n|-\n|[[Sarawak General Hospital]]{{Efn|including positive Covid-19 cases and death from Borneo Medical Centre.|name=|group=lower-alpha}}\n|203\n|9\n|8\n|187\n|-\n|[[Sibu Hospital]]\n|24\n|3\n|0\n|21\n|-\n|[[:ms:Hospital Bintulu|Bintulu Hospital]]\n|5\n|0\n|0\n|5\n|-\n|[[Miri Hospital]]\n|22\n|2\n|2\n|18\n|-\n!Total\n|254\n|14\n|10\n|230\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |{{Reflist|1|liststyle=decimal|group=lower-alpha|refs=1}}\n|}\n\n== Preventative measures by state government ==\n\n=== State Movement Control Order align with 18 March\u201314 April nationwide Movement Control Order ===\n{{main|2020 Malaysia movement control order}}\nOn 16 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced several control measures to prevent Covid-19 infections from further escalating in the state. Among the several control measures imposed are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575169/covid-19-sarawak-schools-shut-or-have-holidays-extended|title=Covid-19: Sarawak schools to shut, or have holidays extended|last=Povera|first=Adib|date=16 March 2020|work=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041602/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575169/covid-19-sarawak-schools-shut-or-have-holidays-extended|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n# All schools in Sarawak have been advised to extend their holidays for another week until 29 March 2020.\n# All [[preschool]]s, [[kindergarten]]s and tahfiz schools state-wide are instructed to close for two weeks effective 17 March 2020.\n# Higher education institutions, both government and private, are to defer their new academic session by two weeks, effective 17 March 2020.\n# All state government official functions involving more than 50 people will be cancelled or postponed until further notice.\n# All visitors (foreign and domestic) coming into Sarawak and returning Sarawakians will be issued with a 14-day Stay Home Notice (SHN). This includes Sarawak residents, and long-term and short-term pass holders. This will take effect on 18 March 2020.\n# The relevant agencies will monitor the Stay Home Notice holders through random visits, phone calls and modern technology applications.\n# Everyone is advised to practice the highest standard of personal hygiene and to strictly practice social distancing.\n\nOn 18 March, The Sarawak government has advised all government offices (except essential services), business premises (except business premises dealing with daily essentials) and factories (except those in [[Samalaju]], Hi-Tech Samajaya, and plywood factories which are allowed to operate with minimum staffs) will be closed. Restaurant and eateries are allowed to open and operate for takeaways only (drinking/dining in the premises are prohibited). People are allowed leave houses, but for purchasing essential items, important goods and services only.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn 19 March, Sarawak Government and Housing Ministry orders all food premises and stalls to close by 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) daily throughtout the [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/sarawak-orders-all-eateries-to-close-at-8pm-during-mco/|title=Sarawak orders all eateries to close at 8pm during Movement Control Order|last=How Pim|first=Lim|date=19 March 2020|work=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123346/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/sarawak-orders-all-eateries-to-close-at-8pm-during-mco/|archive-date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, All fast food outlets (including drive thru services) and supermarkets will stop operation by 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) but convenience store and petrol station will operate as usual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/sarawak-to-puts-digital-cuff-on-quarantine-cases/|title=Sarawak to put digital cuffs on quarantine cases|last=Lumandan|first=Larissa|date=20 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131955/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/sarawak-to-puts-digital-cuff-on-quarantine-cases/|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said all [[hypermarket]]s, [[supermarket]]s, markets, coffee shops, private clinics, [[restaurant]]s, 24-hour convenience stores and petrol stations in the state are to cease operations from 7PM to 7AM ([[UTC+8]]) starting from 24 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/essential-stores-and-services-statewide-to-close-7pm-onwards-starting-march-24/|title=Essential stores and services statewide to close 7pm onwards starting March 24|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=22 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322131512/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/essential-stores-and-services-statewide-to-close-7pm-onwards-starting-march-24/|archive-date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, State Disaster Management Committee in a meeting agreed to allow pet shops and veterinary clinics to operate business throughout Movement Control Order (MCO) period from 7AM to 7PM with immediate effect.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nOn 26 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] has issued directives to ensures there is continuous supply of food:<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n# Farmers, breeders and fishermen can continue with their daily routines.\n# Farmers, breeders and fishermen are allowed to sell their products at places agreed by the local council from 7AM - 7PM ([[UTC+8]]).\n\nOn 29 March, Sarawak has imposed a ban on inter-district travel, and those with valid reasons for travelling must obtain permits from the district office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/sarawak-bans-travel-between-districts-after-162-mco-arrests/|title=Sarawak bans travel between districts|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329133855/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/sarawak-bans-travel-between-districts-after-162-mco-arrests/|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Overseas and domestic travels alert and quarantine arrangements ===\nThe following warnings and quarantine arrangements for inbound and outbound travel to the state are for both foreigners and Malaysian including Sarawakian:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Alert level\n!Country\n!Date of enforcement\n!Status\n!Note\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|China}}\n|1 February 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Mainland China]], the state government has refused entry to all Chinese nationals and foreigners who have travelled to China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1810809|title=Sarawak bars visitors with recent travel history to China|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|agency=Bernama}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{nowrap|{{flagu|South Korea}}}}\n|28 February 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], the state government has refused entry to all South Korean nationals and foreigners who have travelled to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|title=Foreigners who have been to S. Korea in last fortnight banned|date=1 March 2020|work=The Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063044/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|Denmark}}\n|{{nowrap|14 March 2020}}\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark|Denmark]] and its recent [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark#Lockdown|lockdown]], the Malaysian government announced a travel ban to the country.<ref name=\"Denmark travel ban\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|title=Travel ban on Denmark from Saturday|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|date=12 March 2020|work=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314040937/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|Iran}}<br />{{flagu|Italy}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |4 March 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], the state government has refused entry to all Iranian and Italian nationals and foreigners who have travelled to one of the countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|title=S'wak bans Italian and Iranian travellers, after China and South Korea|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=4 March 2020|work=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063646/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Strongly advised\n|{{flagu|Brunei}}<br />{{flagu|Indonesia}}<br />{{flagu|Japan}}<br />{{flagu|Singapore}}\n|{{green|In force}}\n|Visitors and Malaysian that visited [[Singapore]], [[Brunei]], [[Indonesia]] and [[Japan]] must adhere to precautionary guidelines issued by the state Health Department at all entry points into Sarawak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/05/sarawak-extends-entry-ban-on-four-countries|title=Sarawak extends entry ban on four countries|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=5 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063836/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/05/sarawak-extends-entry-ban-on-four-countries|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\nOn 4 April, all Sarawakians that returns from overseas must undergo a 14-days quarantine upon arrivals at quarantine centres arranged by state goverment for observation and supervision for Covid-19 infection.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n=== Prevention for immigrations ===\nOn 29 January, All visitors entering Sarawak are required to declare the status of their health as part of efforts to contain Covid-19 infection in the state where they are required to fill in the health declaration form provided at all entry points in the state, including border checkpoints and onboard aircraft. The regulation also applies to visitors driving vehicles who arrive via [[ferry]] from [[Labuan]] and flight passengers from Mulu [[National park|National Park]] as there are direct flights from [[Kota Kinabalu]] to the location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/146744/sarawak-enforces-health-status-declaration-at-entry-points/|title=Sarawak enforces health status declaration at entry points|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=Daily Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325035738/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/146744/sarawak-enforces-health-status-declaration-at-entry-points/|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] said all border posts in Sarawak will be closed with immediate effect to prevent further spread of Covid-19 except Customs, Immigration and Quarantine Complexes (CIQs) between [[Brunei\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Brunei]] ([[Sungai Tujoh|Sungai Tujuh]], Tedungan, Pandaruan and Mengkalap) would be open from 6AM to 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) while CIQs between [[Indonesia\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Kalimantan]] ([[Tebedu]], [[Biawak]] and [[Lubok Antu District|Lubok Antu]]) would be open between 9AM and 3PM ([[UTC+8]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/all-border-posts-in-sarawak-to-be-closed-except-those-with-brunei-kalimantan/|title=Border posts in Sarawak to be closed except those with Brunei, Kalimantan|last=Lumandan|first=Larissa|date=21 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321120026/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/all-border-posts-in-sarawak-to-be-closed-except-those-with-brunei-kalimantan/|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee chairman Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said border between [[Brunei\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Brunei]] will be open from 6AM to 6PM ([[UTC+8]]) effective 28 March 2020.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Bans on mass gathering events ===\nOn 15 March, immediately after the spikes of the cases which related to the religious gathering at [[Sri Petaling]] Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March, State Disaster Management Committee in a statement said all government and public gatherings involving the participation of more than 50 people in Sarawak must be postponed to a later date.<ref name=\"gathering more than 50 people postponed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574815/sarawak-orders-gatherings-involving-more-50-postponed|title=Sarawak orders gatherings involving more than 50 postponed|date=15 March 2020|work=Bernama|via=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040805/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574815/sarawak-orders-gatherings-involving-more-50-postponed|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Funds and aid on the pandemic ==\nOn 23 March, Toh Puan Datuk Patinggi [[:ms:Ragad Waleed Alkurdi|Raghad Kurdi Taib]], the wife of [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Sarawak|Yang di-Pertua Negeri Sarawak]] Tun Pehin Sri [[Abdul Taib Mahmud]], has donated RM60,000 to the [[Sarawak General Hospital]] in the battle against the Covid-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/23/raghad-donates-rm60000-to-sarawak-general-hospital/|title=Raghad donates RM60,000 to Sarawak General Hospital|last=Chua|first=Sam|date=23 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324013906/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/23/raghad-donates-rm60000-to-sarawak-general-hospital/|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\nSarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced RM1.15 billion Sarawakku Sayang special aid package including 16 measures to reduce Covid-19 impact on the state:<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n# Domestic, Commercial and Industrial consumers given a discount of five per cent to 25 per cent on monthly electricity bill for April until September 2020.\n# Domestic, Commercial and Industrial consumers given discount of 10 per cent to 25 per cent on their monthly water bill for April until September 2020.\n# Sarawakian from the low income category, the B40 group will be provided a monthly cash pay-out of RM250 for 6-months.\n# Special monthly [[incentive]]s for frontline personnel involved in Covid-19.\n# Discount of 50 per cent for rental of market and stalls covering a period of six months up to September 2020.\n# Waiver of permits and licenses fees for traders, hawkers, [[night market]] traders, Tamu and [[bazaar]] [[Ramadan|Ramadhan]] operations.\n# Discount of 25 per cent on annual assessment rate above RM400 threshold given to residential, commercial, industrial and special purpose holdings for the year 2020.\n# [[Deferment]] of loan repayment for Skim Pinjaman Industri Kecil dan Sederhana (SPIKS).\n# Additional RM20 million for SMEs to expand their business and to sustain their businesses.\n# Discount of 30 per cent for payments of land rents to all land uses for the year 2020.\n# Deferment of land premiums.\n# Sarawak Government have placed an order of two million pieces of face masks to be distributed free to Sarawakians through the State Disaster Management Committee.\n# Providing dedicated support to physicians and practices on the front lines of testing, diagnosing, and treating patients at risk of Covid-19.\n# Providing dedicated supports of food supplies to physicians and practitioners on the front lines of testing, diagnosing, and treating patients at risk of Covid-19.\n# Discount of 50 per cent for rental of HDC Houses rental scheme covering a period of six (6) months up to September 2020.\n\nOn 25 March, Leading medical/healthcare beds, [[peripheral]]s and accessories provider LKL International Bhd (LKL International) will supply RM6.6 million worth of [[Personal protective equipment|Personal Protective Equipment]] (PPE) to the Sarawak state government for onward distribution to [[public hospital]]s under the Sarawak State Health Department and the frontline healthcare personnel in their battle against Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/lkl-international-to-supply-rm6-6-million-worth-of-ppe-to-sarawak-govt/|title=LKL International to supply RM6.6 million worth of PPE to Sarawak govt|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326023613/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/lkl-international-to-supply-rm6-6-million-worth-of-ppe-to-sarawak-govt/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, Sarawak has received 20,000 face masks from China's [[Fujian|Fujian province]]. Provincial government of Fujian donated these face masks as a friendship agreement with Sarawak, through the Chinese consulate. Provincial government of Fujian also provided assistance through a video conferencing session between their medical specialists and those in Sarawak. The [[Shandong]] provincial government, which is another friendship state with Sarawak, will send more masks through the consulate in the coming week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|title=Sarawak receives 20,000 face masks from China's Fujian province|last=|first=|date=26 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327020739/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Sarawak]], Tun Pehin Sri [[Abdul Taib Mahmud]] donates various equipment and essential items, worth RM120,500 to the [[Sarawak General Hospital]] (SGH) today, to help in the treatment of COVID-19 patients. The Governor also donated 700 food packs and mineral water to Sarawak Police Operations Room, to be distributed to police, Armed Forces a well as People's Volunteer Corps (RELA) personnel who are carrying out roadblocks during Movement Control Order (MCO).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/03/30/covid-19-sarawak-yang-di-pertua-negeri-donates-rm120500-to-hus/|title=Sarawak Yang di-Pertua Negeri donates RM120,500 to HUS|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=The Malaysian Reserve|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331033913/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/03/30/covid-19-sarawak-yang-di-pertua-negeri-donates-rm120500-to-hus/|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] has announced an additional RM16.4 million to the RM1.15 billion Sarawakku Sayang special aid package in food assistance for the poor in rural and urban areas to mitigate the impact of the Covid-19 pandemic in the state. The aid was for those who were homeless and who had lost their jobs to reduce the their burden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149847/s-wak-gives-additional-rm16-4m-in-food-aid-for-the-poor/|title=S'wak gives additional RM16.4m in food aid for the poor|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=Daily Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331034312/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149847/s-wak-gives-additional-rm16-4m-in-food-aid-for-the-poor/|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sabah]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Malaysia|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://jknsarawak.moh.gov.my/v2/bm/ Sarawak State Health Department website] \u2013 Further details on the coronavirus outbreak in Sarawak\n* {{facebook|SarawakDisasterInfo}} \u2013 Current updates on the coronavirus outbreak in Sarawak\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia by state|Sarawak]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sarawak}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Sarawak\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| caption         = \n| alt             = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Sarawak]], Malaysia\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| date            = \n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 254\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 14\n| deaths          = 10\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://covid19.sarawak.com.my/}}\n| width           = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the state of [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]] in March 2020. As of 4 April 2020, there are 254 confirmed cases.\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 13 March 2020, Sarawak has recorded its first Covid-19 cases, with three patients tested positive for the virus in [[Kuching]]. The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee in a statement said 2 cases were from the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March, the third cases was a family member of case 2.<ref name=\"first three COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sarawak039s-first-three-covid-19-cases-traced-to-sri-petaling-mosque|title=Sarawak's first three Covid-19 cases traced to Sri Petaling Mosque|last=Ling|first=Sharon|work=The Star|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040222/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/13/sarawak039s-first-three-covid-19-cases-traced-to-sri-petaling-mosque|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee reported 6 new cases were recorded, bringing the total of positive cases to nine. The chairman, Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said 2 new cases were recorded in [[Limbang]] while 4 new cases were recorded in [[Kuching]]. All new cases were from the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque.<ref name=\"six new COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148753/six-new-covid-19-cases-in-sarawak/|title=Six new Covid-19 cases in Sarawak|work=The Star|via=Daily Express|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040530/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/148753/six-new-covid-19-cases-in-sarawak/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, Sarawak recorded 11 new positive cases of Covid-19, bringing the total to 20 cases.  Among the 11 new cases, one of them was [[Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] after tested positive for the virus in [[Sibu Hospital]]. Sarawak DAP chairman [[Chong Chieng Jen]] directed all party members and lawmakers who had close contact with the Sarikei MP in the last 14 days to self-quarantine for two weeks.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/15/covid-19-sarawak-dap-orders-lawmakers-members-who-had-close-contact-with-sa/1846812|title=Covid-19: Sarawak DAP orders lawmakers, members who had close contact with Sarikei MP to self-quarantine|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=15 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041034/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/15/covid-19-sarawak-dap-orders-lawmakers-members-who-had-close-contact-with-sa/1846812|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, State Minister of Local Government and Housing Datuk Sri Dr [[Sim Kui Hian]] said 14 new Covid-19 cases were recorded making the total cases to 34. Among the new cases, 6 are from [[Kuching]], 4 from [[Betong Division|Betong]], 2 from [[Sarikei]] and one each from [[Serian Division|Serian]] and [[Simunjan District|Simunjan]].<ref name=\"State Health Department monitoring\">{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/state-health-dept-is-monitoring-sarikei-mps-condition-says-sarawak-cm/1847102|title=State Health Dept is monitoring Sarikei MP's condition, says Sarawak CM|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041808/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/16/state-health-dept-is-monitoring-sarikei-mps-condition-says-sarawak-cm/1847102|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the 2 cases from Sarikei was Malaysian national hammer thrower Jackie Wong Siew Cheer as he was tested positive for the virus in [[Sibu Hospital]] after visiting his father, [[Sarikei]] MP [[Wong Ling Biu]] who was also tested positive for the virus on 15 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/16/hammer-thrower-jackie-wong-first-national-athlete-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|title=Hammer thrower Jackie Wong first national athlete tested positive for Covid-19|work=Bernama|via=Borneo Post|date=16 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041959/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/16/hammer-thrower-jackie-wong-first-national-athlete-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Sarawak records nation first Covid-19 death involving  Patient 18. The victim died at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. Sarawak also recorded 11 new positive cases bringing the total to 45. Out of 11 new cases, 6 are from [[Kuching]], 3 from [[Limbang]] and one each from [[Betong Division|Betong]] and [[Lawas]].<ref name=\"first fatality in Sarawak\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/17/pastor-from-sarawak-is-first-covid-19-fatality-in-malaysia|title=Pastor from Sarawak is first Covid-19 fatality in Malaysia|last=Ling|first=Sharon|work=The Star|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318042229/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/17/pastor-from-sarawak-is-first-covid-19-fatality-in-malaysia|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee confirms 5 new positive cases for Covid-19 with 2 patients currently treated in [[Sarawak General Hospital]], 2 in [[Sibu Hospital]]  and one in [[:ms:Hospital Bintulu|Bintulu Hospital]].<ref name=\"five new COVID-19 cases\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/covid-19-five-new-confirmed-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-at-50/|title=Covid-19: Five new confirmed cases recorded in Sarawak, total at 50|last=C|first=Irene|work=Borneo Post|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319065215/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/18/covid-19-five-new-confirmed-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-at-50/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Sarawak government has enforced measures that align with the federal government [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] from 18 March to 31 March 2020.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite AV media|url=http://www.astroawani.com/video-malaysia/infografik-perintah-kawalan-pergerakan-sarawak-1838900|title=[INFOGRAFIK] Perintah Kawalan Pergerakan Sarawak|date=18 March 2020|language=Malay|trans-title=[INFOGRAPHIC] Sarawak Movement Control Order|accessdate=18 March 2020|format=video|medium=0:45|via=Astro Awani}}</ref> On 19 March, Sarawak recorded one new positive case in [[Kuching]] making the total to 51.<ref name=\"one positive cases recorded today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-only-one-positive-case-recorded-in-sarawak-today-total-at-51/|title=Covid-19: Only one positive case recorded in Sarawak today, total at 51|work=Borneo Post|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123106/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/covid-19-only-one-positive-case-recorded-in-sarawak-today-total-at-51/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Sarawak recorded 7 new Covid-19 cases bringing the total to 58 cases. Sarawak Deputy Chief Minister Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said all 7 cases were reported in [[Kuching]] and are currently treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 4 of the cases are among the cluster who attended a religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March. 2 cases were local church cluster while one are still under investigation.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/covid-19-7-new-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-brings-total-number-to-58|title=Sarawak recorded 7 new positive Covid-19 cases|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=20 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320130822/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/20/covid-19-7-new-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-brings-total-number-to-58|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> State Disaster Management Committee has identified 4 possible Covid-19 clusters other then the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque namely Emmanuel Baptist Church Kuching cluster, Good News Fellowship Church cluster, [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] fundraising dinner cluster and Josephian Day cluster at SMK St Joseph Kuching. Sarawak Multimedia Authority (SMA) has come up with a tracking device to be used by those under home quarantine which will be attached to their wrists and a digital mapping method would also be used to identify hotspots of Covid-19 infections to prevent its spread.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/20/sarawak-identifies-four-possible-covid-19-clusters/1848412|title=Sarawak identifies four possible Covid-19 clusters|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|date=20 March 2020|website=The Malay Mail|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131554/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/20/sarawak-identifies-four-possible-covid-19-clusters/1848412|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Sarawak's National Safety Council branch had identified seven hotspots related to the pandemic, which are [[Kuching]], [[Serian, Sarawak|Serian]], [[Betong, Sarawak|Betong]], [[Sarikei]], [[Bintulu]], [[Miri]] and [[Limbang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astroawani.com/berita-malaysia/sarawak-kenal-pasti-tujuh-lokasi-panas-covid-19-234625|title=Sarawak kenal pasti tujuh lokasi panas COVID-19|trans-title=Sarawak identified seven COVID-19 hotspots|first=Rudi|last=Affendi Khalik|website=Astro Awani|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Another two deaths in the state involving a 79-year-old woman and her 40-year-old daughter were reported within the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|title=Sarawak independently reports two more Covid-19 deaths|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|work=The Malay Mail|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321093731/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/21/sarawak-independently-reports-two-more-covid-19-deaths/1848758|archive-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Sarawak Disaster Management Committee reported 10 new positive cases in the state (inclusive both that died on the same day) making the total to 68 cases.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/covid-19-sarawak-reports-two-more-deaths-10-new-cases|title=Sarawak reports 10 new cases|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=21 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321115808/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/21/covid-19-sarawak-reports-two-more-deaths-10-new-cases|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee recorded 8 new positive Covid-19 cases bringing the total to 76.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/covid-19-sarawak-records-8-new-positive-cases-total-at-76/|title=Sarawak records 8 new positive cases|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=22 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322131020/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/covid-19-sarawak-records-8-new-positive-cases-total-at-76/|archive-date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, Sarawak announced 2 new Covid-19 deaths involving a 49-year-old man from [[Kuching]] and a 51-year-old woman from [[Limbang]]. Sarawak also recorded 6 new positive Covid-19 cases, all from [[Kuching]] bringing the total cases to 82.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths-bringing-toll-to-5/|title=Sarawak records two more Covid-19 deaths|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200323122554/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths-bringing-toll-to-5/|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced RM1.15 billion special aid package to reduce Covid-19 impact on the state.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-announces-rm115bil-aid-to-mitigate-covid-19-impact|title=Sarawak announces RM1.15bil aid to mitigate Covid-19 impact|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=23 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200323123440/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/23/sarawak-announces-rm115bil-aid-to-mitigate-covid-19-impact|archive-date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Sarawak recorded 5 new positive Covid-19 cases with 2 each from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and [[Sibu Hospital]] and one in [[Miri Hospital]]. According to Sarawak DIsaster Management Committee clusters statistic, one of the new cases in [[Sarawak General Hospital]] is from the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] while the other one are connected to the church cluster. The 2 new cases in [[Sibu Hospital]] are also from the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/24/covid-19-sarawak-records-5-new-positive-cases-total-at-87/|title=Sarawak records 5 new positive cases|last=Kong|first=Joash|date=24 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325041334/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/24/covid-19-sarawak-records-5-new-positive-cases-total-at-87/|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, 4 new positive cases were recorded, bringing the total to 91.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/4-new-positive-cases-in-sarawak/|title=4 new positive cases in Sarawak|date=26 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325172458/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/4-new-positive-cases-in-sarawak/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Another 4 new positive cases were detected the following day.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/sarawak-detects-4-new-covid-19-positive-cases-today-total-stands-at-95/|title=Sarawak detects 4 new Covid-19 positive cases today, total stands at 95|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=26 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326160011/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/sarawak-detects-4-new-covid-19-positive-cases-today-total-stands-at-95/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said 15 new cases recorded where all of the cases are treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 7 of them have been traced to having close contacts with three family members who succumbed to the virus due to an imported case from Italy, 4 from the Good News Fellowship church in Kuching and the other four to the religious gathering at Sri Petaling Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/27/sarawak-records-15-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-110/|title=Sarawak records 15 new Covid-19 cases|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328053722/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/27/sarawak-records-15-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-110/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Sarawak recorded 8 new positive cases with 7 cases are treated at [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and one at [[Sibu Hospital]]. Sarawak also recorded 9 positive patients recovered and has been discharged from hospital.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/28/covid-19-8-new-positive-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-stands-at-118/|title=8 new positive cases recorded in Sarawak|last=Edgar|first=Nigel|date=28 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328095637/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/28/covid-19-8-new-positive-cases-recorded-in-sarawak-total-stands-at-118/|archive-date=28 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> On 29 March, 11 new cases recorded in [[Sarawak General Hospital]] bringing the total to 129.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/29/sarawak-records-11-new-positive-covid-19-cases-total-now-129/|title=Sarawak records 11 new positive Covid-19 cases|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=29 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329133112/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/29/sarawak-records-11-new-positive-covid-19-cases-total-now-129/|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Sarawak recorded 2 Covid-19 deaths, one from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and another one from [[Miri Hospital]]. 6 new cases were recorded in the state making the total to 135 where 3 cases recorded in [[Sarawak General Hospital]], 2 in [[Miri Hospital]] and one in [[Sibu Hospital]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/30/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths|title=Sarawak records two more Covid-19 deaths|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=30 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331032603/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/30/sarawak-records-two-more-covid-19-deaths|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March, Sarawak recorded nation's first foreign Covid-19 death involving Indonesian lecturer in [[Sarawak General Hospital]]. 21 new cases recorded in the state and 5 more patients recovered and discharged from hospital.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/31/covid-19-swak-records-21-new-cases-1-death-on-march-31|title=Sarawak records 21 new cases and 1 death .|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=31 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131920/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/31/covid-19-swak-records-21-new-cases-1-death-on-march-31|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April, Sarawak recorded 32 new positive cases with one from [[Samarahan Division|Samarahan]] and the rest from [[Kuching Division|Kuching]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/01/covid-19-32-positive-cases-reported-in-sarawak-total-at-188/|title=32 new positive cases reported in Sarawak|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=1 April 2020|website=Borneo Post|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said 23 new cases and 1 death were recorded bringing the total cases to 211.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-s039wak-records-one-death-on-april-2|title=Sarawak records one death on April 2|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=3 April 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403131509/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/02/covid-19-s039wak-records-one-death-on-april-2|archive-date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> Another 28 new cases recorded in the state the following day.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/03/covid-19-28-new-positive-cases-detected-in-sarawak-total-at-239/|title=28 new positive cases detected in Sarawak|last=Aubrey|first=Samuel|date=3 April 2020|website=Borneo Post|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403122403/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/04/03/covid-19-28-new-positive-cases-detected-in-sarawak-total-at-239/|archive-date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, Sarawak recorded 1 more Covid-19 death bringing the death toll to 10 deaths. The state also recorded 15 new positive cases with 13 from [[Sarawak General Hospital]] and one each from [[Sibu Hospital]] and [[Miri Hospital]].<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/04/sarawak-covid-19-death-toll-rises-to-10-15-new-positive-cases-recorded/1853549|title=Sarawak Covid-19 death toll rises to 10, 15 new positive cases recorded|last=Tawie|first=Sulok|date=4 April 2020|website=Malay Mail|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405004235/https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/04/04/sarawak-covid-19-death-toll-rises-to-10-15-new-positive-cases-recorded/1853549|archive-date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\nCases by Divisions\n!Date\n![[Betong Division|Betong]]\n![[Bintulu Division|Bintulu]]\n![[Kuching Division|Kuching]]\n![[Limbang Division|Limbang]]\n![[Miri Division|Miri]]\n![[Mukah Division|Mukah]]\n![[Samarahan Division|Samarahan]]\n![[Sarikei Division|Sarikei]]\n![[Serian Division|Serian]]\n![[Sibu]]\n![[Sri Aman Division|Sri Aman]]\n!Total\n!Cumulative\n!Source\n|-\n|13/3\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n|1\n!\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n|2\n! rowspan=\"8\" |\n! rowspan=\"18\" |\n|'''3'''\n|'''3'''\n|<ref name=\"first three COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|14/3\n|3\n|2\n|1\n|'''6'''\n|'''9'''\n|<ref name=\"six new COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|15/3\n|1\n|1\n|\n|8\n|1\n|\n|'''11'''\n|'''20'''\n|<ref name=\":7\" />\n|-\n|16/3\n|4\n|\n|6\n|\n|\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|'''14'''\n|'''34'''\n|<ref name=\"State Health Department monitoring\"/>\n|-\n|17/3\n|1\n|\n|6\n|4\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''11'''\n|'''45'''\n|<ref name=\"first fatality in Sarawak\"/>\n|-\n|18/3\n|\n|1\n|2\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|1\n|\n|'''5'''\n|'''50'''\n|<ref name=\"five new COVID-19 cases\"/>\n|-\n|19/3\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''1'''\n|'''51'''\n|<ref name=\"one positive cases recorded today\"/>\n|-\n|20/3\n|\n|\n|7\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''7'''\n|'''58'''\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|21/3\n|2\n|2\n|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|