0\n|5\n|-\n|[[Miri Hospital]]\n|22\n|2\n|2\n|18\n|-\n!Total\n|254\n|14\n|10\n|230\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |{{Reflist|1|liststyle=decimal|group=lower-alpha|refs=1}}\n|}\n\n== Preventative measures by state government ==\n\n=== State Movement Control Order align with 18 March\u201314 April nationwide Movement Control Order ===\n{{main|2020 Malaysia movement control order}}\nOn 16 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced several control measures to prevent Covid-19 infections from further escalating in the state. Among the several control measures imposed are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575169/covid-19-sarawak-schools-shut-or-have-holidays-extended|title=Covid-19: Sarawak schools to shut, or have holidays extended|last=Povera|first=Adib|date=16 March 2020|work=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041602/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/575169/covid-19-sarawak-schools-shut-or-have-holidays-extended|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n# All schools in Sarawak have been advised to extend their holidays for another week until 29 March 2020.\n# All [[preschool]]s, [[kindergarten]]s and tahfiz schools state-wide are instructed to close for two weeks effective 17 March 2020.\n# Higher education institutions, both government and private, are to defer their new academic session by two weeks, effective 17 March 2020.\n# All state government official functions involving more than 50 people will be cancelled or postponed until further notice.\n# All visitors (foreign and domestic) coming into Sarawak and returning Sarawakians will be issued with a 14-day Stay Home Notice (SHN). This includes Sarawak residents, and long-term and short-term pass holders. This will take effect on 18 March 2020.\n# The relevant agencies will monitor the Stay Home Notice holders through random visits, phone calls and modern technology applications.\n# Everyone is advised to practice the highest standard of personal hygiene and to strictly practice social distancing.\n\nOn 18 March, The Sarawak government has advised all government offices (except essential services), business premises (except business premises dealing with daily essentials) and factories (except those in [[Samalaju]], Hi-Tech Samajaya, and plywood factories which are allowed to operate with minimum staffs) will be closed. Restaurant and eateries are allowed to open and operate for takeaways only (drinking/dining in the premises are prohibited). People are allowed leave houses, but for purchasing essential items, important goods and services only.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn 19 March, Sarawak Government and Housing Ministry orders all food premises and stalls to close by 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) daily throughtout the [[2020 Malaysia movement control order|movement control order]] period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/sarawak-orders-all-eateries-to-close-at-8pm-during-mco/|title=Sarawak orders all eateries to close at 8pm during Movement Control Order|last=How Pim|first=Lim|date=19 March 2020|work=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123346/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/19/sarawak-orders-all-eateries-to-close-at-8pm-during-mco/|archive-date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, All fast food outlets (including drive thru services) and supermarkets will stop operation by 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) but convenience store and petrol station will operate as usual.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/sarawak-to-puts-digital-cuff-on-quarantine-cases/|title=Sarawak to put digital cuffs on quarantine cases|last=Lumandan|first=Larissa|date=20 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131955/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/20/sarawak-to-puts-digital-cuff-on-quarantine-cases/|archive-date=20 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, The Sarawak Disaster Management Committee said all [[hypermarket]]s, [[supermarket]]s, markets, coffee shops, private clinics, [[restaurant]]s, 24-hour convenience stores and petrol stations in the state are to cease operations from 7PM to 7AM ([[UTC+8]]) starting from 24 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/essential-stores-and-services-statewide-to-close-7pm-onwards-starting-march-24/|title=Essential stores and services statewide to close 7pm onwards starting March 24|last=Ten|first=Marilyn|date=22 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200322131512/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/22/essential-stores-and-services-statewide-to-close-7pm-onwards-starting-march-24/|archive-date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, State Disaster Management Committee in a meeting agreed to allow pet shops and veterinary clinics to operate business throughout Movement Control Order (MCO) period from 7AM to 7PM with immediate effect.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nOn 26 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] has issued directives to ensures there is continuous supply of food:<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n# Farmers, breeders and fishermen can continue with their daily routines.\n# Farmers, breeders and fishermen are allowed to sell their products at places agreed by the local council from 7AM - 7PM ([[UTC+8]]).\n\nOn 29 March, Sarawak has imposed a ban on inter-district travel, and those with valid reasons for travelling must obtain permits from the district office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/sarawak-bans-travel-between-districts-after-162-mco-arrests/|title=Sarawak bans travel between districts|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329133855/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/29/sarawak-bans-travel-between-districts-after-162-mco-arrests/|archive-date=29 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Overseas and domestic travels alert and quarantine arrangements ===\nThe following warnings and quarantine arrangements for inbound and outbound travel to the state are for both foreigners and Malaysian including Sarawakian:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Alert level\n!Country\n!Date of enforcement\n!Status\n!Note\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|China}}\n|1 February 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|Mainland China]], the state government has refused entry to all Chinese nationals and foreigners who have travelled to China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1810809|title=Sarawak bars visitors with recent travel history to China|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|agency=Bernama}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{nowrap|{{flagu|South Korea}}}}\n|28 February 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], the state government has refused entry to all South Korean nationals and foreigners who have travelled to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|title=Foreigners who have been to S. Korea in last fortnight banned|date=1 March 2020|work=The Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063044/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/01/foreigners-who-have-been-to-s-korea-in-last-fortnight-banned/|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|Denmark}}\n|{{nowrap|14 March 2020}}\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark|Denmark]] and its recent [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Denmark#March lockdown|lockdown]], the Malaysian government announced a travel ban to the country.<ref name=\"Denmark travel ban\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|title=Travel ban on Denmark from Saturday|last=Pei Ying|first=Teoh|date=12 March 2020|work=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314040937/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574096/travel-ban-denmark-saturday|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prohibit\n|{{flagu|Iran}}<br />{{flagu|Italy}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |4 March 2020\n|{{green|In force}}\n|In response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]], the state government has refused entry to all Iranian and Italian nationals and foreigners who have travelled to one of the countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|title=S'wak bans Italian and Iranian travellers, after China and South Korea|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=4 March 2020|work=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063646/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/04/s039wak-bans-italian-and-iranian-travellers-after-china-and-south-korea|archive-date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Strongly advised\n|{{flagu|Brunei}}<br />{{flagu|Indonesia}}<br />{{flagu|Japan}}<br />{{flagu|Singapore}}\n|{{green|In force}}\n|Visitors and Malaysian that visited [[Singapore]], [[Brunei]], [[Indonesia]] and [[Japan]] must adhere to precautionary guidelines issued by the state Health Department at all entry points into Sarawak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/05/sarawak-extends-entry-ban-on-four-countries|title=Sarawak extends entry ban on four countries|last=Ling|first=Sharon|date=5 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314063836/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/05/sarawak-extends-entry-ban-on-four-countries|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\nOn 4 April, all Sarawakians that returns from overseas must undergo a 14-days quarantine upon arrivals at quarantine centres arranged by state goverment for observation and supervision for Covid-19 infection.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n=== Prevention for immigrations ===\nOn 29 January, All visitors entering Sarawak are required to declare the status of their health as part of efforts to contain Covid-19 infection in the state where they are required to fill in the health declaration form provided at all entry points in the state, including border checkpoints and onboard aircraft. The regulation also applies to visitors driving vehicles who arrive via [[ferry]] from [[Labuan]] and flight passengers from Mulu [[National park|National Park]] as there are direct flights from [[Kota Kinabalu]] to the location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/146744/sarawak-enforces-health-status-declaration-at-entry-points/|title=Sarawak enforces health status declaration at entry points|last=|first=|date=30 January 2020|website=Daily Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325035738/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/146744/sarawak-enforces-health-status-declaration-at-entry-points/|archive-date=25 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] said all border posts in Sarawak will be closed with immediate effect to prevent further spread of Covid-19 except Customs, Immigration and Quarantine Complexes (CIQs) between [[Brunei\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Brunei]] ([[Sungai Tujoh|Sungai Tujuh]], Tedungan, Pandaruan and Mengkalap) would be open from 6AM to 8PM ([[UTC+8]]) while CIQs between [[Indonesia\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Kalimantan]] ([[Tebedu]], [[Biawak]] and [[Lubok Antu District|Lubok Antu]]) would be open between 9AM and 3PM ([[UTC+8]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/all-border-posts-in-sarawak-to-be-closed-except-those-with-brunei-kalimantan/|title=Border posts in Sarawak to be closed except those with Brunei, Kalimantan|last=Lumandan|first=Larissa|date=21 March 2020|website=Free Malaysia Today|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321120026/https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2020/03/21/all-border-posts-in-sarawak-to-be-closed-except-those-with-brunei-kalimantan/|archive-date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Sarawak Disaster Management Committee chairman Datuk Amar [[Douglas Uggah Embas|Douglas Uggah]] said border between [[Brunei\u2013Malaysia border|Sarawak and Brunei]] will be open from 6AM to 6PM ([[UTC+8]]) effective 28 March 2020.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Bans on mass gathering events ===\nOn 15 March, immediately after the spikes of the cases which related to the religious gathering at [[Sri Petaling]] Mosque in [[Kuala Lumpur]] on 28 February to 1 March, State Disaster Management Committee in a statement said all government and public gatherings involving the participation of more than 50 people in Sarawak must be postponed to a later date.<ref name=\"gathering more than 50 people postponed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574815/sarawak-orders-gatherings-involving-more-50-postponed|title=Sarawak orders gatherings involving more than 50 postponed|date=15 March 2020|work=Bernama|via=New Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318040805/https://www.nst.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/574815/sarawak-orders-gatherings-involving-more-50-postponed|archive-date=18 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Funds and aid on the pandemic ==\nOn 23 March, Toh Puan Datuk Patinggi [[:ms:Ragad Waleed Alkurdi|Raghad Kurdi Taib]], the wife of [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Sarawak|Yang di-Pertua Negeri Sarawak]] Tun Pehin Sri [[Abdul Taib Mahmud]], has donated RM60,000 to the [[Sarawak General Hospital]] in the battle against the Covid-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/23/raghad-donates-rm60000-to-sarawak-general-hospital/|title=Raghad donates RM60,000 to Sarawak General Hospital|last=Chua|first=Sam|date=23 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324013906/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/23/raghad-donates-rm60000-to-sarawak-general-hospital/|archive-date=24 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\nSarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] announced RM1.15 billion Sarawakku Sayang special aid package including 16 measures to reduce Covid-19 impact on the state:<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n# Domestic, Commercial and Industrial consumers given a discount of five per cent to 25 per cent on monthly electricity bill for April until September 2020.\n# Domestic, Commercial and Industrial consumers given discount of 10 per cent to 25 per cent on their monthly water bill for April until September 2020.\n# Sarawakian from the low income category, the B40 group will be provided a monthly cash pay-out of RM250 for 6-months.\n# Special monthly [[incentive]]s for frontline personnel involved in Covid-19.\n# Discount of 50 per cent for rental of market and stalls covering a period of six months up to September 2020.\n# Waiver of permits and licenses fees for traders, hawkers, [[night market]] traders, Tamu and [[bazaar]] [[Ramadan|Ramadhan]] operations.\n# Discount of 25 per cent on annual assessment rate above RM400 threshold given to residential, commercial, industrial and special purpose holdings for the year 2020.\n# [[Deferment]] of loan repayment for Skim Pinjaman Industri Kecil dan Sederhana (SPIKS).\n# Additional RM20 million for SMEs to expand their business and to sustain their businesses.\n# Discount of 30 per cent for payments of land rents to all land uses for the year 2020.\n# Deferment of land premiums.\n# Sarawak Government have placed an order of two million pieces of face masks to be distributed free to Sarawakians through the State Disaster Management Committee.\n# Providing dedicated support to physicians and practices on the front lines of testing, diagnosing, and treating patients at risk of Covid-19.\n# Providing dedicated supports of food supplies to physicians and practitioners on the front lines of testing, diagnosing, and treating patients at risk of Covid-19.\n# Discount of 50 per cent for rental of HDC Houses rental scheme covering a period of six (6) months up to September 2020.\n\nOn 25 March, Leading medical/healthcare beds, [[peripheral]]s and accessories provider LKL International Bhd (LKL International) will supply RM6.6 million worth of [[Personal protective equipment|Personal Protective Equipment]] (PPE) to the Sarawak state government for onward distribution to [[public hospital]]s under the Sarawak State Health Department and the frontline healthcare personnel in their battle against Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/lkl-international-to-supply-rm6-6-million-worth-of-ppe-to-sarawak-govt/|title=LKL International to supply RM6.6 million worth of PPE to Sarawak govt|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Borneo Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326023613/https://www.theborneopost.com/2020/03/26/lkl-international-to-supply-rm6-6-million-worth-of-ppe-to-sarawak-govt/|archive-date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, Sarawak has received 20,000 face masks from China's [[Fujian|Fujian province]]. Provincial government of Fujian donated these face masks as a friendship agreement with Sarawak, through the Chinese consulate. Provincial government of Fujian also provided assistance through a video conferencing session between their medical specialists and those in Sarawak. The [[Shandong]] provincial government, which is another friendship state with Sarawak, will send more masks through the consulate in the coming week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|title=Sarawak receives 20,000 face masks from China's Fujian province|last=|first=|date=26 March 2020|website=The Star|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327020739/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/26/covid-19-sarawak-receives-20000-face-masks-from-china039s-fujian-province|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, [[Yang di-Pertua Negeri of Sarawak]], Tun Pehin Sri [[Abdul Taib Mahmud]] donates various equipment and essential items, worth RM120,500 to the [[Sarawak General Hospital]] (SGH) today, to help in the treatment of COVID-19 patients. The Governor also donated 700 food packs and mineral water to Sarawak Police Operations Room, to be distributed to police, Armed Forces a well as People's Volunteer Corps (RELA) personnel who are carrying out roadblocks during Movement Control Order (MCO).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/03/30/covid-19-sarawak-yang-di-pertua-negeri-donates-rm120500-to-hus/|title=Sarawak Yang di-Pertua Negeri donates RM120,500 to HUS|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=The Malaysian Reserve|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331033913/https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/03/30/covid-19-sarawak-yang-di-pertua-negeri-donates-rm120500-to-hus/|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Sarawak Chief Minister Datuk Patinggi [[Abang Abdul Rahman Johari Abang Openg|Abang Johari Tun Openg]] has announced an additional RM16.4 million to the RM1.15 billion Sarawakku Sayang special aid package in food assistance for the poor in rural and urban areas to mitigate the impact of the Covid-19 pandemic in the state. The aid was for those who were homeless and who had lost their jobs to reduce the their burden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149847/s-wak-gives-additional-rm16-4m-in-food-aid-for-the-poor/|title=S'wak gives additional RM16.4m in food aid for the poor|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=Daily Express|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331034312/http://www.dailyexpress.com.my/news/149847/s-wak-gives-additional-rm16-4m-in-food-aid-for-the-poor/|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sabah]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Malaysia|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://jknsarawak.moh.gov.my/v2/bm/ Sarawak State Health Department website] \u2013 Further details on the coronavirus outbreak in Sarawak\n* {{facebook|SarawakDisasterInfo}} \u2013 Current updates on the coronavirus outbreak in Sarawak\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:History of Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Malaysia by state|Sarawak]]\n", "name_user": "Night Lantern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverseas and domestic travels alert and quarantine arrangements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Sarawak"}
{"title_page": "Belmont, Harrow", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Belmont, Sutton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place|\n|country =    England\n|static_image_name=Harrow, Belmont Circle, Belmont - geograph.org.uk - 68461.jpg\n|map_type =   Greater London\n|region= London\n|population=  11,343\n|population_ref = (2011 Census. Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13688792&c=Belmont&d=14&e=62&g=6327589&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1477247415637&enc=1|title=Harrow Ward population 2011|accessdate=23 October 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name=             Belmont\n|london_borough=           Harrow\n|constituency_westminster=      [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n|post_town=          HARROW\n|post_town1=         STANMORE\n|postcode_district =       HA3\n|postcode_district1=       HA7\n|postcode_area=            HA\n|postcode_area1=           HA\n|dial_code=      020\n|os_grid_reference=     TQ165905\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.60130|-0.31929|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n'''Belmont''' is an area of the [[London Borough of Harrow]].\n\nThe area is named after the mound constructed in the early 18th century by Henry James Brydges, [[Earl of Carnarvon]] and first [[Duke of Chandos]]. He had a summer house built atop the mound for the wonderful view. The mound, or mount, is now the Stanmore Golf Course.\n\nBelmont is a suburban residential district and was formerly served by [[Belmont railway station, Harrow|Belmont station]], on a railway single-line branch running from [[Harrow & Wealdstone station]] to [[Stanmore Village railway station]]. The line was known locally as The Rattler, a term first coined by Pete Knobbler. The site of the station is now a car park. What may remain of the platform and track lies beneath tons of earth and rubble used to bring the car park up to street level. The Belmont Trail is a nature trail between Wealdstone and Stanmore running along much of the original track route. The circle was originally made for a tram line that would go across London. Its 4 exits were made due to this.<ref>https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/9632158.Health_walk_across_Belmont_s_old_railway_line/</ref>\n\nBelmont Circle provides the main focus of the area, being a large, circular parade of that intersects Kenton Lane.  Many of the outlets are now food-related, with a few bars and a club completing the lineup.  What was formerly the Belmont (and later The Spanish Arch) pub is now 'Funky B, a bar/restaurant serving authentic Indian food. Just off the Circle, Belmont Community Hall hosts local activities, events and a regular [[jumble sale]].\n\nThere are no train stations in Belmont today but both Harrow & Wealdstone and [[Canons Park tube station]] are accessible nearby.\n\n==Demography==\nIn the 2011 census, the largest ethnic group in Belmont ward was Indian (34%), followed by White British (30%).<ref>http://www.ukcensusdata.com/belmont-e05000285</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.belmontcircle.co.uk]\n\n{{LB Harrow}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Harrow]]\n\n\n{{London-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Belmont, Sutton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2016}}\n{{infobox UK place|\n|country =    England\n|static_image_name=Harrow, Belmont Circle, Belmont - geograph.org.uk - 68461.jpg\n|map_type =   Greater London\n|region= London\n|population=  11,343\n|population_ref = (2011 Census. Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13688792&c=Belmont&d=14&e=62&g=6327589&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1477247415637&enc=1|title=Harrow Ward population 2011|accessdate=23 October 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name=             Belmont\n|london_borough=           Harrow\n|constituency_westminster=      [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n|post_town=          HARROW\n|post_town1=         STANMORE\n|postcode_district =       HA3\n|postcode_district1=       HA7\n|postcode_area=            HA\n|postcode_area1=           HA\n|dial_code=      020\n|os_grid_reference=     TQ165905\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.60130|-0.31929|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n'''Belmont''' is an area of the [[London Borough of Harrow]].\n\nThe area is named after the mound, constructed in the early 18th century by ''Henry James Brydges'' - [[Earl of Carnarvon]] and first [[Duke of Chandos]]. He had a summer house built atop the mound for the wonderful view. The mound, or mount, is now the Stanmore Golf Course.\n\nBelmont is a suburban residential district and was formerly served by [[Belmont railway station, Harrow|Belmont station]], on a railway single-line branch running from [[Harrow & Wealdstone station]] to [[Stanmore Village railway station]]. The line was known locally as The Rattler, a term first coined by Pete Knobbler. The site of the station is now a car park. What may remain of the platform and track lies beneath tons of earth and rubble used to bring the car park up to street level. The Belmont Trail is a nature trail between Wealdstone and Stanmore running along much of the original track route. The circle was originally made for a tram line that would go across London. Its 4 exits were made due to this.<ref>https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/9632158.Health_walk_across_Belmont_s_old_railway_line/</ref>\n\nBelmont Circle provides the main focus of the area, being a large, circular parade of that intersects Kenton Lane.  Many of the outlets are now food-related, with a few bars and a club completing the lineup.  What was formerly the Belmont (and later The Spanish Arch) pub is now 'Funky B, a bar/restaurant serving authentic Indian food. Just off the Circle, Belmont Community Hall hosts local activities, events and a regular [[jumble sale]].\n\nThere are no train stations in Belmont today but both Harrow & Wealdstone and [[Canons Park tube station]] are accessible nearby.\n\n==Demography==\nIn the 2011 census, the largest ethnic group in Belmont ward was Indian (34%), followed by White British (30%).<ref>http://www.ukcensusdata.com/belmont-e05000285</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.belmontcircle.co.uk]\n\n{{LB Harrow}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Harrow]]\n\n\n{{London-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Textorus", "label": "safe", "comment": "nix needless italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belmont,_Harrow"}
{"title_page": "You Need Love (Muddy Waters song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = You Need Love\n| cover      = MuddyWatersYouNeedLove.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = US vinyl single released by Chess\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Muddy Waters]]\n| B-side     = Little Brown Bird\n| released   = 1963\n| format     = [[Gramophone record#Formats|7-inch 45&nbsp;rpm record]]\n| recorded   = Chicago, July & October 12, 1962<ref name=\"Wight\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluesandrhythm.co.uk/documents/200.pdf|title=The Complete Muddy Waters discography|last=Wight|first=Phil|last2=Rothwell|first2=Fred|year=1991|website=bluesandrhythm.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| genre      = [[Blues]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Muddy Waters \u2013 You Need Love \u2013 ''AllMusic'' |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/you-need-love-mt0012003691 |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=44}}\n| label      = [[Chess Records|Chess]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Dixon]]\n| producer   =\n*[[Leonard Chess]]\n*[[Phil Chess]]\n| prev_title = [[You Shook Me]]\n| prev_year  = 1962\n| next_title = [[Five Long Years]]\n| next_year  = 1963\n}}\n\"'''You Need Love'''\" is a song with lyrics written by American [[blues]] musician [[Willie Dixon]].  The instrumentation was first recorded by [[slide guitar]]ist [[Earl Hooker]] with backing musicians. [[Chicago blues]] artist [[Muddy Waters]] later overdubbed vocals and [[Chess Records]] released it as a single in 1963. \n\nThe song has since been covered by other artists, including the [[Small Faces]].  [[Led Zeppelin]] subsequently adapted the song for their 1969 hit \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\".<ref name=\":2\" />{{sfn|Inaba|2011|p=194}}{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=77}}<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2016/apr/12/led-zeppelin-other-peoples-records-transformed-borrowed|title=Yes, Led Zeppelin took from other people's records \u2013 but then they transformed them|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=April 12, 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Muddy Waters song ==\n=== Background ===\nSimilar to his previous single, \"[[You Shook Me]]\", Muddy Waters dubbed his vocals onto a backing track, a formula also followed for \"Little Brown Bird\" and \"Black Angel\".{{sfn|Inaba|2011|p=283}} In July 1962, [[Chess Records]] owner [[Leonard Chess]] contacted blues [[slide guitar]]ist [[Earl Hooker]] to record  additional tunes for a new record by Waters. However, Waters was on tour in Ohio, and during his absence, Hooker and the group cut three instrumental backing tracks.  Besides Hooker and organist Big Moose Walker, here are different accounts of who provided the instrumental backing. On October 12, 1962, Waters overdubbed his vocals.{{sfn|Danchin|2001|p=139}} Of the three recordings cut that day, \"Black Angel\" remains unissued.\n\nThe vocals are apparently derived from several earlier songs by Waters, such as \"[[Rollin' Stone]]\", \"Still A Fool\" and \"She's Alright\".{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}} The song is based on a guitar [[riff]] in the key of [[E minor]].{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}} Marie Dixon, Willie Dixon's wife insists that the songs is specially about her:\n\n{{Quote|text=I felt that was more close to me that he wrote is \u201cYou Need Love.\u201d If you listen to those words, I feel that. 'You\u2019re frettin\u2019, I\u2019m pettin\u2019, you need love' that would be more soothing to me, more fitting to me that he wrote. And he had a way of speaking to you through his songs. And I feel that that may have been the one. I\u2019ve always said that that was the one he sort of built the story around me.|sign=Marie Dixon|source=''Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues'' pg. 193}}\n\n=== Release ===\nChess first released the song on a [[7-inch single]], backed with \"Little Brown Bird\" in 1963. As with many of Waters' later singles, it failed to chart on both [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' 100]] and the magazine's [[rhythm and blues chart]]. In the United Kingdom, the single was subsequently withdrawn and replaced by a four-track EP with \"Little Brown Bird\", \"[[You Shook Me]]\" and \"Muddy Waters Twist\". The EP was a favorite of [[Jimmy Page]] and [[Jeff Beck]] during their teenage years.{{sfn|Wall|2010|p=57}}\n\n=== Personnel ===\n* [[Muddy Waters]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Earl Hooker]] \u2013 guitar\n* John 'Big Moose' Walker \u2013 organ\n\nAdditional musicians may include:<ref name=\"Wight\"/>{{sfn|Danchin|2001|p=139}}{{sfn|Chess|1989|p=29}}\n* [[A.C. Reed]] \u2013 tenor sax\n* [[Jackie Brenston]] \u2013 baritone sax\n* Ernest Cotton \u2013 sax\n* Earnest Johnson or [[Willie Dixon]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Casey Jones (musician)|Casey Jones]] or Bobby Little \u2013 drums\n* [[Lafayette Leake]] \u2013 piano\n* Unidentified \u2013 overdubbed percussion (Mbira)\n\n== Small Faces version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You Need Loving\n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[Small Faces]]\n| album      = [[Small Faces (1966 album)|Small Faces]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|05|11}}\n| recorded   = February 1966 \n| studio     = [[IBC Studios|IBC]], London\n| genre      = \n*[[Rhythm and blues]]\n*[[hard rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=56}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Steve Marriott]]\n*[[Ronnie Lane]] (credited)\n| producer   = \n*[[John Pantry]]\n*[[Don Arden]]\n|misc={{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = You Need Loving.ogg\n | description = \"You Need Loving\"\n}}}}\nThree years after its initial release, [[East London]] band [[Small Faces]] released the track as \"You Need Loving\" for their [[Small Faces (1966 album)|eponymous debut album]] in 1966.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/small-faces-decca-mw0000653037|title=''Small Faces'' [Decca] \u2013 Review |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>{{Sfn|Schmitt|Uli|2011|p=33}} The tune, which was a largely improvisational jam by the group, had been a part of their live repertoire along with other [[rhythm and blues]] songs since they formed. At the time, their setlist consisted of about five songs, \"Come On Children\", \"[[Ooh Poo Pah Doo]]\", \"E Too D\", \"[[Baby Don't You Do It]]\" and \"You Need Love\".{{Sfn|Hewitt|Paulo|2004|p=77}} The song was popular with the [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] subculture of the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.makingtime.co.uk/rfr/story2.htm#.XZDDTUYzaUk|title=Room for Ravers: Small Faces Story Part 2 |website=www.makingtime.co.uk|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> It is also noteworthy for 19-year old [[Steve Marriott]]'s raw vocals, one of his most well known characteristics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411004151/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/steve-marriott-was-unbelievable-%E2%80%93-more-on-one-of-classic-rocks-star-singers/ |title='Steve Marriott Was Unbelievable' \u2013 More on One of Classic Rock's Star Singers |date=July 4, 2009 |website=Classicrockmagazine.com |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.epicrights.com/the-most-important-song-youve-never-heard/|title=The Most Important Song You\u2019ve Never Heard|last=Stanley|first=Evan|date=|website=epicrights|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=It was fantastic, I loved it, Muddy Waters recorded it but I couldn't sing like Muddy Waters so it wasn't that much of a nick. I was a high range and Muddy was a low range so I had to figure out how to sing it. So I did and that was our opening number for all the years we were together. Every time we were on stage that was our opening number, unless we had a short set.|sign=[[Steve Marriott]]|source=''Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful...'' pg. 78}}\n\nThe opening verse of the Muddy Waters' original was not included anywhere in \"You Need Loving\", with the Small Faces adding their own bits instead, such as \"[[Eeny, meeny, miny, moe]]\" and \"I can't monkey and I can't dog. Can't do the monkey, yeah\"\n\n{{Poemquote|text=You've got yearnin' and I got burnin'\nBaby you look so sweet and cunning\nBaby way down inside, woman you need love\nWoman you need love, you've got to have some love|source=Muddy Waters, \"You Need Love\", 1963|char=|sign=|title=First verse}}\n\nInfact, the majority of the track was re-written in order to better fit Marriott's style of singing. The first verse was completely remade by replacing it with an altered version of the last verse found in \"You Need Love\":\n\n{{Poemquote|text=Woah you foolin'\nCome and get coolin'\nI'm gonna send you right back to school, alright\nMake your way down the new side girl\nYou know how woman, you need lovin', lovin', alright|char=|sign=|title=First verse|source=Small Faces, \"You Need Loving\", 1966}}\n\nDespite containing several verses found in the original, on original 1966 pressings of the group's debut album, it is only credited to Marriott and [[Ronnie Lane]]. Allegedly, this was a business tactic used by Small Faces manager [[Don Arden]] in order to get more royalties. In fact, Arden kept the royalties himself, with the band earning only \u00a320 a week, despite multiple top ten entries on the [[UK Singles Chart]].{{sfn|Muise|2002|p=91}} Dixon did not sue Arden or the band, because he did not know of its existence.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/6250/20140520/7-songs-other-than-stairway-to-heaven-that-led-zeppelin-stole.htm|title=7 Songs That Led Zeppelin Ripped Off|last=DeGroot|first=Joey|date=May 20, 2014|website=Music Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> On most later reissues of the album, Dixon is credited as a songwriter. The group recorded the song live for [[Saturday Club (BBC Radio)|Saturday Club]] and can be found on the compilation album [[The BBC Sessions (Small Faces album)|''The BBC Sessions'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bbc-sessions-1965-1968-mw0000055356|title=Small Faces: ''BBC Sessions: 1965-1968'' \u2013 Review |last=Unterbereger |first=Richie |authorlink=Richie Unterberger |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> \n\n=== Personnel ===\n* [[Steve Marriott]] \u2013 lead vocals, lead guitar\n* [[Ronnie Lane]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Ian McLagan]] \u2013  [[Hammond organ]], backing vocals\n* [[Kenney Jones]] \u2013 drums\n\n== Similarities with \"Whole Lotta Love\" ==\n{{Main|Whole Lotta Love}}\nNewly formed British [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Led Zeppelin]] recorded a song titled \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\", and released it, backed with \"[[Living Loving Maid (She's Just a Woman)]]\" as a single in November 1969. The track was their first big hit single, reaching number four on [[Billboard Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/led-zeppelin/chart-history/HSI/song/557573|title=Led Zeppelin \u2013 \"Whole Lotta Love\" \u2013 Chart position|last=|first=|date=January 31, 1970|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> and number two in [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox magazine]].{{Sfn|Hoffman|1983|p=341}} The song was largely conceived by [[Jimmy Page]], but is credited to the entire band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-making-of-led-zeppelins-whole-lotta-love-1401390281|title=The Making of Led Zeppelin's 'Whole Lotta Love'|last=Myers|first=Marc|date=May 29, 2014|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> Lyrically however, the song refers to \"You Need Love\"\n\n{{Poemquote|text=You need cooling\nBaby I'm not fooling\nI'm gonna send ya\nBack to schoolin'|source=Led Zeppelin, \"Whole Lotta Love\", 1969}}\n\nVocally, lead singer [[Robert Plant]] phrases the song in the style of Marriott, similar to \"You Need Loving\".{{Sfn|Lewis|1990|p=57}}<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Marriott later stated \"He sang it the same, phrased it the same, even the stops at the end were the same\".{{Sfn|Wall|2010|p=149}} Marriott would later admit that both Page and Plant frequented and attended concerts by Small Faces: \"That\u2019s where Jimmy Page and Robert Plant heard it. Robert Plant used to follow us around. He was like a fan.\"{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=78}}\n\nPlant would eventually later apologize to Marriott in a backstage encounter during the 1970s.{{Sfn|Schmitt|Uli|2011|p=33}} However, Marriott would not belittle \"Whole Lotta Love\", as the first time he heard it he reportedly shouted \"Go on, my son!\"{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=204}} In 1985, Dixon would file a lawsuit against the group after her daughter brought it to his attention.{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}}<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=I ultimately learned . . . about the \u201cWhole Lotta Love,\u201d because I was typing those songs, and he taught me to write music. So I immediately could recognize one of his songs. He taught me the lyric structure and he taught me the music. So, you know, it became obvious to me after a while listened and listened. I was at girlfriend\u2019s house, and the song came on the radio. And I said, \u201cYou know what? That\u2019s my dad\u2019s song.\u201d And she says, \u201cThe song is probably as old as you are (I was thirteen, then), and let\u2019s see I\u2019ve got the album,\u201d she said, \u201cIf they\u2019ve got your dad\u2019s name on it . . .\u201d She said to me, \u201cWell, they\u2019ve got another song on here that your dad wrote, \"[[I Can't Quit You Baby]]\", but that\u2019s [\u201cWhole Lotta Love\u201d] not his song. I said, \u201cOh, yes it is.\u201d And she said, \u201cHave you ever heard him singing it?\u201d I said, \u201cNo, I haven\u2019t, but he taught me how to write. And I see a similar pattern, either he wrote it or it\u2019s twained [sic], and that\u2019s why.\u201d|sign=Shirli Dixon|source=''Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues'' pg. 193}}\n\nThe case would eventually be settled out of court and on all reissues of ''[[Led Zeppelin II]]'', Dixon is credited as a co-writer on the track.{{Sfn|Lewis|1990|p=47}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Robert Plant would later complain in an interview.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Robert Plant's Manic Persona\"|last=Young|first=Charles|publisher=Amordian Press|year=1990|isbn=|location=''[[Musician (magazine)|Musician]]''|pages=45|issn=0733-5253}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Page's riff was Page's riff. It was there before anything else. I just thought, 'well, what am I going to sing?' That was it, a nick. Now happily paid for. At the time, there was a lot of conversation about what to do. It was decided that it was so far away in time and influence that ... well, you only get caught when you're successful. That's the game.|sign=Robert Plant|source=''Musician'' Issue 135-140. pg. 45}}\n== Other covers ==\n* English [[blues rock]] band [[Savoy Brown]] covered the song for their second studio album [[Getting to the Point (album)|''Getting to the Point'']] in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getting-to-the-point-mw0000203332|title=Savoy Brown: ''Getting to The Point'' \u2013 Review|last=Farley|first=Keith|date=|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> It is considered one of the better songs on the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.savoybrown.com/biography/the-early-years/|title=Savoy Brown: ''The Early Years''|last=Celmins|first=Martin|last2=Wat|first2=Jeff|date=2001|website=Savoy Brown|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[The Hoochie Coochie Men]] with [[Deep Purple]] keyboardist [[Jon Lord]] recorded the song live on February 3, 2003 for their 2003 live album ''Live At The Basement.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jonlord.org/recordings/live-at-the-basement/|title=Live At The Basement (with The Hoochie Coochie Men)|last=|first=|date=|website=Jon Lord|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n* [[Muddy Waters discography]]\n* [[Small Faces discography]]\n* [[List of songs that have been the subject of plagiarism disputes]]\n* [[List of Led Zeppelin songs written or inspired by others]]\n* [[Love song]]\n== Notes ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n=== References ===\n*{{cite AV media notes| author = Chess| title = Muddy Waters: Chess Box| others = [[Muddy Waters]]| year = 1989| authorlink = Chess Records| type = Box set booklet| publisher = [[Chess Records|Chess]]/[[MCA Records]]| id = CHD3-80002| oclc = 154264537| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Earl Hooker: Blues Master|last=Danchin|first=Sebastian|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|year=2001|isbn=1-57806-306-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues|last=Inaba|first=Mitsutoshi|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|year=2011|isbn=978-0-8108-6993-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=[[Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful...]]|last=Hewitt|first=Paulo|publisher=[[Helter Skelter Publishing|Helter Skelter]]|year=2004|isbn=1-900924-44-7|ref=harv|location=|pages=|last2=Hellier|first2=John}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JI4LHXgz7YEC&pg=PA89&dq=Small+Faces+Don+Arden&hl=en&ei=5ENJTbTABcLtsgbf7LivDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Small%20Faces%20Don%20Arden&f=false |title=Gallagher, Marriott, Derringer & Trower: Their Lives and Music |last=Muise |first=Dan |publisher=[[Hal Leonard]] |year=2002 |isbn=978-0634029561|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=[[When Giants Walked the Earth: A Biography of Led Zeppelin]]|last=Wall|first=Mick|publisher=[[St. Martin's Griffin]]|year=2010|isbn=978-0-312-59039-0|ref=harv|authorlink=Mick Wall}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Small Faces & Other Stories|last=Schmitt|first=Roland|last2=Twelker|first2=Uli|publisher=Bobcat Books|year=2011|isbn=978-0-85712-451-7|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Cash Box Singles Charts, 1950\u20131981|last=Hoffman|first=Frank|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|year=1983|isbn=978-0810815957|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Led Zeppelin : A Celebration.|last=Lewis|first=Dave|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|year=1990|isbn=978-0-711-92416-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ledzeppelinceleb0000lewi}}\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|muddy-waters|you-need-love}}\n* [http://www.willie-dixon.com/home.html Willie Dixon official website]\n* [https://muddywatersofficial.com/ Muddy Waters official website]\n{{Muddy Waters}}\n{{Small Faces}}\n[[Category:Songs written by Willie Dixon]]\n[[Category:Muddy Waters songs]]\n[[Category:Small Faces songs]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Chess Records singles]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:You Need Love (Muddy Waters song)}}\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = You Need Love\n| cover      = MuddyWatersYouNeedLove.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = US vinyl single released by Chess\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Muddy Waters]]\n| B-side     = Little Brown Bird\n| released   = 1963\n| format     = [[Gramophone record#Formats|7-inch 45&nbsp;rpm record]]\n| recorded   = Chicago, July & October 12, 1962<ref name=\"Wight\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluesandrhythm.co.uk/documents/200.pdf|title=The Complete Muddy Waters discography|last=Wight|first=Phil|last2=Rothwell|first2=Fred|year=1991|website=bluesandrhythm.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| genre      = [[Blues]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Muddy Waters \u2013 You Need Love \u2013 ''AllMusic'' |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/you-need-love-mt0012003691 |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=2|s=44}}\n| label      = [[Chess Records|Chess]]\n| writer     = [[Willie Dixon]]\n| producer   =\n*[[Leonard Chess]]\n*[[Phil Chess]]\n| prev_title = [[You Shook Me]]\n| prev_year  = 1962\n| next_title = [[Five Long Years]]\n| next_year  = 1963\n}}\n\"'''You Need Love'''\" is a song with lyrics written by American [[blues]] musician [[Willie Dixon]].  The instrumentation was first recorded by [[slide guitar]]ist [[Earl Hooker]] with backing musicians. [[Chicago blues]] artist [[Muddy Waters]] later overdubbed vocals and [[Chess Records]] released it as a single in 1963. \n\nThe song has since been covered by other artists, including the [[Small Faces]].  [[Led Zeppelin]] subsequently adapted the song for their 1969 hit \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\".<ref name=\":2\" />{{sfn|Inaba|2011|p=194}}{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=77}}<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2016/apr/12/led-zeppelin-other-peoples-records-transformed-borrowed|title=Yes, Led Zeppelin took from other people's records \u2013 but then they transformed them|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=April 12, 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n== Muddy Waters song ==\n=== Background ===\nSimilar to his previous single, \"[[You Shook Me]]\", Muddy Waters dubbed his vocals onto a backing track, a formula also followed for \"Little Brown Bird\" and \"Black Angel\".{{sfn|Inaba|2011|p=283}} In July 1962, [[Chess Records]] owner [[Leonard Chess]] contacted blues [[slide guitar]]ist [[Earl Hooker]] to record  additional tunes for a new record by Waters. However, Waters was on tour in Ohio, and during his absence, Hooker and the group cut three instrumental backing tracks.  Besides Hooker and organist Big Moose Walker, here are different accounts of who provided the instrumental backing. On October 12, 1962, Waters overdubbed his vocals.{{sfn|Danchin|2001|p=139}} Of the three recordings cut that day, \"Black Angel\" remains unissued.\n\nThe vocals are apparently derived from several earlier songs by Waters, such as \"[[Rollin' Stone]]\", \"Still A Fool\" and \"She's Alright\".{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}} The song is based on a guitar [[riff]] in the key of [[E minor]].{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}} Marie Dixon, Willie Dixon's wife insists that the songs is specially about her:\n\n{{Quote|text=I felt that was more close to me that he wrote is \u201cYou Need Love.\u201d If you listen to those words, I feel that. 'You\u2019re frettin\u2019, I\u2019m pettin\u2019, you need love' that would be more soothing to me, more fitting to me that he wrote. And he had a way of speaking to you through his songs. And I feel that that may have been the one. I\u2019ve always said that that was the one he sort of built the story around me.|sign=Marie Dixon|source=''Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues'' pg. 193}}\n\n=== Release ===\nChess first released the song on a [[7-inch single]], backed with \"Little Brown Bird\" in 1963. As with many of Waters' later singles, it failed to chart on both [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' 100]] and the magazine's [[rhythm and blues chart]]. In the United Kingdom, the single was subsequently withdrawn and replaced by a four-track EP with \"Little Brown Bird\", \"[[You Shook Me]]\" and \"Muddy Waters Twist\". The EP was a favorite of [[Jimmy Page]] and [[Jeff Beck]] during their teenage years.{{sfn|Wall|2010|p=57}}\n\n=== Personnel ===\n* [[Muddy Waters]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Earl Hooker]] \u2013 guitar\n* John 'Big Moose' Walker \u2013 organ\n\nAdditional musicians may include:<ref name=\"Wight\"/>{{sfn|Danchin|2001|p=139}}{{sfn|Chess|1989|p=29}}\n* [[A.C. Reed]] \u2013 tenor sax\n* [[Jackie Brenston]] \u2013 baritone sax\n* Ernest Cotton \u2013 sax\n* Earnest Johnson or [[Willie Dixon]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Casey Jones (musician)|Casey Jones]] or Bobby Little \u2013 drums\n* [[Lafayette Leake]] \u2013 piano\n* Unidentified \u2013 overdubbed percussion (Mbira)\n\n== Small Faces version ==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = You Need Loving\n| type       = song\n| artist     = [[Small Faces]]\n| album      = [[Small Faces (1966 album)|Small Faces]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1966|05|11}}\n| recorded   = February 1966 \n| studio     = [[IBC Studios|IBC]], London\n| genre      = \n*[[Rhythm and blues]]\n*[[hard rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=56}}\n| label      = [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Steve Marriott]]\n*[[Ronnie Lane]] (credited)\n| producer   = \n*[[John Pantry]]\n*[[Don Arden]]\n|misc={{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = You Need Loving.ogg\n | description = \"You Need Loving\"\n}}}}\nThree years after its initial release, [[East London]] band [[Small Faces]] released the track as \"You Need Loving\" for their [[Small Faces (1966 album)|eponymous debut album]] in 1966.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/small-faces-decca-mw0000653037|title=''Small Faces'' [Decca] \u2013 Review |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>{{Sfn|Schmitt|Uli|2011|p=33}} The tune, which was a largely improvisational jam by the group, had been a part of their live repertoire along with other [[rhythm and blues]] songs since they formed. At the time, their setlist consisted of about five songs, \"Come On Children\", \"[[Ooh Poo Pah Doo]]\", \"E Too D\", \"[[Baby Don't You Do It]]\" and \"You Need Love\".{{Sfn|Hewitt|Paulo|2004|p=77}} The song was popular with the [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] subculture of the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.makingtime.co.uk/rfr/story2.htm#.XZDDTUYzaUk|title=Room for Ravers: Small Faces Story Part 2 |website=www.makingtime.co.uk|access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> It is also noteworthy for 19-year old [[Steve Marriott]]'s raw vocals, one of his most well known characteristics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411004151/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/steve-marriott-was-unbelievable-%E2%80%93-more-on-one-of-classic-rocks-star-singers/ |title='Steve Marriott Was Unbelievable' \u2013 More on One of Classic Rock's Star Singers |date=July 4, 2009 |website=Classicrockmagazine.com |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.epicrights.com/the-most-important-song-youve-never-heard/|title=The Most Important Song You\u2019ve Never Heard|last=Stanley|first=Evan|date=|website=epicrights|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=It was fantastic, I loved it, Muddy Waters recorded it but I couldn't sing like Muddy Waters so it wasn't that much of a nick. I was a high range and Muddy was a low range so I had to figure out how to sing it. So I did and that was our opening number for all the years we were together. Every time we were on stage that was our opening number, unless we had a short set.|sign=[[Steve Marriott]]|source=''Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful...'' pg. 78}}\n\nThe opening verse of the Muddy Waters' original was not included anywhere in \"You Need Loving\", with the Small Faces adding their own bits instead, such as \"[[Eeny, meeny, miny, moe]]\" and \"I can't monkey and I can't dog. Can't do the monkey, yeah\"\n\n{{Poemquote|text=You've got yearnin' and I got burnin'\nBaby you look so sweet and cunning\nBaby way down inside, woman you need love\nWoman you need love, you've got to have some love|source=Muddy Waters, \"You Need Love\", 1963|char=|sign=|title=First verse}}\n\nInfact, the majority of the track was re-written in order to better fit Marriott's style of singing. The first verse was completely remade by replacing it with an altered version of the last verse found in \"You Need Love\":\n\n{{Poemquote|text=Woah you foolin'\nCome and get coolin'\nI'm gonna send you right back to school, alright\nMake your way down the new side girl\nYou know how woman, you need lovin', lovin', alright|char=|sign=|title=First verse|source=Small Faces, \"You Need Loving\", 1966}}\n\nDespite containing several verses found in the original, on original 1966 pressings of the group's debut album, it is only credited to Marriott and [[Ronnie Lane]]. Allegedly, this was a business tactic used by Small Faces manager [[Don Arden]] in order to get more royalties. In fact, Arden kept the royalties himself, with the band earning only \u00a320 a week, despite multiple top ten entries on the [[UK Singles Chart]].{{sfn|Muise|2002|p=91}} Dixon did not sue Arden or the band, because he did not know of its existence.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/6250/20140520/7-songs-other-than-stairway-to-heaven-that-led-zeppelin-stole.htm|title=7 Songs That Led Zeppelin Ripped Off|last=DeGroot|first=Joey|date=May 20, 2014|website=Music Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> On most later reissues of the album, Dixon is credited as a songwriter. The group recorded the song live for [[Saturday Club (BBC Radio)|Saturday Club]] and can be found on the compilation album [[The BBC Sessions (Small Faces album)|''The BBC Sessions'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bbc-sessions-1965-1968-mw0000055356|title=Small Faces: ''BBC Sessions: 1965-1968'' \u2013 Review |last=Unterbereger |first=Richie |authorlink=Richie Unterberger |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=September 29, 2019}}</ref> \n\n=== Personnel ===\n* [[Steve Marriott]] \u2013 lead vocals, lead guitar\n* [[Ronnie Lane]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Ian McLagan]] \u2013  [[Hammond organ]], backing vocals\n* [[Kenney Jones]] \u2013 drums\n\n== Similarities with \"Whole Lotta Love\" ==\n{{Main|Whole Lotta Love}}\nNewly formed British [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Led Zeppelin]] recorded a song titled \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\", and released it, backed with \"[[Living Loving Maid (She's Just a Woman)]]\" as a single in November 1969. The track was their first big hit single, reaching number four on [[Billboard Hot 100]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/led-zeppelin/chart-history/HSI/song/557573|title=Led Zeppelin \u2013 \"Whole Lotta Love\" \u2013 Chart position|last=|first=|date=January 31, 1970|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> and number two in [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox magazine]].{{Sfn|Hoffman|1983|p=341}} The song was largely concieved by [[Jimmy Page]], but is credited to the entire band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-making-of-led-zeppelins-whole-lotta-love-1401390281|title=The Making of Led Zeppelin's 'Whole Lotta Love'|last=Myers|first=Marc|date=May 29, 2014|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> Lyrically however, the song refers to \"You Need Love\"\n\n{{Poemquote|text=You need cooling\nBaby I'm not fooling\nI'm gonna send ya\nBack to schoolin'|source=Led Zeppelin, \"Whole Lotta Love\", 1969}}\n\nVocally, lead singer [[Robert Plant]] phrases the song in the style of Marriott, similar to \"You Need Loving\".{{Sfn|Lewis|1990|p=57}}<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Marriott later stated \"He sang it the same, phrased it the same, even the stops at the end were the same\".{{Sfn|Wall|2010|p=149}} Marriott would later admit that both Page and Plant frequented and attended concerts by Small Faces: \"That\u2019s where Jimmy Page and Robert Plant heard it. Robert Plant used to follow us around. He was like a fan.\"{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=78}}\n\nPlant would eventually later apologize to Marriott in a backstage encounter during the 1970s.{{Sfn|Schmitt|Uli|2011|p=33}} However, Marriott would not belittle \"Whole Lotta Love\", as the first time he heard it he reportedly shouted \"Go on, my son!\"{{Sfn|Hewitt|Hellier|2004|p=204}} In 1985, Dixon would file a lawsuit against the group after her daughter brought it to his attention.{{Sfn|Inaba|2011|p=193}}<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n{{Quote|text=I ultimately learned . . . about the \u201cWhole Lotta Love,\u201d because I was typing those songs, and he taught me to write music. So I immediately could recognize one of his songs. He taught me the lyric structure and he taught me the music. So, you know, it became obvious to me after a while listened and listened. I was at girlfriend\u2019s house, and the song came on the radio. And I said, \u201cYou know what? That\u2019s my dad\u2019s song.\u201d And she says, \u201cThe song is probably as old as you are (I was thirteen, then), and let\u2019s see I\u2019ve got the album,\u201d she said, \u201cIf they\u2019ve got your dad\u2019s name on it . . .\u201d She said to me, \u201cWell, they\u2019ve got another song on here that your dad wrote, \"[[I Can't Quit You Baby]]\", but that\u2019s [\u201cWhole Lotta Love\u201d] not his song. I said, \u201cOh, yes it is.\u201d And she said, \u201cHave you ever heard him singing it?\u201d I said, \u201cNo, I haven\u2019t, but he taught me how to write. And I see a similar pattern, either he wrote it or it\u2019s twained [sic], and that\u2019s why.\u201d|sign=Shirli Dixon|source=''Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues'' pg. 193}}\n\nThe case would eventually be settled out of court and on all reissues of ''[[Led Zeppelin II]]'', Dixon is credited as a co-writer on the track.{{Sfn|Lewis|1990|p=47}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Robert Plant would later complain in an interview.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Robert Plant's Manic Persona\"|last=Young|first=Charles|publisher=Amordian Press|year=1990|isbn=|location=''[[Musician (magazine)|Musician]]''|pages=45|issn=0733-5253}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Page's riff was Page's riff. It was there before anything else. I just thought, 'well, what am I going to sing?' That was it, a nick. Now happily paid for. At the time, there was a lot of conversation about what to do. It was decided that it was so far away in time and influence that ... well, you only get caught when you're successful. That's the game.|sign=Robert Plant|source=''Musician'' Issue 135-140. pg. 45}}\n== Other covers ==\n* English [[blues rock]] band [[Savoy Brown]] covered the song for their second studio album [[Getting to the Point (album)|''Getting to the Point'']] in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getting-to-the-point-mw0000203332|title=Savoy Brown: ''Getting to The Point'' \u2013 Review|last=Farley|first=Keith|date=|website=[[AllMusic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> It is considered one of the better songs on the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.savoybrown.com/biography/the-early-years/|title=Savoy Brown: ''The Early Years''|last=Celmins|first=Martin|last2=Wat|first2=Jeff|date=2001|website=Savoy Brown|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[The Hoochie Coochie Men]] with [[Deep Purple]] keyboardist [[Jon Lord]] recorded the song live on February 3, 2003 for their 2003 live album ''Live At The Basement.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jonlord.org/recordings/live-at-the-basement/|title=Live At The Basement (with The Hoochie Coochie Men)|last=|first=|date=|website=Jon Lord|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n* [[Muddy Waters discography]]\n* [[Small Faces discography]]\n* [[List of songs that have been the subject of plagiarism disputes]]\n* [[List of Led Zeppelin songs written or inspired by others]]\n* [[Love song]]\n== Notes ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n=== References ===\n*{{cite AV media notes| author = Chess| title = Muddy Waters: Chess Box| others = [[Muddy Waters]]| year = 1989| authorlink = Chess Records| type = Box set booklet| publisher = [[Chess Records|Chess]]/[[MCA Records]]| id = CHD3-80002| oclc = 154264537| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Earl Hooker: Blues Master|last=Danchin|first=Sebastian|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|year=2001|isbn=1-57806-306-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Willie Dixon: Preacher of the Blues|last=Inaba|first=Mitsutoshi|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|year=2011|isbn=978-0-8108-6993-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=[[Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful...]]|last=Hewitt|first=Paulo|publisher=[[Helter Skelter Publishing|Helter Skelter]]|year=2004|isbn=1-900924-44-7|ref=harv|location=|pages=|last2=Hellier|first2=John}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JI4LHXgz7YEC&pg=PA89&dq=Small+Faces+Don+Arden&hl=en&ei=5ENJTbTABcLtsgbf7LivDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Small%20Faces%20Don%20Arden&f=false |title=Gallagher, Marriott, Derringer & Trower: Their Lives and Music |last=Muise |first=Dan |publisher=[[Hal Leonard]] |year=2002 |isbn=978-0634029561|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=[[When Giants Walked the Earth: A Biography of Led Zeppelin]]|last=Wall|first=Mick|publisher=[[St. Martin's Griffin]]|year=2010|isbn=978-0-312-59039-0|ref=harv|authorlink=Mick Wall}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Small Faces & Other Stories|last=Schmitt|first=Roland|last2=Twelker|first2=Uli|publisher=Bobcat Books|year=2011|isbn=978-0-85712-451-7|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Cash Box Singles Charts, 1950\u20131981|last=Hoffman|first=Frank|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|year=1983|isbn=978-0810815957|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Led Zeppelin : A Celebration.|last=Lewis|first=Dave|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|year=1990|isbn=978-0-711-92416-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ledzeppelinceleb0000lewi}}\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|muddy-waters|you-need-love}}\n* [http://www.willie-dixon.com/home.html Willie Dixon official website]\n* [https://muddywatersofficial.com/ Muddy Waters official website]\n{{Muddy Waters}}\n{{Small Faces}}\n[[Category:Songs written by Willie Dixon]]\n[[Category:Muddy Waters songs]]\n[[Category:Small Faces songs]]\n[[Category:1963 songs]]\n[[Category:Chess Records singles]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:You Need Love (Muddy Waters song)}}\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You_Need_Love_(Muddy_Waters_song)"}
{"title_page": "The Colour and the Shape", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Colour and the Shape\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Foo Fighters]]\n| cover      = FooFighters-TheColourAndTheShape.jpg\n| alt        = A blue background with grey shape. The words \"Foo Fighters\" appear in red.\n| released   = {{Start date|1997|5|20}}\n| recorded   = November 1996 \u2013 February 1997\n| studio     = {{ubl|Bear Creek ([[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville, WA]])|WGNS (Washington, D.C.)|Grandmaster Recorders (Hollywood, CA)}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[post-grunge]]|{{nowrap|[[hard rock]]}}|[[grunge]]}}\n| length     = 46:47\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Roswell Records|Roswell]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| producer   = [[Gil Norton]]\n| prev_title = [[Foo Fighters (album)|Foo Fighters]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[There Is Nothing Left to Lose]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Colour and the Shape\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\n | single1date = April 28, 1997\n | single2     = [[Everlong]]\n | single2date = August 18, 1997\n | single3     = [[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\n | single3date = January 19, 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Colour and the Shape''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Foo Fighters]], released on May 20, 1997, by Roswell and [[Capitol Records]]. It marked the official debut of the Foo Fighters as a band, as their [[Foo Fighters (album)|eponymous 1995 debut album]] was primarily recorded by frontman [[Dave Grohl]] and producer Barrett Jones as a [[demo (music)|demo]]. After the debut became an international success, Grohl recruited guitarist [[Pat Smear]], bassist [[Nate Mendel]], and drummer [[William Goldsmith]] to form the band's full lineup. The group convened in the fall of 1996 for pre-production on a second album, and brought in [[Gil Norton]] as producer to establish a [[pop music|pop]] sensibility for the tracks. The band strived to create a full-fledged rock record, contrary to music press predictions that it would be another [[grunge]] offshoot.\n\nPrimarily inspired by Grohl's divorce from photographer Jennifer Youngblood in 1996, ''The Colour and the Shape'' is more lyrically introspective and musically developed than the Foo Fighters' debut. The album's track listing was designed to resemble a therapy session, splitting the album between uptempo tracks and ballads to reflect conflicting emotions. Early sessions at the Bear Creek studio in Washington went poorly and the band discarded most of those recordings. The band regrouped without Goldsmith in early 1997 to record at Hollywood's Grandmaster Recordings studio, with Grohl sitting in on drums instead. Goldsmith was offended and disgruntled that most of his material had been re-recorded, and he left the band shortly thereafter.\n\nThe singles \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\", \"[[Everlong]]\", and \"[[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\" peaked within the top ten of US rock radio charts, and the album charted at number ten on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. The album was also a commercial success on an international level, peaking at number three in the United Kingdom. Critics deemed the album a significant American rock release of its era, and in retrospective assessments it continues to be viewed as a seminal modern rock album. It was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] [[40th Grammy Awards|in 1998]] for [[Best Rock Album]]. ''The Colour and the Shape'' remains the Foo Fighters' biggest seller in the U.S., having sold more than two million copies according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]]. The album was [[remastered]] and reissued in 2007 with several bonus tracks for its tenth anniversary.\n\n==Background==\nThe album was the debut of Foo Fighters as a full band. On [[Foo Fighters (album)|the first album]] under the Foo Fighters name, frontman [[Dave Grohl]] had performed and recorded all of the parts by himself, with the exception of one guitar part played by [[Greg Dulli]]. The band's original lineup assembled for their exhaustive touring schedule throughout 1995 and 1996, during which the band became an international sensation on the strength of singles \"[[This Is a Call]]\", \"[[I'll Stick Around]]\", and \"[[Big Me]]\". Although the music press generally speculated the band's sophomore record would showcase [[grunge]]-inspired [[garage rock]], the band's intention was to make a more straightforward rock record.<ref name=\"access97\"/> The deal the band struck with [[Capitol Records]] afforded them a large degree of creative control over the band's true \"debut.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> The songs on the record were composed during [[soundcheck]]s during their extensive touring over the previous eighteen months.<ref name=story/> Mendel said \"the germ of every song is Dave's,\" with the frontman providing a riff and a basic song structure. The band would then [[jam session|jam]] and each member would contribute to some aspect of the song.<ref name=id>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14|title=Foo Fighters At Peace With Group Identity; Hollywood Won't Get Whalley|journal=Billboard|author=Newman, Melina|date=1997-05-17}}</ref>\n\nGrohl recruited producer [[Gil Norton]] to provide additional pop polish to the material. He especially wanted to hear guitar overdubs and harmonies with significant clarity.<ref name=\"access97\"/> Grohl said he admired Norton for his earlier work with the [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] and his ability to \"distill a coherent pop song out of all [the Pixies'] multi-layered weirdness.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\">{{cite AV media notes | title=The Colour and the Shape (Bonus Tracks) | year=2007 | others=[[Foo Fighters]] | type=liner notes | publisher=Roswell/RCA/Legacy | location=[[United States|US]] | id=88697 09183 2}}</ref> Norton was highly demanding of the band's performance, prompting bassist [[Nate Mendel]] to practice and improve his musical skill.<ref name=back/> Grohl said \"it was frustrating and it was hard and it was long, but at the end of the day you listened back to what you'd done and you understood why you had to do it one million times.\"<ref name=bill>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Capitol Stresses Group 'Shape' of the Foo Fighters|journal=Billboard|author=Newman, Melina|date=1997-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |salign=center|quote=While recording this record two marriages fell apart, we lost a drummer, someone nearly went to jail, and we discovered late in the day that record making is hellishly expensive and best done with a budget prepared beforehand.|source=\u2013 [[Nate Mendel]], May 2007<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>|align=right|width=25em}}\n''The Colour and the Shape'' was recorded over the period of two months, primarily at Grandmaster Recorders in Hollywood from January to February 1997.<ref name=\"access97\"/> The band spent two weeks in pre-production the previous autumn, rehearsing the tracks and changing arrangements.<ref name=\"access97\"/> Norton had his greatest impact during pre-production, during which he spent days with Grohl in his hotel room \"stripping the songs back to their absolute basics.\"<ref name=story>{{cite book|year=2006|title=The Dave Grohl Story|first=Jeff|last=Apter|publisher=Music Sales Group|ISBN=978-0-85712-021-2|page=304}}</ref> His role in production taught the band the importance of self-editing and gave them confidence to see \"the larger picture in a song.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> Afterward, the band set off for Bear Creek Studios in [[Woodinville, Washington]], where the first recording sessions for ''The Colour and the Shape'' began on November 18, 1996.<ref name=\"story\"/> Mendel described Bear Creek as \"a converted barn with a salmon stream running through it\".<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> The studio was located on a farm and, for the duration of these sessions, the band lived in a cabin adjacent to the studio.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\nGrohl, who described the sessions at Bear Creek as a \"bad experience,\" decided to scrap nearly all of the recorded tracks.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/><ref name=\"kerrang\"/> The band took a break for the holidays, during which Grohl returned to Virginia and wrote several new songs. He recorded two of these songs by himself at WGNS Studios in Washington, D.C.: \"[[Walking After You]]\" and an acoustic version of \"[[Everlong]]\".<ref name=dictionary>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040503202840/http://www.foofighters.com/archives/dictionary.php|url=http://www.foofighters.com/archives/dictionary.php|archivedate=2004-05-03|title=Foo Dictionary|publisher=The Official Foo Fighters Site|accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1997, the band\u2014minus drummer [[William Goldsmith]]\u2014relocated to Hollywood's Grandmaster Recorders, which Mendel said was \"a small studio that sometimes moonlighted as a porn set, and looked the part.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> For a period of four weeks, the band re-recorded most of the album with Grohl playing the drum tracks. Grohl's drumming started with only \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\", as Grohl and Norton felt the drums on that song needed more work, but by the end of the sessions recordings of Goldsmith's drumming remained on only two tracks, \"Doll\" and \"Up in Arms\".<ref name=apter306>Apter, 2006. p. 306</ref> According to Grohl, Goldsmith's drumming had good moments, but his performances mostly did not fit what Grohl had conceived for the drum track, so the frontman decided to redo them himself. Goldsmith even asked if he should go to Los Angeles, but Grohl declined and said he was only performing [[overdub]]s. Eventually, Mendel told Goldsmith the situation. Grohl said that he still wanted Goldsmith as a member of the band, despite replacing his tracks, but the disgruntled drummer decided to leave the Foo Fighters instead.<ref name=back/> Speaking in 2011 about the tension that surrounded the Goldsmith's departure, Grohl said, \"There were a lot of reasons it didn't work out [\u2026] but there was also a part of me that was like, you know, I don't know if I'm finished playing the drums yet. [\u2026] I wish that I would have handled things differently.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=RTE2fm |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WWhsYINKcKM#t=2m56s |title=Oxegen 2011 \u2013 Foo Fighters Dave Grohl |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-07-10 |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter the move to Los Angeles, the album's budget ballooned and deadlines became a more pressing concern.<ref name=\"vox\"/> Studio time was expensive and the group was pressured by Capitol to deliver the record in a timely fashion.<ref name=kerrang>{{cite journal| last =Peake| first =Mike| date =April 1997| title =Leader of the Gang| journal = [[Kerrang!]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher =[[Bauer Media Group]]| location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> However, the pressure never adversely affected the band members, whose main priorities were to make \"music for its own sake [\u2026] and let the commercial concerns take care of themselves.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\nThe album's title came from the band's tour manager of the time, who would often spend afternoons rummaging thrift stores and purchasing strange memorabilia; on one occasion, he purchased a bowling pin with red and white stripes, remarking to the band he rather liked \"the colour and the shape\" of the object.<ref name=\"livewire97\">{{cite journal| last =Anders| first =Marcel| date =October 1997| title =Rock & Grohl| journal = Live Wire| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = | location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> The group found the phrase arbitrary and hilarious and decided to use it as the title, rather than trying to choose a title based on the music's themes or moods.<ref name=\"livewire97\"/> They chose the British spelling of \"''colour''\" with a \"U\" as a tribute to Norton, who is British.<ref>{{cite journal| last =Villeneuve| first =Nicole| date =March 28, 2011| title =Dave Grohl: Times Like These| journal = [[Exclaim!]]| url =http://exclaim.ca/music/article/dave_grohl-times_like_these | accessdate =May 14, 2019 }}</ref> A title track was written and recorded for ''The Colour and the Shape'' during the Bear Creek sessions, but like most of the other songs attempted there, it did not reach the album's final track list. Noted as \"rawer, noisier and thrashier\" than the rest of the songs on the album by ''[[Louder Sound]]''{{'}}s Paul Brannigan, it later became a b-side to the album's eventual lead single, \"Monkey Wrench\".<ref name=\"bsides-louder\">{{cite web |last1=Brannigan |first1=Paul |title=The 10 best Foo Fighters songs tucked away on b-sides |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-10-best-foo-fighters-songs-tucked-away-on-b-sides |website=[[Louder Sound]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703135057/https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-10-best-foo-fighters-songs-tucked-away-on-b-sides |archivedate=July 3, 2019 |date=December 22, 2018}}</ref> After settling on a track sequence, Grohl was struck by the impression that the album's flow from start to finish resembled a therapy session, moving from fear and anxiety at the start to self-assurance and resolve by the end.<ref name=\"vox\"/> He even considered placing a therapist's couch on the album cover.<ref name=\"vox\"/>\n\n==Composition==\nProfessional reviewers have characterized the musical genre of ''The Colour and the Shape'' as [[alternative rock]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|author-link=Douglas Wolk|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ywEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Best New Music: The Five Best Releases This Month \u2014 Foo Fighters / ''The Colour and the Shape'' / Rosewell\u2013Capitol |work=[[CMJ#CMJ New Music Monthly|CMJ New Music Monthly]]|issue=Special Summer Issue|date=July 1997|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> [[grunge]],<ref name=ew/> [[post-grunge]],<ref name=allmusic/> and [[hard rock]].<ref>{{cite web|last=DeGroot|first=Joey|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/7749/20140719/9-great-albums-that-open-with-very-brief-songs-foo-fighters-cat-stevens-and-more.htm|title=9 Great Albums That Open with Very Brief Songs: Foo Fighters, Cat Stevens, and More|work=Music Times|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Melody Maker]]'', Victoria Segal said the album was more cohesive than the debut and was unified by a theme of \"battered romanticism\".<ref name=mm /> More specifically, many of the lyrics address the dissolution of Grohl's marriage to Jennifer Youngblood during the winter of 1996, which Grohl said had been \"the winter of my discontent.\"<ref name=mm>{{cite journal| last =Segal| first =Victoria| date =April 1997| title =All's Well That Ends Roswell| journal = [[Melody Maker]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = [[IPC Media]]| location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> The album's track sequence reflects this sentiment, chronicling his change from chaos to newfound happiness.<ref name=vox>{{cite journal| last =Bailie| first =Stuart| date =June 1997| title =Happy Dave Is Here Again| journal = [[Vox (magazine)|Vox]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = [[IPC Media]]| location = | issn = | url = https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/foo-fighters-happy-dave-is-here-again | via = [[Rock's Backpages]] | accessdate = }} {{subscription required}}</ref> Grohl admitted the lyrics of the previous album had been \"obscure\" and \"nonsense,\" but Norton challenged Grohl to write lyrics that were more meaningful and comprehensible.<ref name=\"mm\"/> Grohl delved deeper into his feelings with the lyrics and said \"there was a new freedom: 'Wow, I can actually write about things I feel strongly about and things that mean something to me and things I wouldn't normally say in everyday conversation.'\" The frontman stated that the experience was \"kind of liberating,\" comparing the album to going to a weekly visit to the therapist \"and then the rest of the week feel pretty good about everything.\" Grohl also found new strength in his singing, overcoming insecurities he had about his singing voice on the debut.<ref name=bill/> Three types of songs permeate the record: ballads, up-tempo tracks and combinations of the two. Grohl felt they were representative of the specific emotions he would feel after the divorce.<ref name=\"livewire97\" />\n\n===Track information===\nThe album's opener, \"Doll\", involves the fear of entering into situations unprepared.<ref name=\"vox\"/><ref name=\"fooarchive1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fooarchive.com/headwires/colourandtheshape.htm |title=The Colour and the Shape : Dave Grohl's Guide To Every Song |publisher=Fooarchive.com |accessdate=2011-11-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124163039/http://www.fooarchive.com/headwires/colourandtheshape.htm |archivedate=2011-11-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> Regarding \"Monkey Wrench\", Grohl stated that it was \"a song about realizing that you are the source of all of the problems in a relationship and you love the other person so much, you want to free them of the problem, which is actually yourself. It was a riff that turned into another riff that turned into another riff and ended up being a nice little power punk song.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> In another interview, Grohl stated his pride in the song: \"With Monkey Wrench I remember I had the main riff, but I didn't have the little jangly riff that goes over the top of it and I thought it needed something. So I came up with the jangly riff and thought 'Oh my God this is never gonna fly! Everyone's gonna hate it'. But I was really excited the first time I heard it on the radio\u2014it was in the middle of a load of mid-'90s grunge shit and I thought it was so killer.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fooarchive.com/gpb/100riffs.htm |title=KERRANG! \u2013 The Top 100 Riffs: No. 50 Monkey Wrench \u2013 October '09 |publisher=Fooarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> The song was released as the first single from the album in 1997.\n\nThe lyrics to \"Hey, Johnny Park!\" song follow a series of different themes (\"about 15 different things\", according to Grohl). Johnny Park is the name of one of Grohl's childhood friends; he noted, \"we were like brothers from the age of 5 to 12\" and that he named the song after Park in hopes that he might restore contact with him.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> \"My Poor Brain\" experiments with different [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]], both musically and lyrically in nature. Grohl likened the disparity in sounds to changes from [[Jackson Five]] to [[Black Sabbath]].<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> Grohl described the concept of \"Wind Up\" as about successful musicians who constantly complain about their lives to the press. He elaborated, \"It drives me insane when I hear musicians that don't understand how fortunate they are that they don't have to go and pump gas for twelve hours a day. They can sit on their couch and smoke pot, and complain to their friends that they hate it when someone comes up and says that he likes their band... there are two sides: there's the reluctant rock-star, and then there is the prying journalist that almost lives for the reluctant rock-star, it's just talking \"about the hand you've been dealt.\" Every time I hear about \"the hand you've been dealt,\" it drives me fucking nuts, spare me your confessions... I've had so many fucking bullshit jobs for the half of my life\u2014you know, working in furniture warehouses and planting trees, painting houses\u2014and it's a lot more fun to play music.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Rock & Grohl |url=http://www.fooarchive.com:80/features/livewire97.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090721002307/http://www.fooarchive.com/features/livewire97.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 July 2009 |magazine=Livewire |date=October 1997 |access-date=23 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGrohl described \"Up in Arms\" as \"A typical love song. It's almost like a [[the Knack|Knack]] song, just a simple pop song.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> Also in the song, Dave changed the last line which is meant to sing \"always coming back I cannot forget you girl\" to \"always coming back I cannot forget you ''Gil''\" in reference to their producer [[Gil Norton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foofighterslive.com/recordinghistory/studio/1997-02-00.php |title=Recording History &#124; Studio &#124; February 1997 \u2013 Grand Master Recorders Ltd, Hollywood, CA |publisher=FooFightersLive.com |accessdate=2013-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021211637/http://www.foofighterslive.com/recordinghistory/studio/1997-02-00.php |archive-date=2013-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"My Hero\" criticizes idolatry and instead extolls friends who are ordinary heroes, which has been considered a statement on fame and partially inspired by former bandmate Kurt Cobain.<ref name=access97>{{cite magazine| date =1997| title =The Think Tank| magazine = [[Select (magazine)|Select]]}}</ref><ref name=\"vox\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Which Foo Fighters song is about Kurt Cobain? |url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/foo-fighters/which-foo-fighters-song-about-kurt-cobain/ |publisher=[[Radio X (United Kingdom)|Radio X UK]] |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407062701/https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/foo-fighters/which-foo-fighters-song-about-kurt-cobain/ |archivedate=April 7, 2019 |date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> In Grohl's own words, the song is, \"(his) way of saying that when I was young, I didn't have big rock heroes, I didn't want to grow up and be some big sporting hero. My heroes were ordinary people and the people that I have a lot of respect for are just solid everyday people\u2014people you can rely on.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> This was the third single to be released from the album. \"See You\" was a song that, according to Grohl, only he liked out of the rest of the band. When Grohl entered the studio, he changed Goldsmith's original drum part to resemble [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\" so the rest of the group would be satisfied with putting it on the record.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/>\n\n\"Enough Space\" is about ''[[Arizona Dream]]'', one of Grohl's favorite films.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> He also said the song emerged from his desire to create a song that would be a good opener on their [[set lists]], with a tempo that mimicked the jumping and bouncing of European crowds in the beginning of sets.<ref name=back>{{cite AV media|author=[[James Moll|Moll, James]] (director)|title=[[Foo Fighters: Back and Forth]]|year=2011|medium=documentary|publisher=RCA}}</ref> The lyrics of \"February Stars\" are said to be about \"hanging on by the tips of your fingers and hoping you don't slip and fall.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> This song dates back to at least January 1994, when an early take of the song with alternate lyrics, titled \"Dave/Acoustic + Voc\" was recorded by Grohl and [[Krist Novoselic]] on [[Pump organ|Harmonium]] during [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s last recording session.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gaar |first=Gillian G. |url=http://www.livenirvana.com/sessions/reading/mojo126.php |title=Nirvana: The Lost Tapes |magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|MOJO]] |date=May 2004}}</ref> \"Everlong\" was written when the band took a break from recording after the initial sessions. Grohl reworked \"Everlong\" by himself at his home in Virginia.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Epstein |first1=Dan |title=Foo Fighters\u2019 \u2018The Colour and the Shape\u2019: 10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/foo-fighters-the-colour-and-the-shape-10-things-you-didnt-know-115404/|magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=20 May 2017}}</ref> It is considered to be one of the best songs by the band and is highly acclaimed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fooarchive.com/other/onfoo.htm |title=Foo Fighters  |publisher=Fooarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> Grohl was almost reduced to tears after performing the song at [[Neil Young]]'s [[Bridge School Benefit]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Scaggs |first1=Austin |title=Dave Grohl |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dave-grohl-203436/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=12 June 2003}}</ref> In 2000, [[David Letterman]] revealed that it is his favorite song.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=A Brief History of David Letterman\u2019s Love for the Foo Fighters |website=Slate |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=21 May 2015 |url= http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/05/21/a_brief_history_of_david_letterman_s_love_for_the_foo_fighters.html }}</ref>\n\n\"Walking After You\" was written and recorded by Grohl on his own in a studio in Washington. This version appears on the album. The band would later re-record the song with all the members for [[The X-Files: The Album|''The X-Files'' soundtrack]], and this version was released as a single.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Gillian Anderson Talks Dave Grohl\u2019s \u2018X-Files\u2019 Cameo |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gillian-anderson-talks-dave-grohls-x-files-cameo-107963/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=22 February 2016}}</ref> Grohl stated that \"Walking After You\" was \"an emotional, sappy song about getting dumped.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> On the record's closing track, \"New Way Home,\" Grohl longs for his hometown and recalls the drive there on Highway 99. Through this journey, \"I realise that it\u2019s OK, I can make my way through all of this, and I\u2019m not that freaked out at the end.\"<ref name=\"vox\"/>\n\n==Release==\n''The Colour and the Shape'' was released on May 20, 1997, preceded the month before by lead single \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\". The promotional campaign emphasized the band's group identity as well as each band member's individual personality.<ref name=bill/> This strategy contrasted with the marketing approach for the prior album, which had centered Grohl at a time before Mendel and Smear felt comfortable being marketed as personalities.<ref name=bill/> Each member gave interviews with press discussing their interests, with guitarist [[Pat Smear]] talking to guitar and fashion magazines.<ref name=id/> Just as recording was finished and [[Taylor Hawkins]] was hired as the new drummer (he was the former touring drummer for [[Alanis Morissette]]'s ''[[Jagged Little Pill]]'' in 1995), Smear expressed his own plans to leave the band, claiming he was exhausted and not motivated to go through with another extended tour.<ref name=back/> This information was not yet highly publicized, and spokespeople for the band denied that the rumors of Smear's impending departure were true.<ref name=\"smear-mtv1\" /> The promotional tour started in May 1997.<ref name=bill/>\n\n\"Everlong\" was released as the album's second single in August 1997. It was the most commercially successful single from the record, being certified [[RIAA|double platinum]] in the United States and being one of only three Foo Fighters songs to reach that status.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Foo+Fighters#search_section|title=American certifications \u2013 Foo Fighters|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> Smear remained with the group until September 4, the night of the [[1997 MTV Video Music Awards]]. After playing \"Monkey Wrench\" during the \"pregame show\" to the event, Smear announced that it was the final song he would play with the band, introducing [[Franz Stahl]] as the band's new guitarist before the band began playing \"Everlong\" later that evening.<ref name=\"smear-mtv1\">{{cite web |author1=MTV staff |title=Pat Smear Leaves the Foo Fighters on Live MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1429056/pat-smear-leaves-the-foo-fighters-on-live-mtv/ |website=[[MTV]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703142734/http://www.mtv.com/news/1429056/pat-smear-leaves-the-foo-fighters-on-live-mtv/ |archivedate=July 3, 2019 |date=September 4, 1997}}</ref> \"My Hero\" was released as the third and final single from the album in 1998. All three singles peaked inside the top ten of the [[Alternative Songs]] and [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]] charts.<ref name=\"Alternativesongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/foo-fighters/chart-history/alternative-songs|title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Alternative Songs| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/foo-fighters/chart-history/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Foo Fighters \u2013 Mainstream Rock Songs chart history| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTo commemorate ''The Colour and the Shape''{{'}}s tenth anniversary, it was reissued on July 10, 2007, with six additional tracks: the B-sides \"Dear Lover\" and \"The Colour and the Shape\", plus covers of [[Killing Joke]]'s \"[[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\", [[Gary Numan]]'s \"[[Down in the Park]]\", [[Gerry Rafferty]]'s \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\" and [[Vanity 6]]'s \"[[Vanity 6 (album)|Drive Me Wild]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1052002/foo-fighters-expand-second-album-for-reissue|title=Foo Fighters Expand Second Album For Reissue|date=May 21, 2007|author=Cohen, Jonathan|accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-colour-and-the-shape-mw0000088006|title=The Colour and the Shape \u2013 Foo Fighters|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|title=Back Catalogue: Nirvana|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=68|location=New York|date=April 2008|pages=88\u201389}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4390319.html|title='The Colour and the Shape', Foo Fighters, Capitol Records|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=May 20, 1997|accessdate=November 18, 2015|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118100104/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4390319.html|archive-date=November 18, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite journal|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1997/05/23/colour-and-shape|title=The Colour and the Shape|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|location=New York|date=May 23, 1997|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Scribner|first=Sara|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-05-18/entertainment/ca-59862_1_album-review|title=Foo Fighters, 'The Colour and the Shape,' Roswell/Capitol|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 18, 1997|accessdate=November 18, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119013652/http://articles.latimes.com/1997-05-18/entertainment/ca-59862_1_album-review|archivedate=November 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=McMahon|first=James|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-foo-fighters-8844|title=Foo Fighters: The Colour And The Shape|work=[[NME]]|location=London|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=November 18, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701215730/http://www.nme.com/reviews/foo-fighters/8844|archivedate=July 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=Christina|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-colour-and-the-shape-19970529|title=The Colour And The Shape|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|date=May 29, 1997|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Wolk\">{{cite book|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|chapter=Foo Fighters|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/306 306\u201307]|editor1-first=Nathan|editor1-last=Brackett|editor2-first=Christian|editor2-last=Hoard|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|edition=4th|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=2004|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA306#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hopper|first=Jessica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLoecqYeotYC&pg=PA113#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Spins|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=13|issue=4|date=July 1997|accessdate=January 7, 2015|page=113}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv797-97.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=July 22, 1997|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nCritical response to the record was generally positive. Victoria Segal at the UK-based ''[[Melody Maker]]'' viewed ''The Colour and the Shape'' as a significant American rock release, writing that it was \"a great rock album at a time when great rock albums are viewed with increasing suspicion.\"<ref name=mm/> Segal's review described the album as leagues ahead of other post-grunge acts: \"The first album might have been a collection of loveable songs, but lacked the sheer visceral attack that thrills this time round,\" Segal wrote, calling it \"[a]n attack that would have{{nbsp}}[\u2026] almost any other US rock band biting their nails in anguish and embarrassment.\"<ref name=mm/>\n\nChristina Kelly of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' was largely positive, although she singled out Norton's production as distracting: \"''Colour'' has a big, radio-ready, modern-rock sound. Some might even call the album overproduced: On the ballads, the vocals are overprocessed and fake sounding.\"<ref name=RS/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised the band's growth, but criticized the sound, which journalist [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] described as \"like much current alt-rock: been there, grunged that.\"<ref name=ew/> In contrast, Stephen Thomas Erlewine of [[AllMusic]] described that production as revolutionary: \"everything here wound up defining the sound of [[post-grunge]] modern rock, and it remains as perhaps the best example of its kind.\"<ref name=allmusic/> In his review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] said the music was routine but elevated by Grohl's \"marital breakup content/concept,\" which allowed him to \"fully inhabit the music that meant so much to him and millions of other Kurt Cobain fans.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> Ryan Schreiber of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' was less favorable, rating the album 3.4 out of 10 and calling the music \"sorely dated.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schreiber|first1=Ryan|title=Foo Fighters: The Colour & The Shape: Pitchfork Review|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/f/foo-fighters/colour-and-the-shape.shtml|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=21 March 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030219043918/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/f/foo-fighters/colour-and-the-shape.shtml|archivedate=19 February 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFour years after Schreiber's 2003 review, ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Stuart Berman gave the tenth anniversary re-release a mildly more favorable review. Scoring the release a 5.8 out of 10, he stated, \"''The Colour and the Shape'' presented a true picture of the kind of group Grohl wanted to be in, had he not been sidetracked by the job of drumming for the biggest American rock band of the early 1990s [...] that band would turn out to be much more formulaically mall-punk than the Foos' torn 'n' frayed debut suggested.\"<ref name=\"berman\">{{cite web |last1=Berman |first1=Stuart |title=The Colour and the Shape [10th Anniversary Special Edition] |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10473-the-colour-and-the-shape-10th-anniversary-special-edition/ |website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530214709/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10473-the-colour-and-the-shape-10th-anniversary-special-edition// |archivedate=May 30, 2019 |date=August 1, 2007}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewed the re-release with the opposite opinion, citing the self titled record's single \"I'll Stick Around\" as an example of \"Grohl's strikingly non-aggressive (read: bland) vocal style\" from the 1995 album; he then described \"Monkey Wrench\" as proof that Grohl \"knew how to rock out\" by comparison.<ref name=\"popmatters-2007\">{{cite web |last1=Schiller |first1=Mike |title=Foo Fighters: The Colour and the Shape |url=https://www.popmatters.com/foo-fighters-the-colour-and-the-shape-2496216428.html |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019|date=August 22, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Commercial performance===\n''The Colour and the Shape'' peaked at number 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], up from a peak of 23 for the 1995 self-titled debut.<ref name=\"US-albums\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=foo fighters|chart=Billboard 200}} | title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History: Billboard 200 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> It also managed to reach the top ten in Australia,<ref name=\"AUS-albums\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=australian-charts.com|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=foo fighters|chart=Canadian Albums}} | title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History: Canadian Albums | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Greece,<ref name=\"IFPI-ireland\" /> Ireland,<ref name=\"IFPI-ireland\" /> New Zealand,<ref name=\"NZ\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=charts.nz|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Sweden,<ref name=\"SWE\">{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=swedishcharts.com|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"UK-albums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/27860/foo-fighters/|title=Foo Fighters|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> The album has also been certified Platinum in the United States,<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> Australia,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref> Canada,<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?fwp_gp_search=Foo%20Fighters|title=Gold/Platinum|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/ |title=Certified Awards Search|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=February 3, 2013|format=enter the search parameter \"Foo Fighters\" into the ''Search'' box, then select \"artist\" in the ''Search by'' box, then select \"Exact match\".}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Dave Grohl]], [[Nate Mendel]] and [[Pat Smear]] except where noted\n| title1 = Doll\n| writer1 = \n| length1 = 1:23\n| title2 = [[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\n| length2 = 3:51\n| title3 = Hey, Johnny Park!\n| length3 = 4:08\n| title4 = My Poor Brain\n| length4 = 3:33\n| title5 = Wind Up\n| length5 = 2:32\n| title6 = Up in Arms\n| length6 = 2:15\n| title7 = [[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\n| length7 = 4:20\n| title8 = See You\n| length8 = 2:26\n| title9 = Enough Space\n| note9 = Grohl\n| length9 = 2:37\n| title10 = February Stars\n| length10 = 4:49\n| title11 = [[Everlong]]\n| note11 = Grohl\n| length11 = 4:10\n| title12 = [[Walking After You]]\n| note12 = Grohl\n| length12 = 5:03\n| title13 = New Way Home\n| length13 = 5:40\n|total_length = 46:47\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Original single\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Australian tour pack (Grey cover)\n| title1 = [[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\n| extra1 = \"Everlong\" (CD2)\n| note1 = [[Killing Joke]] cover\n| length1 = 3:34\n| title2 = Drive Me Wild\n| extra2 = \"Everlong\" (CD1) and \"My Hero\" (Japanese edition)\n| note2 = [[Vanity 6]] cover\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = [[Down in the Park]]\n| extra3 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD2), \"Everlong\" (Australian limited edition) and \"My Hero\" (Japane