gn:center;\"|12\n|\n*UK: Silver<ref name=\"BritCertified\">{{cite web|title=Brit Certified|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/|website=bpi.co.uk|accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"[[Everlong]]\" \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|36\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|\n*IT: Platinum<ref>[https://www.fimi.it/top-of-the-music/certificazioni/certificazioni.kl#/certifications Certificazioni] fimi.it. Retrieved June 26, 2017.</ref> \n*US: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\" />\n*UK: Platinum<ref name=\"BritCertified\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"|1998\n|\"[[My Hero (song)|My Hero]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|59\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|74\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|53\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|\n*AUS: Gold<ref name=\"AustralianSingles2014\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-singles-2014.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles] aria.com.au. Retrieved December 13, 2014.</ref>\n*UK: Silver<ref name=\"BritCertified\"/>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Foo Fighters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colour And The Shape, The}}\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Gil Norton]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records albums]]\n[[Category:Foo Fighters albums]]\n[[Category:Grunge albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Bear Creek Studio]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Colour and the Shape\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Foo Fighters]]\n| cover      = FooFighters-TheColourAndTheShape.jpg\n| alt        = A blue background with grey shape. The words \"Foo Fighters\" appear in red.\n| released   = {{Start date|1997|5|20}}\n| recorded   = November 1996 \u2013 February 1997\n| studio     = {{ubl|Bear Creek ([[Woodinville, Washington|Woodinville, WA]])|WGNS (Washington, D.C.)|Grandmaster Recorders (Hollywood, CA)}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[post-grunge]]|{{nowrap|[[hard rock]]}}|[[grunge]]}}\n| length     = 46:47\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Roswell Records|Roswell]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| producer   = [[Gil Norton]]\n| prev_title = [[Foo Fighters (album)|Foo Fighters]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[There Is Nothing Left to Lose]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Colour and the Shape\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\n | single1date = April 28, 1997\n | single2     = [[Everlong]]\n | single2date = August 18, 1997\n | single3     = [[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\n | single3date = January 19, 1998\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Colour and the Shape''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Foo Fighters]], released on May 20, 1997, by Roswell and [[Capitol Records]]. It marked the official debut of the Foo Fighters as a band, as their [[Foo Fighters (album)|eponymous 1995 debut album]] was primarily recorded by frontman [[Dave Grohl]] and producer Barrett Jones as a [[demo (music)|demo]]. After the debut became an international success, Grohl recruited guitarist [[Pat Smear]], bassist [[Nate Mendel]], and drummer [[William Goldsmith]] to form the band's full lineup. The group convened in the fall of 1996 for pre-production on a second album, and brought in [[Gil Norton]] as producer to establish a [[pop music|pop]] sensibility for the tracks. The band strived to create a full-fledged rock record, contrary to music press predictions that it would be another [[grunge]] offshoot.\n\nPrimarily inspired by Grohl's divorce from photographer Jennifer Youngblood in 1996, ''The Colour and the Shape'' is more lyrically introspective and musically developed than the Foo Fighters' debut. The album's track listing was designed to resemble a therapy session, splitting the album between uptempo tracks and ballads to reflect conflicting emotions. Early sessions at the Bear Creek studio in Washington went poorly and the band discarded most of those recordings. The band regrouped without Goldsmith in early 1997 to record at Hollywood's Grandmaster Recordings studio, with Grohl sitting in on drums instead. Goldsmith was offended and disgruntled that most of his material had been re-recorded, and he left the band shortly thereafter.\n\nThe singles \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\", \"[[Everlong]]\", and \"[[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\" peaked within the top ten of US rock radio charts, and the album charted at number ten on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. The album was also a commercial success on an international level, peaking at number three in the United Kingdom. Critics deemed the album a significant American rock release of its era, and in retrospective assessments it continues to be viewed as a seminal modern rock album. It was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] [[40th Grammy Awards|in 1998]] for [[Best Rock Album]]. ''The Colour and the Shape'' remains the Foo Fighters' biggest seller in the U.S., having sold more than two million copies according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]]. The album was [[remastered]] and reissued in 2007 with several bonus tracks for its tenth anniversary.\n\n==Background==\nThe album was the debut of Foo Fighters as a full band. On [[Foo Fighters (album)|the first album]] under the Foo Fighters name, frontman [[Dave Grohl]] had performed and recorded all of the parts by himself, with the exception of one guitar part played by [[Greg Dulli]]. The band's original lineup assembled for their exhaustive touring schedule throughout 1995 and 1996, during which the band became an international sensation on the strength of singles \"[[This Is a Call]]\", \"[[I'll Stick Around]]\", and \"[[Big Me]]\". Although the music press generally speculated the band's sophomore record would showcase [[grunge]]-inspired [[garage rock]], the band's intention was to make a more straightforward rock record.<ref name=\"access97\"/> The deal the band struck with [[Capitol Records]] afforded them a large degree of creative control over the band's true \"debut.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> The songs on the record were composed during [[soundcheck]]s during their extensive touring over the previous eighteen months.<ref name=story/> Mendel said \"the germ of every song is Dave's,\" with the frontman providing a riff and a basic song structure. The band would then [[jam session|jam]] and each member would contribute to some aspect of the song.<ref name=id>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14|title=Foo Fighters At Peace With Group Identity; Hollywood Won't Get Whalley|journal=Billboard|author=Newman, Melina|date=1997-05-17}}</ref>\n\nGrohl recruited producer [[Gil Norton]] to provide additional pop polish to the material. He especially wanted to hear guitar overdubs and harmonies with significant clarity.<ref name=\"access97\"/> Grohl said he admired Norton for his earlier work with the [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] and his ability to \"distill a coherent pop song out of all [the Pixies'] multi-layered weirdness.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\">{{cite AV media notes | title=The Colour and the Shape (Bonus Tracks) | year=2007 | others=[[Foo Fighters]] | type=liner notes | publisher=Roswell/RCA/Legacy | location=[[United States|US]] | id=88697 09183 2}}</ref> Norton was highly demanding of the band's performance, prompting bassist [[Nate Mendel]] to practice and improve his musical skill.<ref name=back/> Grohl said \"it was frustrating and it was hard and it was long, but at the end of the day you listened back to what you'd done and you understood why you had to do it one million times.\"<ref name=bill>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Capitol Stresses Group 'Shape' of the Foo Fighters|journal=Billboard|author=Newman, Melina|date=1997-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |salign=center|quote=While recording this record two marriages fell apart, we lost a drummer, someone nearly went to jail, and we discovered late in the day that record making is hellishly expensive and best done with a budget prepared beforehand.|source=\u2013 [[Nate Mendel]], May 2007<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>|align=right|width=25em}}\n''The Colour and the Shape'' was recorded over the period of two months, primarily at Grandmaster Recorders in Hollywood from January to February 1997.<ref name=\"access97\"/> The band spent two weeks in pre-production the previous autumn, rehearsing the tracks and changing arrangements.<ref name=\"access97\"/> Norton had his greatest impact during pre-production, during which he spent days with Grohl in his hotel room \"stripping the songs back to their absolute basics.\"<ref name=story>{{cite book|year=2006|title=The Dave Grohl Story|first=Jeff|last=Apter|publisher=Music Sales Group|ISBN=978-0-85712-021-2|page=304}}</ref> His role in production taught the band the importance of self-editing and gave them confidence to see \"the larger picture in a song.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> Afterward, the band set off for Bear Creek Studios in [[Woodinville, Washington]], where the first recording sessions for ''The Colour and the Shape'' began on November 18, 1996.<ref name=\"story\"/> Mendel described Bear Creek as \"a converted barn with a salmon stream running through it\".<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> The studio was located on a farm and, for the duration of these sessions, the band lived in a cabin adjacent to the studio.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\nGrohl, who described the sessions at Bear Creek as a \"bad experience,\" decided to scrap nearly all of the recorded tracks.<ref name=\"linernotes\"/><ref name=\"kerrang\"/> The band took a break for the holidays, during which Grohl returned to Virginia and wrote several new songs. He recorded two of these songs by himself at WGNS Studios in Washington, D.C.: \"[[Walking After You]]\" and an acoustic version of \"[[Everlong]]\".<ref name=dictionary>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040503202840/http://www.foofighters.com/archives/dictionary.php|url=http://www.foofighters.com/archives/dictionary.php|archivedate=2004-05-03|title=Foo Dictionary|publisher=The Official Foo Fighters Site|accessdate=2011-12-12}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1997, the band\u2014minus drummer [[William Goldsmith]]\u2014relocated to Hollywood's Grandmaster Recorders, which Mendel said was \"a small studio that sometimes moonlighted as a porn set, and looked the part.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/> For a period of four weeks, the band re-recorded most of the album with Grohl playing the drum tracks. Grohl's drumming started with only \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\", as Grohl and Norton felt the drums on that song needed more work, but by the end of the sessions recordings of Goldsmith's drumming remained on only two tracks, \"Doll\" and \"Up in Arms\".<ref name=apter306>Apter, 2006. p. 306</ref> According to Grohl, Goldsmith's drumming had good moments, but his performances mostly did not fit what Grohl had conceived for the drum track, so the frontman decided to redo them himself. Goldsmith even asked if he should go to Los Angeles, but Grohl declined and said he was only performing [[overdub]]s. Eventually, Mendel told Goldsmith the situation. Grohl said that he still wanted Goldsmith as a member of the band, despite replacing his tracks, but the disgruntled drummer decided to leave the Foo Fighters instead.<ref name=back/> Speaking in 2011 about the tension that surrounded the Goldsmith's departure, Grohl said, \"There were a lot of reasons it didn't work out [\u2026] but there was also a part of me that was like, you know, I don't know if I'm finished playing the drums yet. [\u2026] I wish that I would have handled things differently.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=RTE2fm |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WWhsYINKcKM#t=2m56s |title=Oxegen 2011 \u2013 Foo Fighters Dave Grohl |publisher=YouTube |date=2011-07-10 |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter the move to Los Angeles, the album's budget ballooned and deadlines became a more pressing concern.<ref name=\"vox\"/> Studio time was expensive and the group was pressured by Capitol to deliver the record in a timely fashion.<ref name=kerrang>{{cite journal| last =Peake| first =Mike| date =April 1997| title =Leader of the Gang| journal = [[Kerrang!]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher =[[Bauer Media Group]]| location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> However, the pressure never adversely affected the band members, whose main priorities were to make \"music for its own sake [\u2026] and let the commercial concerns take care of themselves.\"<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\nThe album's title came from the band's tour manager of the time, who would often spend afternoons rummaging thrift stores and purchasing strange memorabilia; on one occasion, he purchased a bowling pin with red and white stripes, remarking to the band he rather liked \"the colour and the shape\" of the object.<ref name=\"livewire97\">{{cite journal| last =Anders| first =Marcel| date =October 1997| title =Rock & Grohl| journal = Live Wire| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = | location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> The group found the phrase arbitrary and hilarious and decided to use it as the title, rather than trying to choose a title based on the music's themes or moods.<ref name=\"livewire97\"/> They chose the British spelling of \"''colour''\" with a \"U\" as a tribute to Norton, who is British.<ref>{{cite journal| last =Villeneuve| first =Nicole| date =March 28, 2011| title =Dave Grohl: Times Like These| journal = [[Exclaim!]]| url =http://exclaim.ca/music/article/dave_grohl-times_like_these | accessdate =May 14, 2019 }}</ref> A title track was written and recorded for ''The Colour and the Shape'' during the Bear Creek sessions, but like most of the other songs attempted there, it did not reach the album's final track list. Noted as \"rawer, noisier and thrashier\" than the rest of the songs on the album by ''[[Louder Sound]]''{{'}}s Paul Brannigan, it later became a b-side to the album's eventual lead single, \"Monkey Wrench\".<ref name=\"bsides-louder\">{{cite web |last1=Brannigan |first1=Paul |title=The 10 best Foo Fighters songs tucked away on b-sides |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-10-best-foo-fighters-songs-tucked-away-on-b-sides |website=[[Louder Sound]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703135057/https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-10-best-foo-fighters-songs-tucked-away-on-b-sides |archivedate=July 3, 2019 |date=December 22, 2018}}</ref> After settling on a track sequence, Grohl was struck by the impression that the album's flow from start to finish resembled a therapy session, moving from fear and anxiety at the start to self-assurance and resolve by the end.<ref name=\"vox\"/> He even considered placing a therapist's couch on the album cover.<ref name=\"vox\"/>\n\n==Composition==\nProfessional reviewers have characterized the musical genre of ''The Colour and the Shape'' as [[alternative rock]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|author-link=Douglas Wolk|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ywEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Best New Music: The Five Best Releases This Month \u2014 Foo Fighters / ''The Colour and the Shape'' / Rosewell\u2013Capitol |work=[[CMJ#CMJ New Music Monthly|CMJ New Music Monthly]]|issue=Special Summer Issue|date=July 1997|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> [[grunge]],<ref name=ew/> [[post-grunge]],<ref name=allmusic/> and [[hard rock]].<ref>{{cite web|last=DeGroot|first=Joey|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/7749/20140719/9-great-albums-that-open-with-very-brief-songs-foo-fighters-cat-stevens-and-more.htm|title=9 Great Albums That Open with Very Brief Songs: Foo Fighters, Cat Stevens, and More|work=Music Times|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Melody Maker]]'', Victoria Segal said the album was more cohesive than the debut and was unified by a theme of \"battered romanticism\".<ref name=mm /> More specifically, many of the lyrics address the dissolution of Grohl's marriage to Jennifer Youngblood during the winter of 1996, which Grohl said had been \"the winter of my discontent.\"<ref name=mm>{{cite journal| last =Segal| first =Victoria| date =April 1997| title =All's Well That Ends Roswell| journal = [[Melody Maker]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = [[IPC Media]]| location = | issn = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref> The album's track sequence reflects this sentiment, chronicling his change from chaos to newfound happiness.<ref name=vox>{{cite journal| last =Bailie| first =Stuart| date =June 1997| title =Happy Dave Is Here Again| journal = [[Vox (magazine)|Vox]]| volume = | issue = | page = | publisher = [[IPC Media]]| location = | issn = | url = https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Article/foo-fighters-happy-dave-is-here-again | via = [[Rock's Backpages]] | accessdate = }} {{subscription required}}</ref> Grohl admitted the lyrics of the previous album had been \"obscure\" and \"nonsense,\" but Norton challenged Grohl to write lyrics that were more meaningful and comprehensible.<ref name=\"mm\"/> Grohl delved deeper into his feelings with the lyrics and said \"there was a new freedom: 'Wow, I can actually write about things I feel strongly about and things that mean something to me and things I wouldn't normally say in everyday conversation.'\" The frontman stated that the experience was \"kind of liberating,\" comparing the album to going to a weekly visit to the therapist \"and then the rest of the week feel pretty good about everything.\" Grohl also found new strength in his singing, overcoming insecurities he had about his singing voice on the debut.<ref name=bill/> Three types of songs permeate the record: ballads, up-tempo tracks and combinations of the two. Grohl felt they were representative of the specific emotions he would feel after the divorce.<ref name=\"livewire97\" />\n\n===Track information===\nThe album's opener, \"Doll\", involves the fear of entering into situations unprepared.<ref name=\"vox\"/><ref name=\"fooarchive1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fooarchive.com/headwires/colourandtheshape.htm |title=The Colour and the Shape : Dave Grohl's Guide To Every Song |publisher=Fooarchive.com |accessdate=2011-11-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124163039/http://www.fooarchive.com/headwires/colourandtheshape.htm |archivedate=2011-11-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> Regarding \"Monkey Wrench\", Grohl stated that it was \"a song about realizing that you are the source of all of the problems in a relationship and you love the other person so much, you want to free them of the problem, which is actually yourself. It was a riff that turned into another riff that turned into another riff and ended up being a nice little power punk song.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> In another interview, Grohl stated his pride in the song: \"With Monkey Wrench I remember I had the main riff, but I didn't have the little jangly riff that goes over the top of it and I thought it needed something. So I came up with the jangly riff and thought 'Oh my God this is never gonna fly! Everyone's gonna hate it'. But I was really excited the first time I heard it on the radio\u2014it was in the middle of a load of mid-'90s grunge shit and I thought it was so killer.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fooarchive.com/gpb/100riffs.htm |title=KERRANG! \u2013 The Top 100 Riffs: No. 50 Monkey Wrench \u2013 October '09 |publisher=Fooarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> The song was released as the first single from the album in 1997.\n\nThe lyrics to \"Hey, Johnny Park!\" song follow a series of different themes (\"about 15 different things\", according to Grohl). Johnny Park is the name of one of Grohl's childhood friends; he noted, \"we were like brothers from the age of 5 to 12\" and that he named the song after Park in hopes that he might restore contact with him.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> \"My Poor Brain\" experiments with different [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]], both musically and lyrically in nature. Grohl likened the disparity in sounds to changes from [[Jackson Five]] to [[Black Sabbath]].<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> Grohl described the concept of \"Wind Up\" as about successful musicians who constantly complain about their lives to the press. He elaborated, \"It drives me insane when I hear musicians that don't understand how fortunate they are that they don't have to go and pump gas for twelve hours a day. They can sit on their couch and smoke pot, and complain to their friends that they hate it when someone comes up and says that he likes their band... there are two sides: there's the reluctant rock-star, and then there is the prying journalist that almost lives for the reluctant rock-star, it's just talking \"about the hand you've been dealt.\" Every time I hear about \"the hand you've been dealt,\" it drives me fucking nuts, spare me your confessions... I've had so many fucking bullshit jobs for the half of my life\u2014you know, working in furniture warehouses and planting trees, painting houses\u2014and it's a lot more fun to play music.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Rock & Grohl |url=http://www.fooarchive.com:80/features/livewire97.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090721002307/http://www.fooarchive.com/features/livewire97.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 July 2009 |magazine=Livewire |date=October 1997 |access-date=23 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nGrohl described \"Up in Arms\" as \"A typical love song. It's almost like a [[the Knack|Knack]] song, just a simple pop song.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> Also in the song, Dave changed the last line which is meant to sing \"always coming back I cannot forget you girl\" to \"always coming back I cannot forget you ''Gil''\" in reference to their producer [[Gil Norton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foofighterslive.com/recordinghistory/studio/1997-02-00.php |title=Recording History &#124; Studio &#124; February 1997 \u2013 Grand Master Recorders Ltd, Hollywood, CA |publisher=FooFightersLive.com |accessdate=2013-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021211637/http://www.foofighterslive.com/recordinghistory/studio/1997-02-00.php |archive-date=2013-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"My Hero\" criticizes idolatry and instead extolls friends who are ordinary heroes, which has been considered a statement on fame and partially inspired by former bandmate Kurt Cobain.<ref name=access97>{{cite magazine| date =1997| title =The Think Tank| magazine = [[Select (magazine)|Select]]}}</ref><ref name=\"vox\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Which Foo Fighters song is about Kurt Cobain? |url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/foo-fighters/which-foo-fighters-song-about-kurt-cobain/ |publisher=[[Radio X (United Kingdom)|Radio X UK]] |accessdate=May 9, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407062701/https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/foo-fighters/which-foo-fighters-song-about-kurt-cobain/ |archivedate=April 7, 2019 |date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> In Grohl's own words, the song is, \"(his) way of saying that when I was young, I didn't have big rock heroes, I didn't want to grow up and be some big sporting hero. My heroes were ordinary people and the people that I have a lot of respect for are just solid everyday people\u2014people you can rely on.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> This was the third single to be released from the album. \"See You\" was a song that, according to Grohl, only he liked out of the rest of the band. When Grohl entered the studio, he changed Goldsmith's original drum part to resemble [[Queen (band)|Queen]]'s \"[[Crazy Little Thing Called Love]]\" so the rest of the group would be satisfied with putting it on the record.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/>\n\n\"Enough Space\" is about ''[[Arizona Dream]]'', one of Grohl's favorite films.<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> He also said the song emerged from his desire to create a song that would be a good opener on their [[set lists]], with a tempo that mimicked the jumping and bouncing of European crowds in the beginning of sets.<ref name=back>{{cite AV media|author=[[James Moll|Moll, James]] (director)|title=[[Foo Fighters: Back and Forth]]|year=2011|medium=documentary|publisher=RCA}}</ref> The lyrics of \"February Stars\" are said to be about \"hanging on by the tips of your fingers and hoping you don't slip and fall.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> This song dates back to at least January 1994, when an early take of the song with alternate lyrics, titled \"Dave/Acoustic + Voc\" was recorded by Grohl and [[Krist Novoselic]] on [[Pump organ|Harmonium]] during [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s last recording session.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Gaar |first=Gillian G. |url=http://www.livenirvana.com/sessions/reading/mojo126.php |title=Nirvana: The Lost Tapes |magazine=[[Mojo (magazine)|MOJO]] |date=May 2004}}</ref> \"Everlong\" was written when the band took a break from recording after the initial sessions. Grohl reworked \"Everlong\" by himself at his home in Virginia.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Epstein |first1=Dan |title=Foo Fighters\u2019 \u2018The Colour and the Shape\u2019: 10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/foo-fighters-the-colour-and-the-shape-10-things-you-didnt-know-115404/|magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=20 May 2017}}</ref> It is considered to be one of the best songs by the band and is highly acclaimed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fooarchive.com/other/onfoo.htm |title=Foo Fighters  |publisher=Fooarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> Grohl was almost reduced to tears after performing the song at [[Neil Young]]'s [[Bridge School Benefit]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Scaggs |first1=Austin |title=Dave Grohl |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dave-grohl-203436/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=12 June 2003}}</ref> In 2000, [[David Letterman]] revealed that it is his favorite song.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=A Brief History of David Letterman\u2019s Love for the Foo Fighters |website=Slate |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=21 May 2015 |url= http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/05/21/a_brief_history_of_david_letterman_s_love_for_the_foo_fighters.html }}</ref>\n\n\"Walking After You\" was written and recorded by Grohl on his own in a studio in Washington. This version appears on the album. The band would later re-record the song with all the members for [[The X-Files: The Album|''The X-Files'' soundtrack]], and this version was released as a single.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Gillian Anderson Talks Dave Grohl\u2019s \u2018X-Files\u2019 Cameo |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/gillian-anderson-talks-dave-grohls-x-files-cameo-107963/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 September 2018 |date=22 February 2016}}</ref> Grohl stated that \"Walking After You\" was \"an emotional, sappy song about getting dumped.\"<ref name=\"fooarchive1\"/> On the record's closing track, \"New Way Home,\" Grohl longs for his hometown and recalls the drive there on Highway 99. Through this journey, \"I realise that it\u2019s OK, I can make my way through all of this, and I\u2019m not that freaked out at the end.\"<ref name=\"vox\"/>\n\n==Release==\n''The Colour and the Shape'' was released on May 20, 1997, preceded the month before by lead single \"[[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\". The promotional campaign emphasized the band's group identity as well as each band member's individual personality.<ref name=bill/> This strategy contrasted with the marketing approach for the prior album, which had centered Grohl at a time before Mendel and Smear felt comfortable being marketed as personalities.<ref name=bill/> Each member gave interviews with press discussing their interests, with guitarist [[Pat Smear]] talking to guitar and fashion magazines.<ref name=id/> Just as recording was finished and [[Taylor Hawkins]] was hired as the new drummer (he was the former touring drummer for [[Alanis Morissette]]'s ''[[Jagged Little Pill]]'' in 1995), Smear expressed his own plans to leave the band, claiming he was exhausted and not motivated to go through with another extended tour.<ref name=back/> This information was not yet highly publicized, and spokespeople for the band denied that the rumors of Smear's impending departure were true.<ref name=\"smear-mtv1\" /> The promotional tour started in May 1997.<ref name=bill/>\n\n\"Everlong\" was released as the album's second single in August 1997. It was the most commercially successful single from the record, being certified [[RIAA|double platinum]] in the United States and being one of only three Foo Fighters songs to reach that status.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Foo+Fighters#search_section|title=American certifications \u2013 Foo Fighters|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> Smear remained with the group until September 4, the night of the [[1997 MTV Video Music Awards]]. After playing \"Monkey Wrench\" during the \"pregame show\" to the event, Smear announced that it was the final song he would play with the band, introducing [[Franz Stahl]] as the band's new guitarist before the band began playing \"Everlong\" later that evening.<ref name=\"smear-mtv1\">{{cite web |author1=MTV staff |title=Pat Smear Leaves the Foo Fighters on Live MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1429056/pat-smear-leaves-the-foo-fighters-on-live-mtv/ |website=[[MTV]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703142734/http://www.mtv.com/news/1429056/pat-smear-leaves-the-foo-fighters-on-live-mtv/ |archivedate=July 3, 2019 |date=September 4, 1997}}</ref> \"My Hero\" was released as the third and final single from the album in 1998. All three singles peaked inside the top ten of the [[Alternative Songs]] and [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]] charts.<ref name=\"Alternativesongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/foo-fighters/chart-history/alternative-songs|title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Alternative Songs| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/foo-fighters/chart-history/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Foo Fighters \u2013 Mainstream Rock Songs chart history| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTo commemorate ''The Colour and the Shape''{{'}}s tenth anniversary, it was reissued on July 10, 2007, with six additional tracks: the B-sides \"Dear Lover\" and \"The Colour and the Shape\", plus covers of [[Killing Joke]]'s \"[[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\", [[Gary Numan]]'s \"[[Down in the Park]]\", [[Gerry Rafferty]]'s \"[[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\" and [[Vanity 6]]'s \"[[Vanity 6 (album)|Drive Me Wild]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1052002/foo-fighters-expand-second-album-for-reissue|title=Foo Fighters Expand Second Album For Reissue|date=May 21, 2007|author=Cohen, Jonathan|accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-colour-and-the-shape-mw0000088006|title=The Colour and the Shape \u2013 Foo Fighters|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|title=Back Catalogue: Nirvana|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=68|date=April 2008|pages=88\u201389}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kim|first=Jae-Ha|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4390319.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118100104/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4390319.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 18, 2018|title='The Colour and the Shape', Foo Fighters, Capitol Records|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=May 20, 1997|accessdate=November 18, 2015|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite journal|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1997/05/23/colour-and-shape|title=The Colour and the Shape|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 23, 1997|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Scribner|first=Sara|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1997-05-18/entertainment/ca-59862_1_album-review|title=Foo Fighters, 'The Colour and the Shape,' Roswell/Capitol|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 18, 1997|accessdate=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|last=McMahon|first=James|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-foo-fighters-8844|title=Foo Fighters: The Colour And The Shape|work=[[NME]]|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=November 18, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701215730/http://www.nme.com/reviews/foo-fighters/8844|archivedate=July 1, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=Christina|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-colour-and-the-shape-19970529|title=The Colour And The Shape|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 29, 1997|accessdate=November 22, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Wolk\">{{cite book|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|chapter=Foo Fighters|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/306 306\u201307]|editor1-first=Nathan|editor1-last=Brackett|editor2-first=Christian|editor2-last=Hoard|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|edition=4th|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=2004|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9eocwUfoSoC&pg=PA306#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hopper|first=Jessica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JLoecqYeotYC&pg=PA113#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Spins|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=13|issue=4|date=July 1997|accessdate=January 7, 2015|page=113}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv797-97.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|date=July 22, 1997|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nCritical response to the record was generally positive. Victoria Segal at the UK-based ''[[Melody Maker]]'' viewed ''The Colour and the Shape'' as a significant American rock release, writing that it was \"a great rock album at a time when great rock albums are viewed with increasing suspicion.\"<ref name=mm/> Segal's review described the album as leagues ahead of other post-grunge acts: \"The first album might have been a collection of loveable songs, but lacked the sheer visceral attack that thrills this time round,\" Segal wrote, calling it \"[a]n attack that would have{{nbsp}}[\u2026] almost any other US rock band biting their nails in anguish and embarrassment.\"<ref name=mm/>\n\nChristina Kelly of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' was largely positive, although she singled out Norton's production as distracting: \"''Colour'' has a big, radio-ready, modern-rock sound. Some might even call the album overproduced: On the ballads, the vocals are overprocessed and fake sounding.\"<ref name=RS/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised the band's growth, but criticized the sound, which journalist [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] described as \"like much current alt-rock: been there, grunged that.\"<ref name=ew/> In contrast, Stephen Thomas Erlewine of [[AllMusic]] described that production as revolutionary: \"everything here wound up defining the sound of [[post-grunge]] modern rock, and it remains as perhaps the best example of its kind.\"<ref name=allmusic/> In his review for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] said the music was routine but elevated by Grohl's \"marital breakup content/concept,\" which allowed him to \"fully inhabit the music that meant so much to him and millions of other Kurt Cobain fans.\"<ref name=\"Christgau\"/> Ryan Schreiber of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' was less favorable, rating the album 3.4 out of 10 and calling the music \"sorely dated.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schreiber|first1=Ryan|title=Foo Fighters: The Colour & The Shape: Pitchfork Review|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/f/foo-fighters/colour-and-the-shape.shtml|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=21 March 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030219043918/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/f/foo-fighters/colour-and-the-shape.shtml|archivedate=19 February 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFour years after Schreiber's 2003 review, ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s Stuart Berman gave the tenth anniversary re-release a mildly more favorable review. Scoring the release a 5.8 out of 10, he stated, \"''The Colour and the Shape'' presented a true picture of the kind of group Grohl wanted to be in, had he not been sidetracked by the job of drumming for the biggest American rock band of the early 1990s [...] that band would turn out to be much more formulaically mall-punk than the Foos' torn 'n' frayed debut suggested.\"<ref name=\"berman\">{{cite web |last1=Berman |first1=Stuart |title=The Colour and the Shape [10th Anniversary Special Edition] |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10473-the-colour-and-the-shape-10th-anniversary-special-edition/ |website=[[Pitchfork (magazine)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530214709/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10473-the-colour-and-the-shape-10th-anniversary-special-edition// |archivedate=May 30, 2019 |date=August 1, 2007}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewed the re-release with the opposite opinion, citing the self titled record's single \"I'll Stick Around\" as an example of \"Grohl's strikingly non-aggressive (read: bland) vocal style\" from the 1995 album; he then described \"Monkey Wrench\" as proof that Grohl \"knew how to rock out\" by comparison.<ref name=\"popmatters-2007\">{{cite web |last1=Schiller |first1=Mike |title=Foo Fighters: The Colour and the Shape |url=https://www.popmatters.com/foo-fighters-the-colour-and-the-shape-2496216428.html |website=[[PopMatters]] |accessdate=July 3, 2019|date=August 22, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Commercial performance===\n''The Colour and the Shape'' peaked at number 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], up from a peak of 23 for the 1995 self-titled debut.<ref name=\"US-albums\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=foo fighters|chart=Billboard 200}} | title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History: Billboard 200 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> It also managed to reach the top ten in Australia,<ref name=\"AUS-albums\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=australian-charts.com|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Canada,<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=foo fighters|chart=Canadian Albums}} | title=Foo Fighters Album & Song Chart History: Canadian Albums | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Greece,<ref name=\"IFPI-ireland\" /> Ireland,<ref name=\"IFPI-ireland\" /> New Zealand,<ref name=\"NZ\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=charts.nz|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Sweden,<ref name=\"SWE\">{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Foo+Fighters|title=Discography Foo Fighters|publisher=Hung Medien|work=swedishcharts.com|accessdate=September 4, 2012}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"UK-albums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/27860/foo-fighters/|title=Foo Fighters|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}</ref> The album has also been certified Platinum in the United States,<ref name=\"RIAA\" /> Australia,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}</ref> Canada,<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://musiccanada.com/gold-platinum/?fwp_gp_search=Foo%20Fighters|title=Gold/Platinum|publisher=[[Music Canada]]|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/ |title=Certified Awards Search|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=February 3, 2013|format=enter the search parameter \"Foo Fighters\" into the ''Search'' box, then select \"artist\" in the ''Search by'' box, then select \"Exact match\".}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Dave Grohl]], [[Nate Mendel]] and [[Pat Smear]] except where noted\n| title1 = Doll\n| writer1 = \n| length1 = 1:23\n| title2 = [[Monkey Wrench (song)|Monkey Wrench]]\n| length2 = 3:51\n| title3 = Hey, Johnny Park!\n| length3 = 4:08\n| title4 = My Poor Brain\n| length4 = 3:33\n| title5 = Wind Up\n| length5 = 2:32\n| title6 = Up in Arms\n| length6 = 2:15\n| title7 = [[My Hero (Foo Fighters song)|My Hero]]\n| length7 = 4:20\n| title8 = See You\n| length8 = 2:26\n| title9 = Enough Space\n| note9 = Grohl\n| length9 = 2:37\n| title10 = February Stars\n| length10 = 4:49\n| title11 = [[Everlong]]\n| note11 = Grohl\n| length11 = 4:10\n| title12 = [[Walking After You]]\n| note12 = Grohl\n| length12 = 5:03\n| title13 = New Way Home\n| length13 = 5:40\n|total_length = 46:47\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Original single\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Australian tour pack (Grey cover)\n| title1 = [[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\n| extra1 = \"Everlong\" (CD2)\n| note1 = [[Killing Joke]] cover\n| length1 = 3:34\n| title2 = Drive Me Wild\n| extra2 = \"Everlong\" (CD1) and \"My Hero\" (Japanese edition)\n| note2 = [[Vanity 6]] cover\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = [[Down in the Park]]\n| extra3 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD2), \"Everlong\" (Australian limited edition) and \"My Hero\" (Japanese edition)\n| note3 = Gary Numan and Tubeway Army cover\n| length3 = 4:07\n| title4 = [[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\n| extra4 = \"My Hero\" (UK & Japanese editions), \"Next Year\" (CD2)\n| note4 = [[Gerry Rafferty]] cover\n| length4 = 5:40\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = French limited edition ''In\u00e9dits'' bonus disc\n| title1 = The Colour and the Shape\n| length1 = 3:23\n| title2 = Weenie Beenie\n| note2 = live at the [[\u00cele de R\u00e9]]) (Grohl\n| length2 = 3:18\n| title3 = Winnebago\n| note3 = live at the \u00cele de R\u00e9) (Grohl\n| length3 = 3:06\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Original single\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Limited edition European bonus EP\n| title1 = [[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\n| extra1 = \"Everlong\" (CD2)\n| writer1 = [[Jaz Coleman]]\n| note1 = [[Killing Joke]] cover\n| length1 = 3:33\n| title2 = [[Vanity 6 (album)|Drive Me Wild]]\n| extra2 = \"Everlong\" (CD1) and \"My Hero\" (Japanese edition)\n| writer2 = [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]\n| note2 = [[Vanity 6]] cover\n| length2 = 3:14\n| title3 = [[Down in the Park]]\n| extra3 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD2), \"Everlong\" (Australian limited edition) and \"My Hero\" (Japanese edition)\n| writer3 = [[Gary Numan]]\n| note3 = [[Gary Numan]] cover\n| length3 = 4:09\n| title4 = [[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\n| extra4 = \"My Hero\" (UK & Japanese editions), \"Next Year\" (CD2)\n| writer4 = [[Gerry Rafferty]]\n| note4 = [[Gerry Rafferty]] cover\n| length4 = 5:37\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Japanese release bonus track\n| title14 = Dear Lover \n| length14 = 4:32\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Original single\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = US / iTunes bonus track\n| title14 = The Colour and the Shape\n| extra14 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD1)\n| length14 = 3:21\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Original single\n| collapsed = yes\n|total_length = 71:13\n| headline = B-sides released as bonus tracks on 10th anniversary edition\n| title14 = [[Requiem (Killing Joke song)|Requiem]]\n| note14 = [[Killing Joke]] cover\n| extra14 = \"Everlong\" (CD2)\n| length14 = 3:33\n| title15 = Drive Me Wild\n| note15 = [[Vanity 6]] cover\n| extra15 = \"Everlong\" (CD1)\n| length15 = 3:13\n| title16 = [[Down in the Park]]\n| note16 = Gary Numan and Tubeway Army cover\n| extra16 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD2)\n| length16 = 4:08\n| title17 = [[Baker Street (song)|Baker Street]]\n| note17 = Gerry Rafferty cover\n| extra17 = \"My Hero\"\n| length17 = 5:37\n| title18 = Dear Lover\n| extra18 = \"My Hero\" (UK & Japanese editions), \"Next Year\" (CD2)\n| length18 = 4:32\n| title19 = The Colour and the Shape\n| extra19 = \"Monkey Wrench\" (CD1)\n| length19 = 3:23\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Foo Fighters===\n*[[Dave Grohl]] \u2013 lead vocals, guitar, drums\n*[[Pat Smear]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[Nate Mendel]] \u2013 [[electric bass|bass]]\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*[[William Goldsmith]] \u2013 drums on \"Doll\", \"Up in Arms\" (credited for slow intro), \"My Poor Brain\" (verses only, uncredited), \"The Colour and the Shape\" (uncredited), and \"Down in the Park\" (uncredited)\n*[[Taylor Hawkins]] \u2013 drums on  \"Requiem\", \"Drive Me Wild\", and \"Baker Street\" (10th anniversary edition's bonus tracks only)\n*[[Lance Bangs]], Chris Bilheimer and Ryan Boesch \u2013 handclaps on \"See You\"\n*[[Louise Post]] - backing vocals on \"[[Everlong]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Warren Huart|title=Foo Fighters Everlong|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1LDGYI2oaVI|work=Inside the song|publisher=Produce Like A Pro|date=17 July 2015|via=YouTube}}</ref> (uncredited)\n\n===Production===\n*[[Gil Norton]] \u2013 production\n*Bradley Cook, Geoff Turner \u2013 engineering\n*Ryan Boesch, Todd Burke, Don Farwell, [[Ryan Hadlock]], Jason Mauza \u2013 assistant engineering\n*[[Chris Sheldon]] \u2013 mixing\n*[[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013 mastering\n*Bradley Cook, Geoff Turner \u2013 recording technicians\n*Jeffery Fey, Foo Fighters, Tommy Steele \u2013 art direction\n*Jeffery Fey, George Mimnaugh \u2013 design\n*Andy Engel \u2013 logo design\n*Josh Kessler \u2013 photography\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (1997)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{Album chart|Australia|5|artist=Foo Fighters|album=The Colour and the Shape|accessdate=26 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{Album chart|Austria|19|artist=Foo Fighters|album=The Colour and th